<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 0017EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-TradeConference     06-02 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trade Conference,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ministers Reject Protectionism in Swipe at Washington</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY DUNPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A conference of 24 nations on Thursday rejected
protectionist trade policies in an implicit condemnation of the
United States.
   Officials of nations belonging to the Organization for Economic
Cooperation and Development declared their determination to
dismantle trade barriers erected by individual nations in favor of
a stronger international trading system.
   In a communique issued at the end of the annual meeting, the
members said they would continue to fight inflation, cut
unemployment, and improve protection of the environment.
   The meeting, which brought together ministers of economy,
finance, and trade from member countries, provided one barometer of
the main issues that may come up at the annual economic summit of
the seven industrialized democracies, to be held in Paris on July
14-16.
   The most talked about issue at the meeting ending Thursday was
trade, with many countries voicing concern about a U.S. move last
week singling out Japan, India and Brazil as unfair trading
partners.
   Under U.S. trade law, Washington can now take retaliatory
actions in 12 or 18 months if the countries do not remove the
restrictions they are accused of imposing.
   At the trade meeting, Japan vigorously attacked the U.S. measure
and won support from some European nations and Canada in getting
strong language on free trade into the final communique.
   In their final statement Thursday, the ministers said they
wanted to ``express their determination to halt and reverse all
such protectionist tendencies ... and avoid any discriminatory or
autonomous actions.''
   Despite the implied criticism of Washington, U.S Treasury
Secretary Nicholas Brady put a positive face on the meeting. He
insisted ``there was basic agreement on fundamental issues.''
   U.S. Trade Representative Carla A. Hills said the Bush
Administration remained committed to joint trade practices.
   She noted U.S. law does not require retaliation against
purported offenders but did not rule out such action.
   In recommendations for specific countries, the final communique
also said priorities for the United States should remain ``to
contain inflationary pressures'' and cut the federal budget deficit.
   Industrial nations formed the Organization for Economic
Cooperation and Development to foster international economic growth
and cooperation.
</TEXT>
