<DOCNO> AP890602-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 0153EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-InterestRates     06-02 0747</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Interest Rates,0766</SECOND>
<HEAD>Falling Interest Rates Spell Good News for Homebuyers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report; also on financial wire.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   If you're looking to buy a new home, the decline in interest
rates over the past few weeks could open a few doors.
   Economists say an improved inflation outlook and stronger dollar
have helped reverse a stubborn upward trend in rates that began two
years ago and has sent the once-vibrant housing industry into a
slump.
   ``Many people out there who wouldn't be able to buy a home can
now qualify at the lower rates,'' Richard W. Peach, deputy chief
economist of the Mortgage Bankers Association of America, said
Thursday.
   At the same time, rates on some certificates of deposit have
fallen, while changes in other types of consumer interest charges
such as bank auto loans and credit cards have been mixed.
   Many experts predict interest rates will continue easing the
rest of the year as the U.S. economy slows and as foreigners,
attracted by a firm dollar, pump money into U.S. financial
investments. Some predict fixed-rate mortgages could drop to 10
percent before the end of the year.
   Fixed-rate loans have dropped most steeply over the last two
months, dropping below 11 percent in tandem with declining
long-term rates in the credit markets.
   But adjustable rate mortages, which are tied to an index of
one-year Treasury notes, have shown only a slight drop, because
short-term rates remain comparably high. That stems from the
Federal Reserve's decision to keep a tigher rein on credit to fight
inflation.
   The average rate on the first year of an ARM was 9.18 percent
the last week in May, down from 9.28 percent the previous week,
according to the latest bank survey of the Federal Home Loan
Mortgage Corp. The rate averaged 9.40 percent in April.
   Freddie Mac said the average rate on fixed 30-year mortgages
fell to a five-month low of 10.5 percent the last week in May, down
from 10.69 percent the week before. Just two months ago, that same
loan averaged 11.22 percent, a nearly four-year high, and in May
1988 it averaged 10.46 percent, it said.
   The decline of nearly three-quarters of a percentage point in
30-year, fixed-rate mortgages over the past two months could mean
significant savings in comparing monthly mortgage payments.
   Homebuyers, for example, who got a $100,000 conventional loan at
the 11.22 percent rate are paying $972 a month in interest and
principal. Those who took out a mortgage last week at 10.5 percent
pay $915, or $684 less a year, for a 6 percent difference.
   That could mean the difference between qualifying for a mortgage
and having to put home-buying plans on hold, for some. The rule of
thumb is that monthly mortgage payments not exceed 25 percent of
net household income.
   ``For every half percentage point (increase or decrease),
another half a million people get in the housing market or out of
the housing market,'' said Ronnie J. Wynn, president of Montgomery,
Ala.-based Colonial Mortgage Co., one of the nation's largest
mortgage companies.
   Wynn said business is brisker these days as people rush to
exploit the break in rates. Loan applications are running about 20
percent higher than a year ago, compared with a 10 percent drop in
applications during April, he said.
   Stephen Ashley, president of the Rochester, N.Y.-based mortgage
banker Sibley Corp., said his business was slower than last year
but he expects it to pick up this summer.
   ``I think that the drop in rates has been positive in terms of
bringing a greater number of homebuyers into the market ... (But) I
don't want to represent it as being a land rush,'' he said.
   While fixed-rate mortgages have come down significantly, other
consumer interest charges haven't.
   A 48-month bank loan for a new car averages 12.56 percent, up
from 12.54 percent a month ago and 11.73 percent at the beginning
of the year, according to the North Palm Beach, Fla., publication
Bank Rate Monitor.
   Bank credit cards average 18.13 percent, up from 18.09 percent a
month ago and 18.03 percent earlier this year, Bank Rate Monitor
reported.
   For savers, rate changes have been mixed. The yield on a
one-year certificate of deposit has an average yield of 9.28
percent, down from 9.51 percent a month ago, according to the
publication.
   Money market accounts yielded an average 6.62 percent in the
week ended Wednesday, unchanged from the previous month, it said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
