<DOCNO> AP890602-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 0051EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Salvador-Post-Duarte     06-02 0938</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador-Post-Duarte,0967</SECOND>
<HEAD>Terminally Ill, Duarte Lives for Presidential Succession</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exhausted by cancer, calamity
and revolution, President Jose Napoleon Duarte has completed what
may be his greatest victory _ peacefully turning his government
over to an elected successor.
   He yielded power Thursday to Alfredo Cristiani, the new
president who represents Duarte's nemesis on the right wing.
   Duarte's closest political adviser, commenting on condition his
name not be used, said that with the president's ebbing strength,
Duarte is given to reflecting on his crusade for democracy in El
Salvador.
   ``He feels ambivalent, because he began by taking power away
from the oligarchy and now it may seem he's handing it back,'' the
adviser told The Associated Press.
   ``He is aware of the irony in the fact that handing power to the
most disagreeable political opposition will consolidate the
democratic process he has dedicated his life to building.''
   The adviser, an old friend and fellow founder of the Christian
Democratic Party, sees Duarte almost daily.
   He described how Duarte has had to lie in an oxygen tent, wasted
by dehydrating vomiting and diarrhea. Like the ulcers in Duarte's
mouth, they are brought on by chemotherapy.
   The 63-year-old engineer-turned-politician is likely to be
remembered as crucial to a gradual and difficult replacement of an
authoritarian, semifeudal system of government with an incipient
democracy.
   But he approached the end of his term and his life burdened by
failures and compromises that will weigh heavily as history
deliberates its verdict.
   Duarte has terminal liver cancer. Since it was diagnosed in June
1988, he has made periodic trips to Walter Reed Army Medical Center
in Washington for treatment, which leaves him bedridden.
   His doctor, Jose Luis Saca, told the AP the latest round of
chemotherapy was particularly devastating. Duarte is given little
to no chance of reaching his 64th birthday, in November.
   Duarte considers himself to a great degree personally
responsible for conditions permitting the unprecedented succession,
and sees it as a crowning achievement.
   But he also considers Cristiani's Republican Nationalist
Alliance, or Arena, an authoritarian, antidemocratic party inclined
to erode gains in human rights and civil liberties.
   ``One must acknowledge President Duarte's democratic vocation,''
said Cristiani in an interview with foreign correspondents before
taking office. ``He has, with his aptitudes and positions, promoted
democracy. But I wouldn't go so far as to call him the father of
Salvadoran democracy.''
   A summation of Duarte's five-year term includes notable
expansion of freedom of expression, drastic reduction in
politically motivated murders, labor union pluralism and three
nationwide elections judged free and fair by international
observers.
   But his two main objectives _ ending civil war and reviving a
moribund economy _ remained as far from fulfillment as when he took
office.
   Marxist-led guerrillas have been waging a revolution against the
U.S.-backed government for nine years. Despite more than $3.5
billion in economic and military aid from Washington, the rebels
continue to dominate territory in the north and east.
   Though the 7,000 insurgents are outnumbered eight-to-one by
security forces, they have demonstrated the capacity to attack
major garrisons and keep the army on the defensive in much of the
Massachusetts-sized country.
   The economy is a shambles. El Salvador would be virtually
bankrupt without international help. Production of the major export
crops _ coffee, sugar and cotton _ has declined sharply along with
private investment and the standard of living.
   Health care, potable water and primary education are little more
than dreams for most of the rural population. Corruption and
nepotism within Duarte's administration are widespread.
   The judiciary is all but completely ineffective. Though death
squad activity has declined, politically motivated assassins
continue to murder with impunity.
   Duarte, aware of the gravity of his disease, offered in last
year's state-of-the-republic address a balance sheet on his
presidency.
   ``The will of my people has caused me to navigate seas each day
more stormy and more dangerous because of cross-currents. The
absence of fair winds and persistent adversity all along the route
have joined to prevent us from bringing about our high aims,'' he
said.
   A high-ranking U.S. diplomat, who has been in El Salvador for
most of Duarte's term, remarked, ``He didn't work miracles, so he
has taken a lot of knocks, some fair and some not. He was not a
great administrator. He merged the party and the government and
surrounded himself with some unscrupulous people. But he must be
credited with instituting the democratic system itself. His great
legacy is this transition. The rest pales by comparison.''
   Ignacio Ellacuria, a Roman Catholic priest who is rector of the
prestigious Central American University, said Duarte ``never
realized what little real power he had. He's not a false man, but
he is a man who is self-deceived. His hands were completely tied by
the United States and the armed forces.
   ``Obviously, he has governed amid much danger and difficulty.
The FMLN was against him, private enterprise was against him, the
media were against him, Arena was against him. So he had to take
refuge in the armed forces and the United States,'' said Ellacuria.
   The FMLN are the Spanish initials for the rebel Farabundo Marti
National Liberation Front.
   Ellacuria harshly criticized Duarte for presiding over a junta
in 1981-82, the years of most ferocious repression during which
death squads and the military were blamed for abducting and
murdering up to 700 suspected leftists each month.
   ``Duarte accepted thousands of murders with the facile argument
that, if he were not there (on the junta), there would be more.
That is a measure of this man's ambition for power.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
