<DOCNO> AP890602-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 0222EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-CatastrophicCoverage     06-02 0660</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Catastrophic Coverage,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Fights to Preserve Surtax on Elderly</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is urging Congress to
think twice before cutting taxes that finance a catastrophic
illness insurance program for millions of older Americans.
   Until government can get a better estimate of how much the
surtax will bring in and how much catastrophic coverage will cost,
``Treasury would not consider it prudent to alter the premium,''
assistant treasury secretary John G. Wilkins told the Senate
Finance Committee on Thursday.
   The panel and the House Ways and Means Committee are considering
several bills to repeal or delay the surtax, which was enacted less
than a year ago. The new law is under heavy fire from many older
Americans.
   Many say they do not need the coverage because they have private
insurance. Others complain they cannot afford the surtax, which
this year is 15 percent of a Medicare beneficiary's federal income
tax of $150 or more. About 40 percent of older people pay the
surtax; the maximum tax is $800 per beneficiary.
   Unless Congress makes some changes, cautioned Rep. Harris
Fawell, R-Ill., ``there is going to be a popular revolt the likes
of which haven't been seen since'' a massive mail campaign led to
repeal of withholding of taxes from interest and dividends in 1983.
   Efforts to change the catastrophic law gained momentum recently
when Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, chairman of the Finance
Committee, disclosed government forecasts that the new tax will
bring in more than had been estimated just a year ago. He raised
the possibility of cutting the tax.
   During the five years ending in 1993, the Congressional Budget
Office now estimates, the surtax is likely to bring in about $10
billion more than is expected to be spent for catastrophic benefits.
   However, administration officials cautioned that the surplus may
never exist, because the new program of catastrophic drug benefits
starting in 1991 could cost far more than previously estimated.
   ``We cannot recommend a reduction in premium (surtax) revenue at
this time, knowing that the drug benefit faces financial difficulty
in the near future,'' said Louis W. Sullivan, secretary of health
and human services.
   The committee got lots of advice to the contrary from members of
Congress and from organizations representing older Americans.
   ``The seniors of America are angry, are growing more angry
daily, and their numbers are growing as new questions about this
act materialize,'' said Daniel L. Hawley of Las Vegas, president of
Seniors Coalition Against Catastrophic Act. ``If this act is not
repealed, beginning in 1990 there will be the largest turnover in
Congress in its history.''
   Lovola Burgess of Albuquerque, vice president of the American
Association of Retired Persons, said that organization _ the
largest representing seniors _ would prefer another financing
method but believes the benefits are important enough to justify a
less-than-perfect tax.
   But if Congress changes the tax, she said, it should do so by
reducing the surtax rate below its 15 percent level. Using
Congressional Budget Office estimates of the projected surplus, she
said the rate could be cut to 10.5 percent this year; the 28
percent level scheduled for 1993 could be cut to 19.6 percent.
   ``This option affects the largest number of beneficiaries...
from those paying the least, to those paying the most,'' Ms.
Burgess said. Although it would not reduce the number of people
paying the surtax, it would cut the number paying the maximum
amount.
   ``Over 20,000 Arizonans have contacted me since passage of the
final act,'' Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., told the committee. ``Not
more than 10 have indicated their support.''
   Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., sponsor of a bill to require
upper-income Americans of all ages to pay for the program, said the
the elderly are unwilling to pay the surtax.
   ``They don't understand ... why they are the only group in our
society which is being asked to subsidize another part of their
group,'' Levin said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890602-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 0225EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-S&amp;Ls     06-02 0732</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;Ls,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>S&amp;L Bill Could Go to House Floor Next Week</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Republicans who oppose President Bush's
effort to make savings and loan banks put more of their own money
at risk will have another chance to fight that provision of the $50
billion industry bailout bill.
   As Majority Leader Thomas Foley, D-Wash., moved Thursday to
speed the bill to the House floor for action next week, lobbyists
said three House Republicans were planning to fight its capital
requirements.
   The bill would make some 500 cash-poor savings and loan banks
come up with $13 billion in new capital by 1995.
   Foley told Rep. Joe Moakley, D-Mass., acting chairman of the
House Rules Committee, that he wants the panel to act on the
legislation next Tuesday so that the full House can begin
considering it next Wednesday.
   But lobbyists said Rep. Jimmy Quillen of Tennessee, ranking
Republican on the Rules Committee, was working with Reps. Thomas
Ridge, R-Pa., and Henry Hyde, R-Ill., on spearheading a movement to
thwart Bush's plan for making S&amp;L owners put up more of their own
money.
   Ridge tried unsuccessfully to defeat the new capital
requirements in the House Banking Committee. And Hyde last week
failed on a 17-17 tie vote in the House Judiciary Committee to
delay the new capital requirements for 18 months.
   As approved by the banking committee, the bill would make
cash-poor S&amp;Ls either raise new capital to act as a buffer between
future loan losses and federal deposit insurance funds, or require
the institutions to shrink in size.
   Under current regulations, S&amp;Ls can operate without their owners
having any of their own money at risk. Bush and others have blamed
that lax standard for the magnitude of the current crisis, which
has created an estimated $35 billion to $55 billion hole in the
government's deposit insurance fund.
   The House bill would require S&amp;L owners to put at least $1.50 of
their own money at risk by June 1990 for each $100 of federally
insured deposits they loan out. By 1995, that capital requirement
would climb to $3 for every $100 in loans.
   Meanwhile, another House committee on Thursday rejected as
``voodoo accounting'' Bush's plan to prevent the $50 billion that
the government will borrow for the bailout from swelling the
federal deficit.
   On a 22-15 party-line vote with only one Democrat supporting
Bush's plan, the House Government Operations Committee approved
including the immediate $50 billion taxpayer share of the bailout
as part of the federal budgets for this year and fiscal 1990 and
1991.
   The House Ways and Means Committee took a similar posture
earlier as the S&amp;L measure wound its way through several House
committees with shared jurisdiction over parts of the complicated
legislation.
   The Senate has already passed its version, with Democrats
falling 12 votes short of defeating Bush's financing mechanism,
which would raise the deficit by only $4.5 billion over the three
years but cost taxpayers a like amount in higher interest charges.
   Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich., the Government 0perations
Committee's chairman, said Bush's approach creates ``a windfall for
Wall Street in which wealthy purchasers of the bonds benefit at the
expense of taxpayers.''
   Borrowing from the term ``voodoo economics'' Bush once used to
describe President Reagan's theory that lower taxes would reduce
the deficit, Conyers called the administration's S&amp;L plan ``voodoo
accounting designed only to hide the true costs of the bailout from
the American people.''
   The only Democrat on the committee to vote in favor of Bush's
financing plan was Rep. Doug Barnard of Georgia, a former banker.
   Assistant Treasury Secretary David Mullins accused Democrats of
using the S&amp;L crisis ``in a back-door way'' to fight the
no-new-taxes agreement between Bush and Congress to reduce the 1990
fiscal budget deficit to $100 billion.
   ``This has nothing to do with S&amp;Ls,'' he said. ``The questions
is whether we maintain in a new administration the budgeting
discipline of Gramm-Rudman. The real issue is creating a waiver
process for new spending.''
   Including interest costs on the borrowing, the bailout will cost
an estimated $285 billion to $330 billion over the next 30 years,
making it the largest in the nation's history.
   The General Accounting Office estimates that at least 70 percent
of that money _ or approximately $1,000 for every man, woman and
child in the country _ will come from taxpayers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
