<FIRST>u a AM-S&amp;LIndictment     06-02 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;L Indictment,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former President of Dallas S&amp;L Charged In Fraud Investigation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of a savings and loan and several of
the company's senior officers were charged Thursday with
misapplying funds to make campaign contributions to members of
Congress.
   A federal grand jury here returned a 33-count indictment
charging Patrick G. King, former president of Vernon Savings and
Loan Association, with conspiring with other senior Vernon officers
to commit fraud.
   The scheme allegedly involved reimbursing Vernon officers
approximately $55,000 for political campaign contributions to
candidates for state and federal office, said FBI special agent
Woody Specht.
   The indictment charges that the scheme involved contributions in
1986 to Texas Republican gubernatorial candidate Tom Loeffler and
the 1986 Texas Tribute, an organization that donated money to
several politicians, including House Speaker Jim Wright of Fort
Worth, U.S. Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., and U.S. Rep. Jack Kemp,
R-New York.
   But the indictment emphasized that there were no allegations
whatsoever that any of the candidates or campaign organizations
knew that the contributions were coming from Vernon or were
otherwise illegal.
   Wright, under fire for alleged ethics violations, announced his
resignation as speaker Wednesday.
   Cranston was serving on the banking committee at the time of the
donations, the indictment said.
   The indictment, which charges King with conspiring with other
senior officers to defraud the Federal Home Loan Bank Board and to
misapply Vernon funds and enter false statements in its books and
records, was announced by the Dallas Bank Fraud Task Force.
   The task force is a multi-agency group which brought the charges
as part of the U.S. Justice Department's ongoing investigation of
suspected fraud in the Texas banking and savings industry.
   ``In effect, the indictment charges that officials contributed
to campaigns but were then reimbursed through various methods like
through payroll accounts, expense accounts,'' Specht said. ``They
were getting the money back.
   ``The indictment shows that bank officials made contributions
and then false entries were made, et cetera, to conceal the fact
that funds were really paid for political contributions,'' he said.
   Vernon, which had offices in Vernon, Texas, and Dallas, was
closed by the Federal Savings and Loan Insurance Corporation, on
Nov. 19, 1987.
</TEXT>
