<FIRST>u i PM-Uno-Profile     06-02 0499</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Uno-Profile,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Uno, Ruling Party's Second Choice, Lacks Power</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Japan-Politics, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Restoring public confidence in Japan's government
would be a formidible task for anyone in the wake of the Recruit
Co. scandal that toppled Prime Minister Noboro Takeshita.
   For Foreign Minister Sousuke Uno, it could be an impossible one.
   In giving its blessing today for Uno to succeed Takeshita, the
governing Liberal Democrats have picked an experienced politician
who was the party's second choice.
   Party leaders first tried to persuade Masayoshi Ito, 75, to take
the job but Ito refused, citing poor health at age 66 and
dissatisfaction with the party's handling of reforms.
   Few leaders within the scandal-ridden party sang the praises of
Uno. Indeed, many put forward last-minute alternatives to his
nomination.
   Many fear he cannot win public confidence in the government,
shaken by the influence-peddling Recruit scandal that forced
Takeshita to step down and led to charges against 17 politicians,
bureaucrats and businessmen.
   Analysts have speculated that party bosses, who are too tainted
by the financial scandal to take the post now, settled on Uno as an
interim leader who will allow them to exert influence and not
derail their future aspirations.
   Even the conservative Yomiuri Shimbun, Japan's largest
newspaper, described Uno, who has been foreign minister since 1987,
only as ``a reasonable choice.''
   ``Some party leaders would have preferred that the successor to
Prime Minister Takeshita come from the junior ranks in order to
revitalize the party. But Uno was chosen to maintain party
harmony,'' Yomiuri said in an editorial.
   Former prime ministers Zenko Suzuki and Takeo Fukuda suggested
group leadership and expressed fears Uno may be too weak to steer
the conservative party to victory in parliamentary elections this
summer.
   Support for the Liberal Democrats has fallen to the lowest
levels ever, largely because of the scandal.
   The Recruit Co., a publishing and information services
conglomerate, is accused of winning government favors by handing
out millions of dollars in political donations and underpriced
stock.
   Though Uno himself is untainted by the scandal, he is closely
allied with former Prime Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone. The scandal
developed during his 1982-87 tenure.
   Uno said today that he would quit Nakasone's political faction.
   However, their previous close ties damaged Uno's reputation, and
they almost cost him the party nomination, analysts say.
   But supporters say Uno's high-ranking Cabinet posts in a country
striving for a stronger international role have made him a familiar
figure to the Japanese public.
   Uno has headed the Ministry of International Trade and Industry,
the Defense Agency, and the Science and Technology Agency. He is a
10-term member of the lower house of Parliament from Shiga
prefecture in western Japan.
   Born Aug. 27, 1922, into a wealthy family in Shiga, Uno fought
in World War II and served on the Asian mainland before being taken
prisoner by Soviet troops in northern Korea. He and his wife,
Chiyo, have two children, a son and daughter.
</TEXT>
