<DOCNO> AP890602-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 0330EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     06-02 0717</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leahy Says Congress Will Move Slowly on Drought Relief</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress won't be rushing into drought relief
legislation this session the way it did last year, say the chairman
of the Senate Agriculture Committee and a Republican colleague.
   Sens. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., and Rudy Boschwitz, R-Minn., said
Thursday the drought that has devastated winter wheat in some key
states doesn't appear to be a problem yet to other crops.
   After a press conference on an unrelated topic, the senators
said the dry weather problems this year have not reached the
emergency proportions of 1988.
   ``We will take the appropriate steps, but not precipitously,''
said Leahy in reference to the dry spell that hit Kansas and nearby
states hard during early spring.
   ``I'm very concerned about winter wheat,'' he said, ``but I
don't want to move until we see about present crops.''
   Rains have been heavy in recent days in farm states, but they
didn't come soon enough to save most of the winter wheat crop which
the Agriculture Department this week called mostly fair to poor.
   In Kansas, the wheat looks poor to very poor, the department
said. Harvesting of the crop is under way in California, Georgia,
Oklahoma and Texas, while the wheat is still growing elsewhere.
   Winter wheat is planted in the fall and begins to sprout in
early spring, but shortage of spring rain, particularly in Kansas,
has devastated the crop.
   Sen. Bob Dole, R-Kan., has introduced legislation that would
extend the 1988 drought relief law to this year's winter wheat
crop, but no further action has been taken on the bill.
   Leahy said he would ask Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter to
brief members of the Agriculture Committee and other senators
interested in drought legislation soon.
   Yeutter, after touring Iowa drought areas earlier this week,
said, ``We have to be careful we don't overestimate the problems
and respond in a way that just isn't called for under the
circumstances.''
   The House Agriculture Committee last week passed drought
legislation that would extend the 1988 law to many crops besides
winter wheat. The bill has not been voted on by the full House.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China is purchasing wheat at an unusually
rapid rate for the new marketing year, according to Agriculture
Department statistics.
   The department announced Thursday that exporters reported the
country had bought another 100,000 metric tons of soft red winter
wheat.
   That brings China's total for the marketing year beginning June
1 to 850,000 tons.
   The department said 300,000 tons was purchased in April under
the Export Enhancement Program, a U.S. government subsidy that
discounts commodities.
   But 550,000 tons purchased since May 25 have been a full market
value, estimated to be about $82.5 million.
   Last marketing year, China bought a total 8.3 million metric
tons for the full year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Advocates for the popular federal nutrition
program known as WIC say the government should spend $150 million
more on it next fiscal year for the poor people who should be
getting help but aren't.
   About 7.5 million women, infants and children are eligible, but
48 percent are not participating in the program, said Robert Fersh,
executive director of the Food Research and Action Center, who held
a press conference Thursday to announce the results of two studies
of the program.
   ``Our central finding is that young children, those between the
ages of one and five, are the least likely to receive the benefits
of WIC (Special Supplemental Food Program for Women, Infants and
Children),'' he said.
   ``In general, low-income children tend to be shorter and
lighter, and are more likely to suffer from impaired iron status
and anemia,'' he said. ``Poorer iron status is associated with
poorer performance on standardized tests.''
   He said the number of people who participate is dependent on the
amount of money Congress spends on the program.
   The federal budget resolution for fiscal 1990 passed by Congress
in a compromise with the White House calls for spending a total
$2.158 billion on WIC, including the $150 million Fersh wants in it.
   But the details of the budget are not worked out and the
Agriculture Department is facing a requested $1 billion in cuts and
the WIC program is part of agriculture.
</TEXT>
