<FIRST>r w PM-GOP-Ethics     06-02 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-GOP-Ethics,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Republican Lawmakers Urged to Make Hay Out of Ethics Mess</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Wright Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican strategists are urging GOP
lawmakers to make hay out of the ethics mess in the House of
Representatives by claiming it shows Democrats have held power
there for too many years.
   ``The Democrats in the House have grown arrogant with their
unchallenged power,'' says a memo circulated quietly among
Republican lawmakers this week by the National Republican
Congressional Committee.
   The committee produced the paper as a political script for
Republican congressmen in the ethics drama unfolding in the House.
   House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, announced his resignation
Wednesday following a yearlong ethics probe. Less than a week
earlier, Majority Whip Tony Coelho, D-Calif., resigned rather than
subject the Democrats and his family to an investigation of his
$100,000 junk bond purchase.
   The National Republican Congressional Committee raises funds,
produces briefing papers and videos, provides polling, research and
a wide array of other services aimed at helping GOP lawmakers
polish their political image. House Democrats and both parties in
the Senate maintain similar committees.
   In some respects, the briefing paper resembled dozens of others
turned out by the committee. In this case, however, it made
explicit a GOP strategy of exploiting the ethics mess for political
advantage.
   ``Power tends to corrupt, absolute power corrupts absolutely,''
it quoted the 19th Century historian Lord Acton. It cautioned
against falling in with what it described as a Democratic tendency
to blame the fall of Wright and Coelho on ``ethical McCarthyism''
and character assassination.
   ``This is absolutely false,'' it said. ``Jim Wright and Tony
Coelho's falls were character suicides.''
   It called the resignations of two of the top three Democrats in
the House ``the bitter fruit of 35 years of Democratic control of
that body,''
   ``Why did two prominent, intelligent members of the Democratic
leadership get into this bind?'' it asked at another point.
``Because there may have been a feeling of invulnerability. When
you can abuse the rights of the minority ... for as long as they
have, there could well be a feeling that you can do what you want,
ethics be damned.''
   Committee spokesman John Buckley said he was the author of the
document and that it was meant primarily for the eyes of Republican
congressmen. ``Obviously, it wasn't intended to be provided to a
reporter,'' he said.
   He said the GOP was ``fully prepared to take advantage of the
revelations about Democrats,'' but he denied there was any special
campaign-style effort to dig up new dirt.
   House Democratic leader Thomas Foley of Washington, who is
expected to become the next speaker of the House, called for
conciliation Thursday. But some of his followers were in a mood to
fight fire with fire politically.
   ``Democrats are trying to act with restraint,'' declared Rep.
Gary Ackerman, D-N.Y. ``But there comes a time when people are
going to push back, and push back awfully hard.''
</TEXT>
