<FIRST>r w PM-GephardtLeadership     06-02 0646</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gephardt Leadership,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gephardt Appeals to Democrats to Elect Him Majority Leader</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Wright Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard Gephardt is banking on his national
reputation and youthful appeal as a ``new generation'' congressman
in seeking Democratic support to become the next House majority
leader.
   Gephardt, who ran unsuccessfully for president in 1988, said in
an interview Thursday that he is ``encouraged'' by the backing he
has received so far from Democratic colleagues.
   ``The feedback has been positive, but I'm surely not prepared to
say that we've done it,'' said Gephardt.
   The 48-year-old Missourian is running against Rep. Ed Jenkins,
D-Ga., for the No. 2 leadership post to replace Rep. Thomas Foley
of Washington, who is expected to become House speaker next week.
   The leadership scramble, which had been taking shape behind the
scenes, boiled into the open this week with the announcement by
House Speaker Jim Wright's resignation announcement.
   Gephardt publicly launched his campaign with a letter to
Democrats, an appeal for change that stressed his background as one
of the new breed of American politicians who have risen to power in
the post-Watergate era.
   ``John Kennedy said in 1961 that it was time for a new
generation of Americans to lead our country,'' Gephardt wrote.
``Now I believe it is time for a new generation of members to lead
the Congress.''
   He noted that, like himself, two-thirds of current House members
have been elected since 1978, and he described the Democrats as a
``young and vibrant majority.'' Jenkins, 56, also was elected in
1978 and serves with Gephardt on the House Ways and Means Committee.
   Gephardt said he would not seek the 1992 presidential nomination
if he becomes majority leader and said in the letter he would
``devote all of my energies to the work of the House.''
   Some Democrats were annoyed at Gephardt's prolonged absence from
the House during last year's presidential campaign, when he was
head of the party caucus, the No. 4 leadership job. He served four
years in that post.
   Gephardt said he had been seriously considering another run for
the White House, but decided to seek the House post because it was
the ``best way'' to tackle a wide range issues before the country.
   ``I am not going to use a House leadership position as a
stepping stone to something else,'' Gephardt said.
   ``I haven't said this about '92 because I thought it was
necessary to get elected but because I believe that you can't do
two things at once of this magnitude. You can't be an effective
majority leader and be running for president. It's just that
simple.''
   Gephardt's allies contend he would serve as an articulate
spokesman for the party in the television age of sound-bite
politics. He earned a name for himself as an early advocate of
politically attractive issues such as tax reform and a champion of
a get-tough trade policy, which became the centerpiece of his
presidential campaign.
   ``I think I have learned how to put together coalitions in the
House so we can reach consensus in the Congress and be able to
assert a policy,'' said Gephardt. ``I also have learned something
about conveying an issue to voters in the country at large.''
   Gephardt also is viewed as one of the party's few potential
leaders who have been certified by a presidential campaign as free
of any ethical problems that could cause Democrats further
embarrassment.
   He said he decided to jump into the leadership race over the
weekend after learning from news accounts that Rep. Tony Coelho,
D-Calif., the majority whip, was resigning from the House in order
to avoid a lengthy investigation into his own personal finances.
   Before that, he had decided not to challenge Coelho for the post
because of their friendship and instead was considering running for
whip, the No. 3 leadership job.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890602-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 0409EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-HouseLeadership     06-02 0699</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-House Leadership,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Democrats Working In Atmosphere Of Suspicion</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Wright Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Democrats are trying to elect new
leaders in an atmosphere of suspicion that shows few signs of
abating despite the resignation of Speaker Jim Wright.
   Rep. Thomas Foley, D-Wash., certain to replace Wright as speaker
in an election scheduled for Tuesday, said he hoped to return the
House ``to a mood of mutual respect and conciliation between the
parties.''
   Wright, in a luncheon with reporters, said, ``There has to come
an end, there must come an end'' to the use of ethics as a
political weapon. ``Do I believe that's going to happen overnight
because I said it? No, I do not.''
   Democrats had hoped Wright's resignation, which followed the
resignation of the No. 3 Democrat, Rep. Tony Coelho of California,
also because of controversy over personal finances, would put the
ethics issue behind them.
   So they were angered Thursday about news reports that the
Justice Department was checking personnel practices in the office
of Rep. William H. Gray III of Pennsylvania, the fourth-ranking
House leader and now candidate for Coelho's slot in the coming
succession.
   ``The Democrats very clearly believe this is a concerted,
planned, coordinated effort. It is a continuation of the 1988
campaign. I think there is certainly a feeling now that the White
House is accountable,'' said Rep. Steny Hoyer, D-Md., a member of
the Democratic leadership.
   House Minority Leader Bob Michel, R-Ill., sent a letter to the
Justice Department decrying the leaks in the Gray case.
   But Republicans, who caucused Thursday to discuss ethics,
otherwise made clear they saw no reason to let go of the issue with
which they have been battering the Democrats for months.
   Rep. Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., who launched the ethics investigation
which eventually brought down Wright, said Thursday he was ``angry
at the tone'' of Wright's speech before the House on Wednesday.
   Wright's calling it ``mindless cannibalism'' that had engulfed
him was ``an insult to the ethics committee and every decent person
in the House... It was not mindless, it was very serious,'' said
Gingrich, who as the House Minority Whip is Michel's next in
command.
   Gingrich said while Justice Department leaks of the case
involving Gray were wrong, the political parties could ``police
each other'' by checking into possible wrongdoing by the
opposition. ``Jim Wright's a symbol of how sick the Congress has
become,'' he said.
   While some clearly remained in a confrontational mode, others
said the point of deepest angst had passed with Wright's
resignation.
   Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., said the speaker's announcement
was ``a catharsis.''
   Rep. Byron Dorgan, D-N.D., called on those ``couple of dozen
members'' who have been badmouthing the House to stop.``I think
it's time for the members of this House who don't want to serve
here to leave,'' he said.
   With Foley running for speaker, Rep. Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., is
promising to stay and serve if he's elected Majority Leader.
Gephardt ran for president in 1988 but is promising to stay in the
House and forego another attempt in 1992.
   Gephardt, who is battling Rep. Ed Jenkins, D-Ga., for Majority
Leader, said in a letter to colleagues Thursday that he ``was not
interested in wallowing in rumor or engaging in partisan intrigue.''
   He wrapped himself in Foley's coattails, pledging to work with
his popular colleague to install a ``new generation'' of leaders in
the House.
   The race for Majority Whip includes Gray, who is now the
chairman of the House Democratic Caucus; David Bonior, the Chief
Deputy Whip, and Rep. Beryl Anthony, D-Ark., the chairman of the
Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee. Rep. Henry Waxman,
D-Calif., was also assessing his chances.
   ``Will Bill Gray be able to hold his troops? That's the
question,'' said Schumer, alluding to the bad publicity Gray had to
explain to jittery Democrats. ``So far, there aren't many
defections.''
   While election of a new speaker by the Democrats and the full
House has been scheduled for Tuesday, no date has been set for
Democrats to choose their party leadership posts.
   Lawmakers said it would most likely occur a week or more after
the speaker's election.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
