<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 0440EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-FamilySlayings-Reax     06-02 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Family Slayings-Reax,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suspect in 1971 Slayings Seemed Average to Neighbors</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Family Slayings, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILARY APPELMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIDLOTHIAN, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man known here as Robert P. Clark was
a quiet, hard-working, church-going man.
   So neighbors were shocked when FBI agents came looking for him
Thursday, saying he was John E. List and was wanted for the
slayings of his family nearly 18 years ago.
   ``I don't know what a guy who's killed five people is supposed
to look like, but he was not that person,'' said Pat Ferguson, who
lives two doors from the man she knew as Clark in this Richmond
suburb.
   The agents didn't find List at home, but arrested him later at
the Richmond accounting firm where he worked.
   He was charged with fleeing to avoid prosecution. He faces five
counts of first-degree murder in New Jersey for the 1971 shooting
deaths of his mother, wife and three children in Westfield.
   The FBI said List, 63, was identified by his fingerprints. He
was ordered jailed pending a Monday bond hearing.
   The arrest, which resulted from tips from viewers of the Fox
television program ``America's Most Wanted,'' stunned neighbors and
co-workers of the balding, bespectacled accountant.
   ``You talk about an average neighborhood, this is it,'' said
Ferguson, who described Clark as a good neighbor.
   ``He worked hard in his yard, went to work every day, went to
church every Sunday. The guy was so average,'' Ferguson said.
   Clark and his wife, Delores, moved into the area last July from
Colorado, neighbors said. They had not yet gotten around to
painting their name on the rust-colored mailbox in front of their
small blue ranch house.
   Joseph and Jacqueline Stefano said the Clarks were good,
hardworking people who did not like to talk about their past.
   ``We thought they were normal people _ like us,'' Mrs. Stefano
said.
   The two families did odd jobs for each other and exchanged books
and videotapes, Stefano said. An American flag hanging in front of
the Stefano's house was a gift from Clark, he said.
   Clark often would call up and recommend a particular movie or
television show, Stefano said. One of his picks was ``America's
Most Wanted,'' but Stefano missed the program the week List was
featured.
   The Clarks had been married since 1983, Mrs. Stefano said. Mrs.
Clark had told her that Clark's first wife had died and that he had
no children from either marriage.
   Clark ``just seemed like a very, very nice fellow,'' said a
woman who worked with him at the Maddrea, Joyner, Kirkham &amp; Woody
accounting firm. She said she ``would hold him up to my husband as
a model because I heard him talk to his wife on the phone. He would
say how much he loved her.''
   Another co-worker said Clark ``even had a Fraternal Order of
Police sticker on his car.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
