<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 0318EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     06-02 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tokyo Stocks Off Sharply, Dollar Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange dropped sharply
Friday, while the U.S. dollar declined against the Japanese yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average closed at 33,667.42, falling
313.93 points or 0.92 percent.
   The dollar finished trading at 141.80 yen, 0.72 yen below its
finish on Thursday. It opened at 142.12 yen and ranged between
141.32 and 142.15 yen during the day.
   A trader with Mitsubishi Bank in Tokyo said the dollar fell as
speculative investors sold it for profit-taking.
   ``Japanese investors sold the dollar today more than we have
expected, but most of them are making position adjustments,'' he
added, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The majority of market players avoided major moves ahead of the
U.S. jobless report, the trader added. The United States is to
announce the nation's unemployment rate for May later Friday in
Washington.
   On the stock exchange, ``the index started to fall as investors'
wait-and-see mood became stronger,'' said Nikko Securities' dealer
Yoshio Shimoyama.
   ``The Nikkei's early gain was just a rebound effect from
yesterday's plunge, and the market today was lacking buying
incentives,'' he said.
   Market players avoided buying issues ahead of the release of the
jobless report, Shimoyama said.
   ``Although the dollar-yen rate, which has been investors' major
concern, has stabilized pretty much, now they are more concerned
about the jobless rate,' he said.
</TEXT>
