<DOCNO> AP890602-0047 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 0447EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-TankerSpill     06-02 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tanker Spill,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coast Guard Chief Says He's Pleased With Spill Cleanup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL JENKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Coast Guard commandant said Exxon is
making progress in cleaning up its huge oil spill off the Alaskan
coast, but the state's top conservation official said a lot more
work needs to be done.
   ``I'm seeing a massive project that appears to be well run,''
Adm. Paul Yost said Thursday after touing Prince William Sound
beaches.
   The state's commissioner for environmental conservation said
Exxon has increased its effort but is not through gearing up for
the job.
   ``We think there's a long way to go both inside and outside
Prince William Sound,'' Dennis Kelso said.
   Meanwhile, a rule went into effect Thursday requiring alcohol
tests for skippers and other tanker crew members who might operate
oil-laden vessels through the sound. Shipping companies are to hire
contractors who will administer the tests.
   The requirement is part of an interim set of state rules
established after the tanker Exxon Valdez ran aground March 24 in
the sound and spilled nearly 11 million gallons of oil. Its
captain, Joseph Hazelwood, failed sobriety tests administered more
than 10 hours after the accident. The vessel's third mate was
operating the ship when it ran aground.
   Yost, making his fourth visit to contaminated beaches as a
chilly rain fell, was accompanied by Otto Harrison, Exxon's general
manager in Valdez, and Coast Guard Vice Adm. Clyde Robbins, the
federal on-scene coordinator of the cleanup.
   During a visit to Homer on Wednesday, Yost said the company
almost certainly will miss its Sept. 15 deadline for oil cleanup.
   Robbins said Exxon has been doing a good job logistically in the
sound, but perhaps should be prodded to do more on south-central
Alaska beaches outside the sound.
   Exxon has the money and means to get the job done, Robbins said,
and that leads him ``farther away from the idea of federalizing''
the cleanup. Some critics of Exxon's performance contend the
government should take over the project.
   At Smith Island _ one of the most heavily oiled beaches and one
that drew the most effort early in the cleanup _ rocks, sand and
gravel remained coated with oil Thursday, and an oily sheen washed
off the shore.
   Exxon officials classified the beach as ``environmentally
clean.'' That means birds, seals and otters are not picking up more
oil from the beach, Harrison said.
   He said crews have cleaned 20 miles of beach inside the sound
and about 50 miles outside. State officials said more than 700
miles were contaminated. Exxon has said it will be able to clean
just over 350 miles.
   Yost was confronted by residents Wednesday when he visited some
coastal communities of south-central Alaska. People were angry that
he called Exxon's logistical work good, he said.
   After a meeting with state and Exxon officials later Thursday,
Yost said that more work needs to be done, but he is impressed by
the technology being used in the cleanup.
   ``It's a disaster that doesn't lend itself to restoration very
quickly or very easily, and there will not be a complete
restoration this summer, either in Prince William Sound or probably
outside of Prince William Sound,'' Yost said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890602-0048 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 0447EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-People-DustinHoffman     06-02 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Dustin Hoffman,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Stage Debut in Shakespeare Gets Cool Reception</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Dustin Hoffman received mixed reviews today
after his British stage debut as Shylock in Shakespeare's play,
``The Merchant of Venice.''
   While the production won cheers Thursday night from a
celebrity-studded first-night audience at London's Phoenix Theater,
critic Irving Wardle wrote in The Times of London today:
   ``All the clamorous hype and slavering expectation is a poor
preparation for the modest Shylock who arrived on the Phoenix stage
last night ... Hoffman's is much the most genial Shylock that I
have seen ...
   ``What does not come off are the directly emotional climaxes,
which strain his voice to the limit and substitute rhetoric ... for
his particular and priceless capacity for expressing the secrets of
a man's mind through low-key unguarded utterance.''
   Michael Billington said in The Guardian: ``Although Mr.
Hoffman's humorous approach pays handsome dividends ... it also
means a loss of the tragic dimension. ... What it lacks is any
strong sense of the character's inveterate malignity.''
   Jack Tinker wrote in the London tabloid the Daily Mail:
``Without being great, he is most certainly good.''
   Lester Middlehurst, writing in Today, another tabloid, said:
``Hoffman's Shylock is ... fascinating.''
   The production was by Sir Peter Hall, who directed the National
Theater in London from 1973 until last year.
   Hoffman agreed to the part of Shylock but said after studying
the play that he found it very anti-Semitic. Critics agreed today,
however, that Hoffman's portrayal had reversed this traditional
view.
   ``The manifest aim... is to show him (Shylock) as a good man
driven beyond endurance by his bestial treatment from the
Christians,'' Wardle wrote.
   The actor, who won the Oscar this year as best actor for his
performance in ``Rain Man,'' is said to receive $6 million dollars
for each film. But the British domestic agency Press Association
said Hoffman is getting paid $3,140 a week for three months in the
play.
   The first-night audience included Dame Peggy Ashcroft, Joan
Collins and ex-Beatle Paul McCartney.
</TEXT>
