<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 0510EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Senate-ArmsControl 1stLd-Writethru a0439 06-02 0747</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Senate-Arms Control, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0439,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arms Pact Would Not Mean Destruction Of New Weaponry</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs, bgng ``We have, to restore Herres' first
name; picks up 4th graf, Sen. Alan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Expensive, state-of-the-art weapons, such as
the F-16 jet fighter or the M-1 battle tank, would be redistributed
rather than destroyed if an agreement on arms reduction in central
Europe is reached with the Soviet Union, Bush administration
officials say.
   Addressing concerns expressed Thursday by members of the Senate
Armed Services Committee, the officials said the cuts proposed by
Bush in NATO and Warsaw Pact forces can be accomplished by
destroying older weapons.
   ``We have enough of the older weapons that can be destroyed
without destroying newer weapons,'' said Air Force Gen. Robert T.
Herres, vice chairman of the military Joint Chiefs of Staff.
   Sen. Alan Dixon, D-Ill., declared: ``It doesn't make sense to
destroy $20 million F-16 fighters at a time when our reserve and
guard units are still flying 1960's vintage F-4 fighters.''
   But Herres said that will not be allowed to happen.
   ``We propose to redistribute new equipment such as F-16's and
M-1 tanks,'' he said. ``We have no intention of destroying them.
Our obvious target will be older equipment.''
   He also said there is nothing in the Bush proposal to prevent
NATO or the Soviets from modernizing the military forces that
remain after reductions.
   Meanwhile, Defense Secretary Richard Cheney said in an interview
published in The Washington Post today that the United States might
wind up stressing lighter equipment for land forces to ease rapid
deployment if Bush's proposals for armed forces reductions in
Europe are accepted.
   Cheney said the proposed ceiling of 275,000 troops for both the
United States and the Soviet Union in Europe might raise other
questions, such as whether ships would be better than aircraft for
reinforcement from the United States in war.
   Though the proposal makes military sense, Cheney said he was
worried that Congress would try to double or triple the president's
proposed reduction of 30,000 U.S. troops. ``Maybe eventually we can
talk about those numbers, but not now,'' he said in the Post
interview.
   Herres and Under Secretary of Defense Paul Wolfowitz commented
as a broad bipartisan cross section of the committee praised the
Bush proposal as a potentially historic breakthrough that could
sharply reduce the prospects for war in Europe.
   Chairman Sam Nunn, D-Ga., hailed the Bush proposal as taking
``an innovative'' approach and said it will ``reduce the dangers of
war in Europe,'' while posing the possibility of creating future
savings that could eventually help the United States deal with the
budget deficit.
   The Bush proposal calls for:
   _Reductions in tanks, armored troop carriers and artillery in
the area from the Atlantic to the Ural Mountains that will require
far deeper cuts by the Soviet Union and its allies than by the
United States and NATO.
   _Reductions of 15 percent below current levels of helicopters
and land-based combat planes in the Atlantic to the Urals zone.
   _A ceiling of 275,000 on U.S. and Soviet ground and air force
personnel in the zone, a ceiling which would require a reduction of
some 325,000 Soviet troops to achieve.
   _Speeding up the pace of negotiations and the implementation of
an agreement to accomplish the reductions by 1992 or 1993, about
four or five years sooner than the time table suggested by the
Soviets.
   Herres and Wolfowitz said the plan does not set a rigid
timetable which might trap the United States into accepting a bad
agreement contrary to U.S. security interests.
   And Wolfowitz said it will require verification procedures far
more intrusive than any so far put into effect for any other arms
control arrangement.
   Several committee members declared, and the administration
witnesses agreed, that no attempt should be made to cut defense
spending before agreement on the Bush proposal is reached.
   ``We've got to be very careful of not getting out in front of
reality,'' Herres said. ``But if we are successful in the arms
control adventure, we will be relieving future generations of a
considerable burden if we can defuse the situation in central
Europe in this way.''
   Speaking to reporters after the hearing, Herres remarked:
   ``If four or five years ago someone had told me we were going to
be in a position to achieve parity with the Soviet Union in five
important categories I would have walked away laughing.''
</TEXT>
