<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 0354EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Japan 6thLd-Writethru   06-02 0867</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan, 6th Ld-Writethru,a0474,0887</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Uno Becomes Prime Minister After Quick House Approval</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with seven grafs to UPDATE with upper house passage, Uno
becomes prime minister. Picks up graf 4, `The Recruit ...' TRIMS final
four grafs to shorten.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANICE FUHRMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sousuke Uno became Japan's prime minister Friday
and pledged political reforms to clear the air of a scandal that
has decimated the top ranks of the long-governing Liberal
Democratic Party.
   The 66-year-old former foreign minister also sounded a tough
note about trade problems with the United States, saying
Washington's use of its new trade law to force concessions from
Japan was ``like negotiating with your fists up.''
   The conservative party was to get a new leadership roster and a
new Cabinet was to be installed in an effort to wipe the slate
clean of the Recruit influence-buying scandal before a national
election for half the upper house of Parliament, expected within
two months.
   The scandal erupted a year ago, ruined many careers and forced
Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita, 65, to resign and take
responsibility for a widespread loss of trust in politics.
   The two houses of the Diet, Japan's parliament, met separately
Friday afternoon and elected Uno prime minister on the strength of
the Liberal Democrats' large majorities.
   In the House of Representatives, Uno got 285 of 477 votes, with
Japan Socialist Party Chairwoman Takako Doi receiving 139, Eiichi
Nagasue of the Democratic Socialist Party 26 and Kenji Miyamoto of
the Communist Party 25. Two votes were ruled invalid.
   The upper House of Councillors gave Uno 124 of 220 votes, with
Ms. Doi capturing 65, Miyamoto 17 and Nagasue 9. Five ballots were
blank, officials announced.
   ``The Recruit scandal had a great impact, and I understand what
it means to be chosen as prime minister in such a situation,'' Uno
said. ``I would like to promise to carry forward political reforms
with all my loyalty and strength.''
   Many within the party objected to Uno because he is a senior
member of the faction of former Prime Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone.
The scandal, involving bribes and cut-rate sales of stock in a
subsidiary of the Recruit Co. information conglomerate, developed
during Nakasone's 1982-87 administration.
   But in his acceptance speech, Uno said he was resigning from the
Nakasone faction, taking one of the steps recommended by a party
panel on reform.
   Factional rivalry within the party is regarded as one reason why
large amounts of money are needed in Japanese politics, because
factional leaders must help finance their followers' political
activities.
   Nakasone resigned from the party because of the Recruit scandal,
but he retained his seat in Parliament and analysts expect him to
retain his influence.
   Takeshita announced April 25 that he would resign, but the
search for a replacement took more than a month because of the
Recruit scandal, which reached the top levels of politics, business
and the bureaucracy. Uno agreed on Wednesday to take the job.
   Although Uno was endorsed by Takeshita and the party's power
brokers, a rebel candidate, 68-year-old lawmaker Ganri Yamashita,
was put forward Thursday by young party hawks who favor more
military spending. Yamashita is a former Defense Agency chief who
had tried to put forward an alternate candidate when the party
chose Takeshita as its leader in October 1987.
   There was no official count at Friday's meeting, attended by 341
of the party's 436 Diet members. Instead, those present stood in
response to a call for support of Uno.
   Yamashita's supporters complained of a lack of democracy and
demanded a ballot, but the leadership said the conference was
called only to endorse the decision made behind closed doors by the
party's Executive Council.
   ``The majority of the party wants to find a candidate
peacefully,'' said Ryutaro Hashimoto, the party deputy secretary
general. ``And we took it into consideration that it has to be
someone who has currency in international society. Japan must make
contributions in international society, and we have decided to
recommend Sousuke Uno.''
   The new prime minister will have a major task in convincing the
Japanese public that the Liberal Democrats will retool the
political style that let politicians and aides accept huge tax-free
profits through the purchase of pre-listed shares in 1986 in the
Recruit subsidiary.
   Three Cabinet members resigned in connection with the Recruit
scandal, and 14 people, including two former vice ministers, were
arrested on suspicion of bribery or securities exchange law
violations.
   Takeshita apologized Friday for his role in the scandal, which
has stained the top ranks of politics, business and the bureaucracy.
   ``Considering the burning anger among the Japanese people and
also some facts around me in relation to the stock scandal, I
thought it is most appropriate for me to resign if it would help to
pursue policital reforms,'' he said in a short, somber speech.
   ``I would also like to apologize to the public for all the
troubles due to my lack of discretion,'' he said.
   Many of the Liberal Democrats' top leaders were ineligible to
succeed Takeshita because they are tainted by the Recruit scandal.
Party power brokers finally turned to Uno after elder statesman
Masayoshi Ito repeatedly refused the job.

</TEXT>
