<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-CongressChaos     06-02 0658</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Congress Chaos,0677</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chaos Co-Opts Traditional Soviet Control in New Congress</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet-Parliament, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For a Soviet system that has stressed order and
control above all else, the inaugural meeting of its new Congress
has been a lesson in the untidiness of democracy. And the people
love it.
   In a week of nationally broadcast sessions that have captivated
Soviets, the 2,250 members of the Congress of People's Deputies
have been learning by trial and error that basic rules of procedure
_ and basic tools such as microphones _ can be as important as
debate itself.
   ``We were the first country in the world to send a man to space,
and our president is counting the votes in the hall with his
fingers,'' complained one deputy, Moldavian writer Ion Drutse.
   Gone are the strict order and decorum that marked previous
incarnations of the Soviet parliament over 70 years of Communist
rule. However dull those sessions were, the agenda was clear and
the speakers had a clear purpose _ to sop up to the leadership.
   Some deputies are impatient with the new disorder, and one said
Monday the session was marred by ``a lot of messing around'' about
procedural matters, such as how long speakers should be given the
floor.
   Another said that with the people's hopes raised the meeting
would begin to solve some of the country's most pressing problems,
it had become ``a Congress of unused opportunities.'' The deputy,
Oleg V. Chernyshev, said some deputies had suffered ``intoxication
with the air within the Kremlin walls.''
   Not even the length of the session is known. It was originally
scheduled to end Wednesday but could last at least a week longer.
   More than 500 deputies have signed up to speak, and the list
keeps growing. So far, only about half have taken the floor.
   The agenda of the Congress also was never clearly spelled out.
In the first four days, the deputies elected a president, Mikhail
S. Gorbachev, heard his report on the state of the union, chose a
vice president, Anatoly I. Lukyanov, and a smaller law-making body.
   But aside from a speech expected by Premier Nikolai I. Ryzhkov,
the remaining agenda is unclear, so the debate has wandered from
the sad state of Soviet libraries to sharp criticism of members of
the ruling Politburo, including Gorbachev.
   At times, deputies pop up from their seats to shout at speakers
or presiding officers. Some demand to speak from the stage; others
prefer just to stand and shout. Only a couple of microphones were
set up on the huge floor for deputies to raise points of order.
They were installed late and are only used ocassionally.
   ``Why did we put up microphones? To decorate the room?'' deputy
Alexei Yastrebov asked sarcastically.
   Some presiding officers have lost their tempers.
   ``You sit down!'' the chairman of Thursday's session, Ukrainian
Boris Y. Paton, shouted to one deputy who walked onto the stage
uninvited.
   Gorbachev intervened on several occasions to calm the hall.
   Long delays and confusion have marred voting, and several
deputies have complained their legislative proposals were not being
distributed to the Congress.
   Electronic voting equipment was never needed for previous
incarnations of the Soviet parliament, because votes were almost
always unanimous. But substantial opposition has surfaced in the
new Congress.
   Drutse, in a speech Thursday, charged that party leaders
intentionally did not have voting equipment installed.
   ``This has happened because the apparatus wants to control the
voting,'' he declared.
   Lukyanov was also criticized for not having prepared rules of
procedure for the Congress in advance. He said this was not done
because presiding officers thought it more democratic if the
deputies themselves set procedure.
   But even when procedures are set, they are often violated. After
much wrangling intitially, the Congress decided to allow each
speaker 15 minutes.
   Gorbachev complained on Wednesday, ``No sooner had this rule
been set than it was broken.''
</TEXT>
