<DOCNO> AP890602-0056 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 0434EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     06-02 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tokyo Stocks Off Sharply, Dollar Declines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange dropped sharply
today, while the U.S. dollar also declined against the Japanese yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average closed at 33,667.42, falling
313.93 points or 0.92 percent.
   The dollar finished trading at 141.80 yen, 0.72 yen below
Thursday finish. It opened at 142.12 yen and ranged from 141.32 to
142.15 yen during the day.
   ``Market players were adjusting their positions before the U.S.
announces its jobless rate,'' said a foreign exchange dealer at the
Bank of Tokyo on condition of anonymity.
   The United States is to announce the nation's unemployment rate
for May later today in Washington.
   A strong trend toward buying Swiss francs that began earlier
this week also is pulling buyers away from the yen, the dealer said.
   The Swiss National Bank has said it will introduce a floating
rate system, which investors see as favorable to the Swiss currency.
   The dealer said the yen will remain weak until the confusion
plaguing Japanese politics settles down.
   A major bribery scandal, which resulted in the resignation of
Noboru Takeshita as prime minister, has created an air of political
uncertainty for months.
   The dealer said he did not expect today's official selection of
former Foreign Minister Sousuke Uno as Japan's new prime minister
to have much effect on the market.
   However, uncertainty about Uno and how he will deal with the
scandal was keeping some buyers away from the yen.
   ``People do not know Uno abroad.'' the dealer said.
   In the stock market, political concerns also discouraged
investors, said Noboru Ohsuga, chief portfolio manager for Daiwa
Investment Trust and Management Co.
   In a gradual retreat, the market has closed lower in five of the
last six trading days due to profit-taking and a shift by investors
away from domestic demand-related issues and toward high-tech
shares.
</TEXT>
