<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 0606EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MemoryWhiz     06-02 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Memory Whiz,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grant Commissioned to Study Man's Amazing Memory</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WICHITA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A student whose extraordinary memory has
enabled him to memorize 35,000 digits of an equation _ and pick up
a few bar bets along the way _ is the subject of a $157,000 federal
study, a newspaper reported today.
   Srinivasan Mahadevan, a graduate student from India at Kansas
State University in Manhattan, is trying to become the fourth
person to remember the first 100,000 digits to pi, the
theoretically infinite computation that measures the ratio of the
circumference of a circle to its diameter. He has already memorized
the first 35,000 digits of pi.
   Only three cases of such ability to remember have been
documented in 200 years. One of those people became insane when he
became unable to forget anything and his reasoning processes
drowned in a flood of facts.
   To find out what makes Mahadevan tick, the federal government
has awarded a $157,000 grant to Kansas State, The Wichita
Eagle-Beacon reported.
   The answer may shed light on how other people remember things.
   ``We're hoping to find insights into the average intelligence,
too,'' said Rod Vogl, a graduate assistant in charge of
administering tests.
   Four students with average memories also are being studied as a
control group, and so far they haven't fared well against
Mahadevan. A test involves flashing one number on a screen per
second _ or speaking one number per second _ and seeing how many
the students can remember. The average score is seven or eight and
anything above 10 is considered exceptional. Mahadevan typically
tallies about 38 if he sees the numbers, about 50 if hears them.
   Of course, that's under clinical conditions. Vogl says Mahadevan
usually scores much better _ as many as 105 _ in the friendlier
atmosphere of the Manhattan watering holes where he has been known
to win some astounding bar bets.
   The 30-year-old native of Mangalore, India, thinks heredity and
his childhood environment both played significant roles.
   ``It runs in the family,'' he said. ``My father knows all 37
plays and 150 sonnets of William Shakespeare by heart, so I think
there is a genetic basis for it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890602-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 0615EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BlastTest     06-02 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Blast Test,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>Explosion Designed to Test Blast on Structures, Equipment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIE AICHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WHITE SANDS MISSILE RANGE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A simulated nuclear blast
destroyed scaled-down versions of bridges, homes and a forest in a
test to show what happens to military and civilian equipment during
and after a large explosion.
   The pine trees, model bridges and and structures were among
hundreds of items placed at various distances from ground zero
where 2,440 tons of ammonium nitrate and fuel oil were detonated
Thursday.
   It will take months for scientists to evaluate the results, said
Navy Cmdr. J.R. Lund of the Defense Nuclear Agency's Test
Directorate.
   The agency sponsored the test, called Miser's Gold and designed
to determine the effects of air blast and ground shock on such
things as bunkers, underground shelters and radar. It was the fifth
in a series of non-nuclear explosions the agency has set off since
1976.
   Seven of about 180 test trees remained after the explosion. The
walls of the buildings facing the blast site looked as though a
giant fist had torn through them.
   One of two small model bridges collapsed; the other was severely
damaged.
   ``No one is going to be driving over that bridge,'' Lund told
reporters during a drive through the 120-acre test bed about two
hours after the blast.
   Some of the military equipment used in the blast included a
helicopter, tanks, parts of Navy ships and some foreign vehicles.
   The equipment, including three Soviet military vehicles, was
covered immediately after the blast to hide the damage.
   Lund said it would be possible for other countries to fly
overhead and photograph the damage.
   ``We don't want other people to know how much damage it caused
to our equipment or theirs,'' he said.
   Thursday's blast had a simulated equivalent of a 4-kiloton
nuclear bomb. The bomb dropped on Hiroshima, Japan, had a force of
13 kilotons.
   Lt. Col. David Barber, who helped design the test bed, said the
fallout from the explosion sounded like rain on the tin roof of the
George McDonald ranch house. Barber watched the explosion from the
house two miles from ground zero.
   ``It knocked one guy's hat off (in the house),'' said Barber,
his own hat speckled with dust pellets from the fallout.
   Lund said the cost of the experiment was $7.6 million to $7.8
million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
