<FIRST>r a PM-Defaults-Worst     06-02 0579</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Defaults-Worst,0598</SECOND>
<HEAD>Schools Fear Report on Loan-Defaults Could Put Them Out of Business</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Student Defaults</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By A.J. DICKERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CENTER LINE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Michigan trade schools may not
survive a federal report listing them as having the nation's worst
student-loan default rates, according to school officials.
   ``This could put us out of business,'' said Joseph Belliotti
Jr., vice president of the Saywer School of Business in this
middle-income Detroit suburb. He said a U.S. Education Department
report stating that 93.8 percent of Sawyer students who were due to
start repaying loans in 1986 failed to do so was inaccurate.
   Officials at other trade schools with high percentages of
delinquent borrowers said federal penalties could discourage
schools from serving low-income students.
   ``We're the schools of last resort. These people have been shut
out of the entire school system,'' said Ted Jakub, president of the
Cambridge Business College of Detroit, which had a loan-default
rate of 86 percent. ``They can't go to the community colleges. The
only place they've got to go is a school that will show interest in
them.''
   Education Secretary Lauro Cavazos announced Thursday that
schools with extremely high percentages of delinquent borrowers
will face an escalating series of corrective and punitive actions.
   Under the new federal guidelines, schools with default rates
above 60 percent could be barred from the government's student loan
program starting Jan. 1, 1991, and schools with 40 percent to 60
percent of their students failing to pay back loans must reduce the
figure by 5 percent a year or face the same penalties.
   The four schools with the highest default rates were from
Michigan.
   Officials at Sawyer expressed shock at having the nation's
highest student loan-default rate, since the federal figure was
more than twice the rate reported by the state of Michigan, which
administers the school's guaranteed loan program.
   Based on loans from 1975 through April 30, Sawyer's cumulative
default rate was 38.39 percent, according to George Lamb,
supervisor of claims and collections for the Michigan School Loan
Guarantee Program.
   ``Nobody from the state wants to talk to the feds, and no one
from the feds wants to talk to the state,'' said Sawyer
administrator Mike Shiner, who questioned how the federal figure
was calculated.
   The school trains about 300 students in office skills. A
six-month secretarial course costs $3,900.
   Officials at other trade schools with high default rates said
the income levels of the students they serve should be taken into
consideration.
   ``We have quite a few low-income, less advantaged students
through here,'' said Jessica Murray, co-owner of the Kalamazoo
Beauty Academy in Kalamazoo, which had the second-highest default
rate nationally, 89.5 percent. ``I think that always should put
some credence into the fact that our default rate is going to be
higher.''
   She added, ``We have no recourse to collect loans, nor to
enforce payment. I think we've become a little bit of a scapegoat.''
   At the Cambridge Business College of Detroit, ``We deal strictly
with the inner-city minorities,'' Jakub said.
   ``Some of our students go to work after graduation. Some do not
go to work because of the welfare system,'' he said. ``They find
the welfare benefits equal to what they earn out there.''
   Federal sanctions could force the Cambridge school, which has
about 200 students, out of business, Jakub said.
   The fourth Michigan school on the federal list, the
Payne-Pulliam School of Trade in Detroit, had a default rate of
85.5 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
