<DOCNO> AP890602-0063 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 0624EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Coelho     06-02 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coelho,0444</SECOND>
<HEAD>Resigning House Whip Says `No Other Issue Involved'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MODX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE BIGHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MODESTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Majority Whip Tony Coelho returned
to his home district insisting nothing is hanging over him besides
his already revealed purchase of $100,000 in junk bonds that led to
his resignation.
   ``Some say this is not the type of mistake to do what you are
doing,'' Coelho told reporters late Thursday on his first visit to
the district since his startling resignation announcement.
   ``There is no other issue involved,'' he said. ``It's just that
I set a high standard. I made a mistake. I'm willing to live with
it, and it's time to move on.''
   Pressed again about whether any other undisclosed financial
dealings could prove embarrassing, he responded:
   ``I just answered that and don't care to answer it again.''
   He said he decided to quit Congress for fear he would be
ineffective because questions about his financial deals would
overshadow his work.
   ``I felt for the next two years, I would be answering no
questions except my personal finances, and my ability to represent
would not be there,'' Coelho said. ``Everybody is replaceable,
myself included.''
   Coelho's announcement last week that he will resign from
Congress on June 15, his 47th birthday, surprised many observers
who felt he had not been that severely damaged from disclosures
about his investment in a $100,000 junk bond for which he put up no
money of his own.
   Still, Coelho said he didn't want to put his family or the
Democratic party through a protracted controversy over his finances.
   During Thursday's news conference, Coelho said: ``If you are a
hard-driving, partisan politician, and you like to make a
difference, if you make a mistake as I admitted I did, it is
difficult to do what you want done.''
   He contended that his junk bond purchase was legal, and news
reports that he is subject to a criminal investigation for owing
back taxes are false.
   Even though allegations are untrue, ``you can't take them back
once they are printed,'' Coelho said.
   With his wife, Phyllis, and two teen-age daughters at his side,
Coelho said he wears a Mickey Mouse watch ``to remind myself never
to take myself personally that seriously. During the last 10 years,
I always thought personal power was not that important. Power is
important to get things done.''
   Coelho, whose youthful hope of becoming a priest was stopped
when he learned he had epilepsy, said he has no regrets about
leaving Congress.
   ``I have tremendous inner peace,'' he said.
</TEXT>
