<FIRST>r i PM-SouthAfrica-Hangings     06-02 0187</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa-Hangings,0192</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman, Three Men Hanged in Pretoria</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four convicted murderers were
hanged today, including the first woman to be executed in South
Africa since 1986.
   Sandra Smith, a 24-year-old mother of three, was hanged at
Pretoria Central Prison along with a co-accused, Yassiem Harris,
21, for the stabbing death of a 16-year-old girl during a 1986
burglary in Cape Town.
   Also hanged was Michael Erasmus, convicted of suffocating a
fellow prisoner in a police cell in 1987, and Jacob Ndada, 28,
convicted of killing five blacks with a stolen pistol during a
weeklong rape and robbery spree in 1987.
   Ndada was black, while Smith, Harris and Erasmus were of
mixed-race.
   So far this year, 28 people have been hanged in South Africa,
including two whites, 22 blacks and four people of mixed-race.
   The rate of executions is down sharply from last year, when 117
people were hanged, or 1987, when a record 164 people were executed.
   The Justice Department said 37 Death Row prisoners have been
granted reprieves so far this year. About 200 prisoners remain on
Death Row.
</TEXT>
