<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     06-02 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,1st Ld-Writethru, a0475,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lede of 2nd item to DELETE extraneous word; picks up 2nd
item, 2nd graf, ``I have</HEAD>
<HEAD>FDA Approves ``Orphan'' Drug for Anemia Patients</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has approved a genetically
engineered drug that can help reduce anemia in patients suffering
from kidney failure and may also benefit cancer and AIDS patients.
   The drug approved by the Food and Drug Administration Thursday
is a copy of a natural human protein, erythropoietin, which
stimulates the body to produce red blood cells.
   Lack of those cells, which carry energy-giving oxygen around the
body, is known as anemia. And since the kidneys produce
erythropoietin, patients with kidney failure often develop anemia.
   Food and Drug Commissioner Frank Young said that in addition to
about 95,000 kidney patients who should benefit from the new drug,
it also may be useful to chronically anemic patients suffering from
other diseases, such as cancer and AIDS.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Fulton Drops Out of Consideration for HHS Job</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Fulton has dropped out of consideration
for a top welfare post in the Bush administration after strong
opposition from Senate conservatives and anti-abortion advocates.
   ``I have requested my name be withdrawn, but, of course, I don't
do that with any joy,'' Fulton, Oklahoma's social services
secretary, said Thursday.
   Health and Human Services Secretary Louis W. Sullivan, who had
wanted Fulton to head the Family Services Administration which
manages the government's major welfare programs, said he accepted
Fulton's decision with ``profound regret.''
   Fulton was named as a defendant in a 1985 lawsuit alleging that
from 1977 to 1983 several babies born with the severe spinal defect
were denied life-saving surgery at the state hospital. He was
recently dropped as a defendant.
   Fulton, 57, said in Oklahoma City he was ``disturbed about this
type of influence by people who don't mind using smear tactics to
get their objective.''
   ``They misrepresented what has gone on in the spina bifida
controversy in Oklahoma and they were able to scare up alliances
with other groups,'' Fulton said.
</TEXT>
