<FIRST>r i PM-SouthAfrica-Bomb     06-02 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa-Bomb,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bomb Damages Home of Leader of Parliament's Indian Chamber</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb blast today damaged the
home of the leader of the Indian chamber of Parliament but police
said there were no injuries.
   Ebrahim Abramjee, chairman of the House of Delegates, was
visiting Britain with his wife, but his three sons and his
80-year-old mother were at the house when the blast occurred
shortly after midnight in Laudium, a township for Indians outside
Pretoria.
   Windows were shattered, and a wall was badly damaged by the
bomb, which police identified as a Soviet-made limpet mine.
   There was no claim of responsibility, and police gave no
indication who might have been responsible.
   Last month, the home of a white Parliament member of the
governing National Party was damaged by a bomb. There were
unconfirmed press reports that white right-wing extremists may have
been responsible.
   Parliament has segregated chambers for whites, Indians and
people of mixed-race, but excludes the black majority. The Indian
and mixed-race legislators are viewed by many anti-apartheid
militants as government collaborators because of their decision to
seek office rather than join an election boycott when the two
non-white chambers were established in 1984.
   Seats in all three chambers will be contested in a general
election Sept. 6.
</TEXT>
