<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Eases, Gold Firms in Calm Market</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar eased in calm trading this morning
in what dealers described as a readjustment rather than a change in
a long-term trend.
   Gold profited from the dollar's slight decline.
   ``There's a bit of indecision in the market right now as the
dollar tries to find a new bottom,'' said a trader in Milan, Italy.
``But people are only waiting for the new low so they can start to
buy again.''
   Another trader said that a ``nervous'' market on Thursday had
been followed by a ``lazy'' market today.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar closed at 141.80 yen, down from 142.52 on
Thursday. Later, in London, the dollar was quoted at 141.90 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Thursday:
   _1.9715 West German marks, down from 1.9835
   _1.6920 Swiss francs, down from 1.7040
   _6.6900 French francs, down from 6.7185
   _2.2230 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2370
   _1,432.00 Italian lire, from 1,442.50
   _1.2026 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2068.
   In London, it cost $1.5835 to buy one pound, compared to $1.5730
on Thursday.
   Gold opened in London at $362.50 a troy ounce, unchanged from
late Thursday. At midmorning, the city's five major bullion dealers
fixed a recommended price of $362.70.
   In Zurich, the bid was $362.50 compared with $361.85 late
Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold closed at $362.60.
   Silver was quoted in London at $5.22 a troy ounce, unchanged
from late Thursday.
