<FIRST>u i PM-Pope 1stLd-Writethru   06-02 0625</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pope, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0463,0642</SECOND>
<HEAD>PRECEDE Oslo</HEAD>
<HEAD>Pope Calls for Fight Against Materialism</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with pope's speech, details, quotes.
Picks up graf 9 pvs, `Aarflot and ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRONDHEIM, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II today called on Roman
Catholics and Protestants in Europe to fight the forces of
materialism that he said threatened individualism and their
freedoms.
   On the second day of a five-nation tour of Scandinavia, a
stronghold of Lutheranism, John Paul traveled north to this fjord
city of 135,000 people where less than 1 percent of the residents
are Catholics.
   At an ecumenical prayer service in a cathedral that was the
center of Catholicism in pre-reformation Scandinavia, John Paul
emphasized the common roots of Catholics and Lutherans.
   ``As Christians we proclaim a wisdom that recognizes and upholds
the priority of ethics over technology, the primacy of the person
over things, the superiority of spirit over matter,'' the Roman
Catholic leader said.
   ``Before us lies the duty of opening a new Christian chapter in
history in response to the many challenges of a changing world.
   ``Christians understand what is at stake. The history of our own
century clearly shows that where no transcendent norm is
acknowleged, people are in danger of surrendering themselves to
forces which take command of society without concern for
individuals and their freedoms.''
   The papal tour of Scandinavia opened Thursday with a frank
exchange between the pope and Norway's top Lutheran bishop, who
urged the Roman Catholic leader to view Scandinavia's dominant
religion as an equal.
   The five-country, 10-day tour is the first ever by a pope to
this region, where the Protestant Reformation vanquished
Catholicism four centuries ago.
   The meeting between John Paul and Bishop Andreas Aarflot of Oslo
followed a reception by sparse crowds in this country of only
27,800 Roman Catholics.
   John Paul was scheduled to travel later in the day to Tromsoe,
more than 200 miles north of the Arctic Circle for a late prayer
service.
   Aarflot and the pope exchanged speeches in English and applauded
each other's remarks in an hourlong meeting in a hall richly
decorated with tapestries and portraits of Norwegian royalty.
   In his speech, Aarflot said there were many signs that the Roman
Catholic Church is breaking away ``from what many observers and
historians would call its isolation and self-sufficiency through
the centuries.''
   But he said much more needs to be done as far as Lutherans were
concerned. In his response, John Paul pledged that the quest for
unity was an ``irrevocable part of the Catholic Church's life.''
   But, he added, ``Catholics and Protestants must acknowledge that
we cannot yet proclaim a common faith in the mystery of the
eucharist and of the church.
   ``The Catholic position on eucharistic sharing is not meant to
offend our partners in dialogue,'' he said, adding that ``the
eucharist is only to be shared by those in full communion with one
another.''
   With only 200,000 Catholics in the five countries, or less than
1 percent of the population, John Paul was not expected to draw
sizeable crowds as he has been used to during many of his 42
foreign trips in his 10{-year papacy.
   Scandinavian attitudes also contrast with Rome on issues such as
abortion, contraception and divorce, all prohibited by church
teaching.
   A leading Oslo newspaper, the tabloid Dagbladet, published a
caricature Thursday depicting the pope's miter in the shape of a
condom.
   Norway's prime minister, Gro Harlem Brundtland, said she
discussed the problem of fighting AIDS among other issues in talks
Thursday. The Vatican is opposed to the use of condoms to protect
against the spread of the disease and views the issue mainly as a
problem of sexual morality.
  
</TEXT>
</DOC>
