<HEAD>Bush Plants Tree at U.S. Envoy's Home in London</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Ambassador Henry Catto chose an American tree
for the lawn of his home here, and persuaded President Bush to
plant it.
   Bush did the honors today before he ended a week-long European
tour and flew back to the United States. He planted Catto's pin oak
sapling near the rose garden on the grounds of Winfield House, the
ambassador's official residence near Regent's Park.
   The tree, a species native to New England, came from a nursery
in Tunbridge Wells, Kent, in southeastern England. Most of the
trees on Catto's lawn are chestnuts and beeches.
