<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 0734EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Obit-James 1stLd-Writethru   06-02 0689</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-James, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0510,0708</SECOND>
<HEAD>Caribbean-Born Political Historian C.L.R. James Dead at 88</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS six grafs at bottom with biographical details. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   C.L.R. James, a Caribbean-born political
historian, Marxist philosopher, novelist, political activist and
cricket writer, has died at his home above a bookshop in south
London's largely black Brixton district, colleagues said. He was 88.
   The London newspaper The Independent hailed James in an obituary
today as ``probably the most versatile and accomplished
Afro-American intellectual of the 20th century.''
   Writer and television producer Tariq Ali said James died
Wednesday. No cause of death was stated and obituary notices made
no mention of any family members.
   Frail with white hair, lean features and a quavering voice,
James exercised a considerable influence over independence
movements in Africa and the Caribbean after World War II.
   His support for Marxist revolution and sharp criticism of
opponents contrasted with his soft-spoken charm, eloquence and
gentle manner.
   Cyril Lionel Robert James was born at Tunapuna near Port of
Spain, Trinidad, in 1901 and like his father became a teacher.
   Educated at Queen's Royal College, one of the ex-British
colony's top schools, he had an encyclopedic knowledge of English
literature and history and a command of Latin and ancient Greek.
   He left Trinidad in 1932 at the urging of fellow Trinidadian
Learie Constantine, later Lord Constantine, who was then a
professional cricketer and became a political leader in Britain.
   James went to stay with Constantine at Nelson in northwest
England and published his first book, ``Life of Captain Cipriani,''
soon after his arrival.
   The book, about a Trinidadian politician agitating on behalf of
working class people there, was financed by Constantine.
   With the support of British cricket writer Neville Cardus, James
began to write about the game for the northern England newspaper
The Manchester Guardian. He later wrote books about the game, which
had been a passion with him since boyhood days.
   Moving to London later in the 1930's, he became a Marxist and
involved himself in left-wing political causes of the time.
   His close colleague at that time was fellow Trinidadian George
Padmore, a former member of the 3rd Communist International, or
Comintern, founded in Moscow.
   Padmore had been head of the Comintern department responsible
for what it called ``Negro propaganda.'' But in 1935 he broke with
Soviet leader Joseph Stalin and came to London, where he produced a
journal dedicated to African emancipation that James edited.
   James' best-known book, ``The Black Jacobins,'' was published in
1938. With the rise of fascism and the 1936 Italian invasion of
Ethiopia in mind, it told of black revolt in Haiti against French
rule during the French Revolution at the end of the 18th century.
   In a shift of political views, James came to reject Stalin's
brand of Communism, siding instead with Stalin's exiled rival Leon
Trotsky. James and Trotsky met in 1939 in Mexico. Trotsky was
assassinated there the following year at what is thought to have
been Stalin's instigation.
   Soon after publication of ``The Black Jacobins,'' which won wide
acclaim, James went to the United States, having established a
close relationship in London with the black American singer and
political activist Paul Robeson. He and Robeson worked together on
African and Negro issues.
   James spent 15 years in America, addressing books and articles
on political issues to small black, Marxist and labor groups.
   He was expelled from the United States in 1953 during the
anti-Communist campaign headed by the late Sen. Joseph McCarthy and
again became involved in the African independence movement.
   James returned to Trinidad in 1958 at the invitation of Dr. Eric
Williams, the Chief Minister, to edit his party's newspaper and
later became secretary of the West Indies Federal Labor Party.
   But he differed with Williams, left Trinidad and in the 1960s
and 1970s was permitted back into the United States for a series of
college lecture tours.
   He later returned to live in Britain, where a group of admirers,
mostly young and black, gathered around him, heralding him as a
Trotskyite sage. His writing, meanwhile, inspired numerous young
intellectuals in the Caribbean.
   Funeral arrangements were incomplete.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890602-0079 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 0815EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Israel     06-02 0568</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0583</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jewish Settlement Drops `Alien' Tags For Arab Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Jewish settlement on the West Bank dropped
plans today to force Palestinian laborers to wear tags reading
``alien worker'' after the U.S. State Department strongly
criticized the idea as undemocratic.
   Also today, Israeli media reports said the army may restrict the
movement of West Bank settlers suspected of vigilante acts against
Palestinians.
   The reports came hours after troops stopped dozens of residents
of the Jewish settlement Kiryat Arba from raiding the nearby Arab
village of Halhoul to avenge stone-throwing attacks on Israeli cars.
   On Thursday, Kiryat Arba settlers reportedly entered Halhoul,
shooting at homes and smashing windows of cars and houses.
   In another development, peace crusader Abie Nathan was charged
with supporting terrorist organizations because he met in September
with PLO chief Yasser Arafat in Tunisia and France.
   Nathan could face up to three years in prison for violating a
1986 law that bars Israelis from meeting with members of terror
organizations. Israel considers the Palestine Liberation
Organization a terror group.
   Nathan called the law ridiculous and said he has met Arafat
repeatedly since September. ``I'm ready to meet anybody, including
Satan himself, if I find an answer to questions that can save the
life of one person,'' Nathan told The Associated Press. Nathan, 61,
said the charges apparently were filed so many months after his
first meetings with Arafat because of what he described as ``the
lynching mood in this country.''
   Leaders of the Jewish West Bank settlement of Ariel today
reversed an earlier decision to force Palestinian laborers to wear
``alien worker'' badges.
   The new regulations say temporary workers, both Arabs and Jews,
will undergo a security check when entering Ariel and then be
issued a card reading ``security permission to enter Ariel,'' said
Mayor Ron Nachmann. He said workers can carry the cards in their
pockets.
   The initial decision would have required only Arab workers to
wear tags. It drew strong criticism and raised comparisons with the
yellow Star of David that Jews were forced to wear in Nazi Germany.
   On Thursday, Richard Boucher, a spokesman at the U.S. State
Department, denounced the practice as ``offensive.''
   ``In our view, this one settlement's requirement of badges for
Palestinian workers is incompatible with democratic values,''
Boucher said.
   Nachmann rejected the criticism. ``They (U.S. officials)
continue to insult us by calling us `obstacles to peace' and
`occupiers,''' he said.
   Washington's longstanding Middle East policy calls for Israeli
withdrawing from the occupied land in exchange for peace. U.S.
officials have repeatedly said the settlements are an obstacle to
such a solution.
   The army refused comment today on reports that it may restrict
the movement of certain Jewish settlers from Kiryat Arba and the
West Bank towns of Hebron and Nablus who are suspected in taking
part in vigilante raids on Arabs.
   Such restrictions would mainly affect a small group of followers
of the anti-Arab Kach movement in the three areas, the newspapers
Yediot Ahronot and Al Hamishmar reported. Settlers have stepped up
vigilante attacks in recent weeks, firing wildly in Arab villages.
In one raid, a 13-year-old Palestinian girl was shot to death by
settlers.
   Also today, an army officer was sentenced to 14 days in a
military jail for opening fire illegally while dispersing a protest
march at the Tulkarem refugee camp this week, the army said.
</TEXT>
