<FIRST>r a PM-HostageWife 1stLd-Writethru a0524 06-02 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hostage Wife, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0524,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hostage's Wife Lives With Hope, Not Expectations, After Four Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: ADDS 1 graf on others held hostage.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOINA CHIACU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As American Tom Sutherland marks his
fourth year as a hostage in Lebanon, his wife says the Bush
administration has a chance to solve Middle Eastern problems that
got him there.
   ``I live with enormous hope, but no expectations,'' said Jean
Sutherland, who was to attend a ceremony today at Iowa State
University in Ames, where she and her husband first met.
   Mrs. Sutherland said a new administration represents a prospect
for change in how the U.S. approaches the kaleidoscope of problems
affecting Lebanon.
   ``The Bush administration has a chance to do something new after
coming out of eight years in which you have had policy set,
especially after Irangate when things were put on hold,'' she said.
   Sutherland, dean of agriculture at the American University of
Beirut and a former Iowa State student, was abducted on June 9,
1985.
   Mrs. Sutherland said she and her husband were aware of the risks
involved in deciding to go to Beirut five years ago, and she feels
no bitterness or anger toward the U.S. government's handling of the
hostage situation.
   ``I felt that the integrity of our choice really rests on the
fact that we can't ask anybody to get us out of it,'' Mrs.
Sutherland.
   ``I think the issue for our government is that the hostages are
a symptom and symbol of what is wrong in that area and in the
world,'' she said. ``That is something the government needs to get
a grip on and deal with.''
   Mrs. Sutherland has continued to live in Beirut, teaching in a
special English program at American University. She said remaining
there made her feel close to her husband and gave her a sense of
continuing their life together.
   The Ames native said the ISU ceremony, where bells will toll 48
times for each month Sutherland has been in captivity, is special
to her and her husband.
   ``We really appreciate how people have stuck in there for all
these years and offered us their care and concern _ it's been a
lifeline for us,'' she said. ``We'll stick in there, even if we do
go in with no expectations, we still hope that this year is a
decisive one.''
   Before coming to Iowa, she had visited her husband's family in
his native Scotland. She will spend the actual anniversary of his
captivity in Fort Collins, Colo., with her daughters.
   ``What I'm doing is an odyssey for Tom,'' said Mrs. Sutherland.
``I think I'll be going back to Beirut and taking back all the
strength and all the friendships from here.''
   There are eight other Americans still held hostage in Lebanon.
The longest held is Terry Anderson, 41, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press. He was captured March 16,
1985.

</TEXT>
