<HEAD>Sailor's Lawyer To Ask Navy to Clear his Name in Iowa Blast</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: To update with Rubin and Truitt remarks on Today Show, INSERTS
three grafs after 2nd graf bgng, ``Attorney Ellis Rubin ... ''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The attorney for Kendall L. Truitt, the sailor
who was mentioned in connection with the investigation of the USS
Iowa disaster, says he will ask the U.S. Navy today to clear his
client's name.
   Attorney Ellis Rubin of Miami said he also would announce other
demands which he plans to make of the Navy.
   ``We demand somebody in a uniform getting on television or radio
and the print media and explaining to the country that this was an
unfortunate accusation that leaked out, and that the Navy is
apologizing and is also clearing the record of this hero,'' Rubin
said on NBC's ``Today'' program.
   Truitt, appearing this morning on the same program, was asked
whether he believes his reputation has been irreparably damaged.
   He replied: ``I think it's certainly damaged. We're going to be
trying to get it cleared here shortly. We still want an apology
from the Navy.''
   Rubin said he had not received word from the Navy about whether
its investigation of the April 19 explosion had cleared Truitt. ABC
News, however, quoted Pentagon sources Thursday as saying that the
Naval Investigative Service had ruled out involvement by Truitt, a
gunner's mate 3rd class who survived the explosion.
   ABC said Navy investigators had been unable to reach any
conclusion about what caused the explosion, which killed 47 sailors.
   Navy spokesman Lt. Cmdr. James Kudla said Thursday night he
could not comment on the matter because the investigation has not
been reviewed by Navy officials.
   Truitt had been named as a beneficiary of a life-insurance
policy of his friend, Clayton Hartwig, 25, who died in the blast.
   Truitt said last month he wanted the Navy to apologize for
leaking information that implicated him in the explosion. News
reports based on unidentified sources had said investigators were
exploring the relationship between Truitt and Hartwig.
   Truitt has repeatedly denied being involved with the blast. He
and Rubin have suggested the explosion may have occurred when an
inexperienced sailor pushed bags of gun powder too quickly into the
breech of the gun.
