<HEAD>Dying Man Left by Emergency Crews Who Feared For Their Safety</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two paramedics said they abandoned a
dying homeless man in a vacant lot because his friends reacted
angrily to the emergency treatment they tried to administer.
   ``In harm's way, you retreat,'' said Earl Riggs, president of
the Regional Ambulance Service.
   The company's unwritten policy is to leave a scene that might be
dangerous, he added.
   Ambulance company investigators on Thursday questioned the two
paramedics and a paramedic intern, who was a witness to the
incident.
   The man's friends told police the paramedics left him on the
street Wednesday because he was unable to walk unassisted to the
ambulance, but the paramedics said the friends became agitated and
appeared to be picking up rocks.
   The paramedics retreated and waited for police. The man, who
apparently suffered a heart attack, was pronounced dead when he was
taken to a hospital.
   County Emergency Medical Services Director Art Lathrop said he
will review the company's investigation, but he expects the
paramedics to be absolved of any wrongdoing.
