<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 0950EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-TroubledMayor     06-02 0531</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Troubled Mayor,0545</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Says Bradley Involved in Three Drexel Projects</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Tom Bradley took actions on three
projects that stood to benefit Drexel Burnham Lambert while holding
personal investments through the firm, a newspaper reported today.
   Bradley approved Drexel's exemption from a sewer law in a
still-unbuilt $230 million development, made a video sales pitch
for a $26.9 million Drexel deal and gave final authority to allow
Drexel to be lead underwriter on a $190 million city bond issue,
the Herald Examiner reported.
   The report comes as supporters of the embattled mayor say they
fear his plans for the city could be stalled by lengthy
investigations of his personal finances.
   But the mayor's wife, Ethel Bradley, told the Los Angeles Times
her husband is determined to remain in office despite any damage to
his political career. ``All they are out to do is to try to tear
down his reputation,'' she said in an interview appearing in
today's editions.
   Bradley, re-elected to an unprecedented fifth term in April, is
facing the biggest political crisis of his career. Various city,
state and federal authorities are investigating his ties to Drexel
and two banks.
   Bradley refused to comment Thursday on his reported actions on
the three Drexel deals. Drexel spokesman Steve Anreder said he
couldn't locate a company official to comment.
   The mayor has held an investment worth from $10,000 to $100,000
with Drexel since 1979. He said the firm has been his broker in
other, unnamed stock investments.
   While holding these investments, the mayor asked the City
Council to exempt the Pershing Square Centre Associates project
brokered by Drexel from the city's growth-limiting sewer law.
   The City Council approved the exemption last year. The project
was one of only a handful of downtown developments to receive such
an exemption.
   David Houk, PSCA's chief executive, said his firm hired Drexel
in 1987. He said its role in the project had nothing to do with the
exemption and that he did not believe the mayor knew Drexel was
used.
   The amount of money Drexel earned from its involvement in the
project could not be immediately determined. PSCA has filed for
bankruptcy, and the project's future is uncertain.
   In 1984, Bradley appeared in a 12-minute videotape commissioned
by Drexel to persuade limited partners to buy $100,000 interests in
Angelus Plaza, one of the country's largest senior citizen rental
projects. It was not known how much money Drexel earned on that
deal.
   In that same year, Bradley approved a council action allowing
Drexel to join the city's housing bond underwriting team.
   Drexel became the lead underwriter of a $190 million deal to
build 1,916 apartments, the largest housing bond issue ever in the
city. The firm earned $633,333 on the deal, city officials said.
   Some of the Bradley's strongest supporters say his problems may
jeopardize downtown redevelopment and hamper other city projects.
   ``It is important to have a closure of the issue, an array of
the facts, and take whatever action that has to be done, and get it
behind us,'' said Ray Remy, president of the Greater Los Angeles
Chamber of Commerce and a former deputy mayor to Bradley.
</TEXT>
