<FIRST>r i PM-Shakespeare'sTheater     06-02 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shakespeare's Theater,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Developer Unveils New Plan to Build Offices Over Shakespeare Relic</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Developers today announced they would build an
office building on stilts to preserve the remains of the historic
Rose Theater, where William Shakespeare is believed to have debuted
as an actor.
   But protestors who have waged a campaign to save the partly
excavated theater condemned the plan as ``worse than expected.''
   The 10-story office building would stand 22 feet above the
Elizabethan theater's remains and be supported by steel girders,
the developers said.
   The theater's remains would be on view from entrances on three
sides of the office building, they said.
   The government-approved plan for the site south of the Thames
River would cost $15.8 million more than the initial plan and would
reduce some office and parking space, the developers said.
   The remains of the 16th century theater were discovered nearly
six months ago during demolition to prepare for the office
building. The Rose is the only Elizabethan theater ever uncovered.
   Shakespeare is thought to have made his debut as an actor at the
Rose in 1592 and to have acted there in his own play ``Henry VI.''
   The modified development plans were announced by property
company Imry Merchant Developers and the government agency English
Heritage after a vocal preservation campaign by 3,000 actors,
lawmakers and local residents. At one point, actors staged an
all-night vigil to protect the site from bulldozers.
   Simon Jenkins, an English Heritage official, said: ``The Rose
has been saved and people will come and see it. It has not been
cheap for Imry, but we have achieved our objective and the theater
is safe.''
   However, Anthony Grayling, a committee member of the Rose
Theater Campaign, said: ``Our reaction is of very deep
disappointment. The plans are worse than expected because they
threaten to destroy parts of the theater which hasn't yet been
excavated.''
   ``The developers will be going blindfold into something everyone
recognizes to be of tremendous architectural, cultural and
historical significance,'' Grayling said.
   The developers were submitting a planning application for the
scheme to local Southwark Council today, he said. No date was set
for work to begin.
</TEXT>
