<FIRST>r a PM-ChurchClosings     06-02 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Church Closings,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Churches Slated for Closing Sue Archdiocese in County Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of 18 Roman Catholic churches closed or
targeted for closing as part of a reorganization plan have sued the
Archdiocese of Detroit. The lawsuit filed Thursday in Wayne County
Circuit Court seeks an order allowing 16 of the churches to remain
open beyond the June 30 closing deadline so they can appeal
Cardinal Edmund Szoka's decision to the Vatican.
   It also wants Circuit Judge James Hathaway to reopen an internal
grievance process that archdiocesan officials allegedly blocked
earlier.
   The churches are among 30 that have been closed or scheduled to
close as the Detroit archdiocese seeks to reduce overhead costs and
cope with a priest shortage and other problems.
   Two of the parishes already are closed. Mary Ann Waterman, one
of five attorneys who filed the lawsuit, said she hoped both could
reopen.
   Jay Berman, a spokesman for the archdiocese, said the lawsuit
represented harassment of Szoka. He said lawyers for the
archdiocese would seek to have the suit thrown out because it
violated constitutional principles of church-state separation.
   ``We'll go through all of this, and money will be spent on both
sides that could be better used elsewhere and the outcome is
obvious before either side starts it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
