<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 1030EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Clerk-Shooting     06-02 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Clerk-Shooting,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grand Jury to Consider Shooting of Purse-grabbing Suspect</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A store clerk who chased a suspect in a
purse-snatching and then shot him in the back was freed from jail
when a prosecutor declined to bring charges but referred the case
to a grand jury.
   The suspect, David Adams, 22, was in critical condition today in
Methodist Hospital with a bullet lodged in his spine and police
said he may be permanently paralyzed. The shooting occurred
Wednesday evening.
   James E. Mason, a clerk at a supermarket, was released from jail
Thursday after Marion County Prosecutor Stephen Goldsmith said he
would not immediately file criminal charges. A grand jury will
consider whether Mason should be charged.
   In 1985 the U.S. Supreme Court ruled that police officers may
not use deadly force to stop fleeing suspects if the suspects do
not seem to be dangerous. But Goldsmith said ``the law is a little
bit confusing in this area,'' as it applies to private citizens.
   Police said a 68-year-old customer at the supermarket was in her
car while her husband brought out the groceries when a man grabbed
her purse and ran away. The husband asked store employees for help.
   Mason ran inside and told co-workers to call police, then chased
the suspect about 10 blocks in his car, shot the man in the back
and then returned the stolen handbag to its owner. He said later
that he thought the man was pulling out a weapon, but no weapon was
found. He also said he told the man to stop.
   Mason was originally charged by police with battery and
recklessness with a deadly weapon, and held overnight in a a
city-county lockup on $15,000 bond. He was freed when the
prosecutor decided not to bring charges for the time being.
   Police said Mason did not have a license to carry a firearm.
However, no criminal charges have been made on that issue.
</TEXT>
