<FIRST>r w PM-SpellingBee 1stLd-Writethru a0449 06-02 0626</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spelling Bee, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0449,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>To the Victor Belongs the Spoliators</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 7th graf, Scott flew, with 2 new grafs with quotes from
``Good Morning America.'' ^LaserPhoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In January, Scott Isaacs started studying 104
dictionary words a day, the number he could fit on a piece of
computer paper. It paid off.
   Thursday, Scott, a 14-year-old eighth grader from Littleton,
Colo., won the 62nd National Spelling Bee in a spelldown with Ojas
Tejani, 12, a sixth grader from Hixson, Tenn.
   They were the last survivors of a record 222 local and regional
bee winners who were in the field when the national competition
started on Wednesday.
   The final word was ``spoliator.''
   Scott said he had studied the word, which means a spoiler, and
the only thing that made him hesitate over it was whether it ended
with ``er'' or ``or.''
   He made the right choice, and tonight will collect $1,500 at a
prize banquet. Ojas will get $1,000, and others will receive
smaller prizes.
   In an appearance today on ABC's ``Good Morning America,'' Scott
said he had a nervous stomach Thursday morning and ``didn't feel
like getting up on the stage at all.''
   Once he was there, however, he said, ``I started recognizing a
lot more words ... and I just kept on thinking to myself, `Well, if
you can spell a lot of the words that everyone else is getting, you
have a pretty good chance of spelling the words you're getting.'''
   He was also invited today to meet with Vice President Dan
Quayle, along with all of the bee contestants from Quayle's home
state of Indiana.
   He is the 30th male champion or co-champion of the national bee.
Girls have won the crown 35 times.
   This was his third time in national competition. Altogether,
starting in the fourth grade, he has competed in 15 local, regional
and national bees and has won eight of them.
   In 1987 he placed 41st in the national competition, misspelling
psittacine, which means relating to parrots. In 1988, he flunked
telencephalon, a subdivision of the forebrain.
   ``I might be into words when I get older, or I might become a
pilot,'' he told reporters. He said he is thinking of trying for
the Air Force Academy or going to San Jose State College after high
school, but first he would like to be on the staff of the National
Spelling Bee.
   Both Scott and Ojas are engineers' sons. Bud Isaacs is an oil
engineer in Denver and Indian-born Vinay Tejani is a chemical
engineer. The boys' mothers list their occupations as homemaker.
   Scott attends Kent Denver Country Day School and Ojas goes to
St. Nicholas School in Chattanooga.
   Ojas said he studied from 40 minutes to as much as 3{ or 4 hours
a day in preparation for the competition.
   In the final rounds, Ojas correctly spelled ``saponaceous,'' an
adjective for something resembling soap, and Scott countered with
the correct spelling of ``ideaphoria,'' which is a capacity for
creative thought or imagination.
   Both spellers missed ``pasigraphy,'' which means an artificial
international written language. Ojas then missed the next word,
``senescing,'' which means growing old.
   Scott spelled the word correctly and under contest rules had to
spell the next word correctly, which he did.
   Arthur A. Hodge, 14, of Pottsville, Pa., placed third, missing
``trinklied,'' a word meaning a drinking song. Samantha Cassell of
Johnson City, Tenn., stumbled on the word ``pedicled,'' which means
having a slender stalk, and finished fourth.
   The winner's eyes brimmed with tears as he was handed the
championship trophy and friends and relatives came to the stage and
embraced him. He also received a handshake from the runner-up and
Ojas' father.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
