<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 1031EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Germany-Soviet     06-02 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Soviet,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government: Hitler-Stalin Pact on Baltics Still on File</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secret documents deeding the Baltic
nations to the Soviet Union were destroyed by the Nazis, but a
microfilm copy survived and has been inspected by the Soviets,
officials said today.
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, who visits West Germany
in less than two weeks, has called for an inquiry on the shadowy
non-aggression pact between Adolf Hitler and Josef Stalin, and the
subject could come up during his visit.
   Challenging Gorbachev's policy of glasnost, independent groups
have pressed the Kremlin to admit it has been lying for more than
40 years in claiming the three Baltic republics voluntarily sought
Soviet annexation.
   West Germany's information minister, Hans Klein, said the
original non-aggression pact signed by the wartime foreign
ministers, Vyacheslav Molotov of the Soviet Union and Joachim von
Ribbentrop of Nazi Germany, survives in the West German Foreign
Ministry archives.
   But Klein and a Foreign Ministry spokesman, Juergen Chrobog,
said the secret protocols added to the pact to pave the way for
Soviet takeover of Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania were deliberately
destroyed by Nazi officials in the last days of World War II.
   ``However, a microfilm copy of this and other documents was
preserved by a diplomat,'' Chrobog told reporters at a news
conference.
   The protocols to the treaty signed on Aug. 23, 1939, deeded the
Baltic states to the Soviet Union and allowed Nazi Germany to
invade Poland a week later.
   The officials said they did not know details of who preserved
the microfilm that was returned to the West German archives in the
1950s, but they contended the documents shown on the microfilm are
probably the originals.
   ``It's not just presumable, we believe that it is authentic,''
Klein said when asked how Bonn could be sure it had an accurate
copy of the protocols. ``I cannot imagine how or why anyone at that
time would reproduce the documents and then make a microfilm of
them.''
   Klein said two Soviet historians traveled to Bonn a few weeks
ago to examine the documents contained in the microfilm, including
a map that shows the territories divided between the two nations.
   Chrobog was asked to detail the statements included in the
secret protocols but declined, saying their contents were
well-known and had for years been made available to qualified
researchers.
   Gennady I. Gerasimov, Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman, said in
Moscow in August that the Kremlin has no copy of the secret
protocols.
   Soviet officials had asked the West German government about West
German records on the agreement in an ongoing effort to shed light
on the events leading up to Soviet occupation of the Baltic in 1940.
   The so-called Molotov-Ribbentrop agreement has come under close
scrutiny over the past year as Soviet reforms have allowed open
discussion about the controversial takeover and prompted an
official investigation.
   At Gorbachev's urging, the newly assembled Congress of People's
Deputies on Thursday ordered an inquiry into the events leading up
to Soviet annexation of the Baltic states.
   An official Estonian-language newspaper, Voice of the Nation,
published segments of the secret protocols Aug. 10-11, disclosing
in print for the first time that the Baltic takeover was engineered
in collusion with the Germans.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
