<FIRST>r a PM-ChineseSailor     06-02 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chinese Sailor,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Sailor With Appendicitis Rescued From Ship</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STANFORD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chinese sailor suffering from
appendicitis was airlifted from a ship 700 miles off San Francisco
in a dramatic 12-hour rescue by the Air National Guard, officials
said today.
   Guo Jil, 19, was in stable condition today after undergoing an
appendectomy at Stanford University Hospital, where he arrived late
Thursday, said nursing supervisor Darlene Murphy.
   The sailor's arrival at the hospital ended a rescue operation
that began at about 10:30 a.m. Thursday, when a Coast Guard C-130
transport plane from Sacramento dropped three paramedics into the
water near the ship, said Coast Guard Petty Officer Richard
Lieberman in San Francisco.
   The team was taken aboard nearly four hours later and stabilized
Guo until an Air National Guard helicopter flew in three hours
later and made the airlift, Lieberman said.
   The C-130 was sent first because it could get medics to the ship
faster than the helicopter, which had to refuel several times.
   The Coast Guard first received word of the stricken mariner
Wednesday when his ship, the Xiang Cheng, en route from China to
Panama, was about 1,100 miles southwest of San Francisco.
   The team had to wait until the ship was about 700 miles from
land before beginning the rescue, which is usually undertaken no
more than 600 miles from shore, Lieberman said.
</TEXT>
