<FIRST>r i PM-Spain     06-02 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spain,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rail Workers Smash Windows During Strike for Better Pay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government rail workers went on a one-day
strike for better pay today and smashed windows, cut power lines
and blocked railroad tracks, authorities said.
   The walkout is the latest labor dispute involving state employee
groups opposed to the Socialist administration's efforts to keep
pay levels down to contain inflation.
   Also today, workers at the state-run Spanish Television monopoly
ended at midday their 24-hour strike for improved pay. The strike
left many of Spain's television screens showing only test patterns.
   One-day strikes today also were under way at the state telephone
monopoly and the government mint, union and company officials said.
   The RENFE state railroad reported that rail workers disrupted
service during their strike, which began at midnight and involves
63,000 workers.
   Workers delayed the departure out of Madrid and Barcelona of
several long-distance trains for up to 90 minutes early today and
temporarily blocked rail lines in the northern cities of
Valladolid, Zaragoza and Miranda de Ebro.
   Pickets also delayed four short-run trains out of Madrid by
smashing numerous windows, RENFE said. The company also said
pickets in Zaragoza had cut power cables near the city's train
station.
   The company also said 30 percent to 50 percent of regular
commuter trains ran in the major cities but only during the morning
and afternoon rush hours.
   A television union official, Joaquin Aguilar, said on Thursday
the only exceptions permitted to the total blackout were four
20-minute newscasts, followed by obligatory public service campaign
spots for the June 15 European parliamentary elections and an hour
of children's cartoons.
