<SECOND>PM-Amtrak Flushing,0203</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amtrak Charged With Discharging Wastes in River, on Fishermen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALATKA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amtrak trains dumped untreated restroom and
other wastes as they passed over a creek, dousing fishermen below,
said state officials who charged the rail service with three felony
counts of littering.
   ``It is just unfair for people out enjoying the river to be
sprayed with effluent,'' Assistant State Attorney Dennis Bayer said.
   State officials said Amtrak was charged with dumping wastes as
trains crossed trestles at Buffalo Bluff and Rice Creek, a
tributary of the St. Johns River.
   Commercial littering is a third-degree felony under state law
and carries a maximum $5,000 fine.
   Federal regulations governing Amtrak supersede state laws
governing the discharges from toilets and holding tanks on the
trains, Amtrak spokesman Clifford Black said Thursday.
   ``I submit that the alligators in the St. Johns River produce
more effluent in the St. Johns River than an occasional Amtrak
train,'' he said.
   Bayer said Amtrak should comply with state laws and will be
arraigned on the charges before a circuit judge in Palatka later
this month. He said his office had received complaints from
fishermen who were doused by the discharge.
