<FIRST>r i PM-Sudan     06-02 0563</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sudan,0581</SECOND>
<HEAD>Goverment Plane Bombs Air Strip As U.N. Relief Plane Delivers Food</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Sudanese government plane bombed a
landing strip in southern Sudan as a U.N. flight unloaded famine
relief supplies, a U.N. official said today.
   Several civilians were injured in the attack Thursday at the
rebel-held city of Torit, said John Usher, a spokesman for the U.N.
Children's Fund.
   In Kenya, meanwhile, Sudan's foreign minister said his
government will begin peace talks with the rebels June 10 without
requiring any conditions for the negotiations.
   UNICEF is spearheading Operation Lifeline Sudan, a campaign to
deliver food to southern Sudan where 100,000 people are facing
starvation because of a famine caused by the war.
   A U.N. flight had landed on the air strip at Torit and was
delivering supplies when the Sudanese bomber attacked, said Usher.
   As the Sudanese bomber turned to make its second assault, the
U.N. plane took off and escaped safely. Three civilians on the
ground were injured, including a woman whose legs were mangled,
according to U.N. reports.
   The $132 million aid project seeks to distribute food to remote
areas before villages and refugee camps are cut off by rains in the
next few weeks.
   Last year, about 500,000 people died of war-induced starvation
and disease.
   UNICEF director James Grant called in Sudan's U.N. ambassador,
Amin M. Abdoun, to protest the attack. Grant said later that based
on his discussions with Sudanese Prime Minister Sadel Mahdi, he
believes the attack was not ordered by top government authorities.
   Grant requested an investigation of how and why the bombing took
place and wanted assurances it would not be repeated.
   In Nairobi, Kenya, Sudan's foreign minister, Sidahmen Elhusain,
said he had no knowledge of the bombing except what he had heard on
news reports. He called it ``an isolated incident.''
   Torit fell to the rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army on Feb.
26 and has become a major redistribution center for Operation
Lifeline Sudan.
   The Sudan People's Liberation Army is fighting for autonomy for
the three southern provinces, which are populated mainly by
Christians and animists.
   The Moslem-dominated government based in Khartoum has attempted
to impose Islamic law on the nation.
   Peace talks between the government and the Sudan People's
Liberation Movement are to begin June 10 in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia.
   Elhusain said there would be no conditions set on the talks. He
brushed aside rebel complaints that the government still has not
met an earlier peace accord that called for abolishing the
country's strict Moslem legal code.
   The foreign minister spoke at a news conference during a visit
to neighboring Kenya which he said was meant to brief President
Daniel arap Moi on the peace process and seek his help.
   Abolishment of the Moslem code is one of the primary aims of the
rebels, but Elhusain said the purpose of the Addis Ababa talks was
to work out a means of achieving that and other goals.
   A previous pact between the government and the rebels on Nov. 16
called for elimination of Moslem law, the lifting of a state of
emergency and a permanent cease-fire in the 6-year-old civil war.
   Elhusain said Mahdi ``is in support (of the November accord) and
is pushing it fully.'' He said the government would make a
``serious, genuine, consistent'' effort to end the conflict.
</TEXT>
