<HEAD>American Author Frederic Prokosch Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American writer Frederic Prokosch died today after
a heart attack at his home at Plan de Grasse in southern France,
his French publisher, Fayard, said. He was 81.
   Prokosch wrote several works of fiction and poetry during his
60-year career, including his best-selling first novel, ``The
Asians,'' published in 1935. Other works include ``The Seven
Sisters'' and ``The Missolonghi Manuscript.''
   Prokosch was born May 17, 1908, in Madison, Wis., and was
educated at Yale University and King's College in Cambridge,
England.
   ``Voices,'' his memoir published in 1983, described his
encounters with Bertold Brecht, Marc Chagall, Colette, James Joyce
and Andre Malraux.
