<HEAD>Bush Arrives Home, Buoyed by Success on European Stage</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: tops with 6 grafs Bush arrival; picks up 6th graf pvs, The president;</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precedes LONDON</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTSMOUTH, New Hampshire (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush arrived home
today after his foreign policy debut on the European stage, leaving
U.S. allies cheering his leadership at the NATO summit and bringing
``a message of hope'' for the American people.
   ``We have a great and historic opportunity to shape the changes
that are transforming Europe,'' the president said. ``In this
period of historic change, the NATO alliance has never been more
united, never been stronger.''
   On his return from London, Bush was greeted at Pease Air Force
Base by a crowd of about 2,000 people including hundreds of
flag-waving schoolchildren.
   Buoyed by positive reaction to his disarmament proposals, Bush
told the crowd: ``I am now returning from Europe with a message for
the American people _ a message of hope.''
   ``We must get to work now to end the Cold War. The world has
waited long enough,'' he said.
   Bush will spend the weekend at his oceanside retreat near here
at Kennebunkport, Maine, returning to Washington late Sunday.
   The president arranged separate meetings Monday with his Cabinet
and with Democratic and Republican congressional leaders to assess
the results of his week-long tour of Rome, Brussels, Bonn and
London and the prospects for negotiated reductions in conventional
NATO and Soviet-led Warsaw Pact forces.
   ``We will spare no effort to achieve agreements that will reduce
the risk of war and strengthen the foundations for peace,'' said
White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater.
   Bush capped his trip Thursday night by having dinner with
British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher at 10 Downing Street.
Afterward, Bush declared, ``NATO is strong. We are showing a very
solid front.''
   As Bush's black limousine pulled away, Mrs. Thatcher approached
reporters and said, ``We're very much together.''
   Asked if Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev was trying to
divide the NATO alliance, Mrs. Thatcher said, ``He wouldn't
succeed. NATO is strong and the alliance is firm.
   ``We're not going to have our defenses undermined,'' she added.
   In a dinner toast, the prime minister assured Bush, ``You always
will be able to count on Britain when there is danger, when you
need us. That's why the relationship is so special.''
   Bush called Mrs. Thatcher a prime minister ``who holds the reins
of history.''
   He noted ``it was in this very city that a little more than a
century ago Karl Marx died, leaving behind ideas that were to bear
his name.''
   A succession of British prime ministers and American presidents
worked ``to stem Marxism at full tide,'' Bush said. Now ``we can
explore possibilities for peace that would have seemed widely
unrealistic just a handful of years ago.''
   ``We seek to free Europe from the shadow of Soviet military
power,'' he said.
   The farewell dinner, attended by a phalanx of British
celebrities and sporting stars, capped a week filled with praise
from Western allies for America's new president.
   The final day of Bush's trip was filled with colorful pageantry.
   Before dinner with the prime minister, the president and his
wife Barbara went to Buckingham Palace for lunch with Queen
Elizabeth II.
   When Bush's limousine pulled up to the red-carpeted Grand
Entrance of the palace, Bush jumped out. But nobody opened Mrs.
Bush's door until the queen, frowning and shaking her head, raised
her voice and said: ``Open it.''
   A U.S. Secret Service agent complied immediately and Mrs. Bush,
wearing an emerald green dress, emerged smiling as though nothing
had happened.
   Earlier in the day, Denis Thatcher, the prime minister's
husband, gave Mrs. Bush a gallant kiss on the hand when he greeted
her at 10 Downing Street.
   When photographers clamored for a repeat, a playful Mrs. Bush
clasped Denis Thatcher's hand and planted a kiss on it.
   Bush's staff was buoyant about positive reviews of the
president's performance.
   ``I hope that it might put to rest some of that speculation''
about Bush being too timid, said Secretary of State James A. Baker
III.
   ``It is important, I think, that an American president be seen
to be leading the alliance,'' he said.
   With Thatcher's support, Bush won approval of a NATO communique
against early negotiations to reduce or eliminate short-range
nuclear missiles in Europe. He also got an endorsement of his
proposal for reducing American and Soviet combat troops in Europe
to 275,000 each.
   European newspapers gave Bush high marks, although many noted
that he acted only after Gorbachev dominated the public opinion
stage for months with his disarmament proposals.
   In Amsterdam, the left-leaning Dutch de Volkskrant said: ``The
image of George Bush as a president lacking a vision on the
development of the peace and disarmament process in Europe must be
corrected.''
   The Times of London, an independent daily, wrote that Bush ``has
proved an important point this week _ that he can change up a gear
when the international going demands it.''
   But the independent Swiss daily Le Matin said Bush's optimism
may be unfounded. ``This charm operation runs the risk of rapidly
getting bogged down in the details of the Vienna negotiations''
over conventional forces in Europe, it said.
   Bush spent his final day polishing relations with Thatcher.
There are strains over U.S. military aid to Argentina, which fought
and lost a war with Britain earlier this decade over the Falkland
Islands.
   Washington and London also are at odds over South Asian ``boat
people.'' About 750 are arriving daily in Hong Kong and the
Thatcher government would like to stem the flow and send some back
to Vietnam and Cambodia.
</TEXT>
