<FIRST>r i AM-Bangladesh     06-02 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bangladesh,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Killed in Bomb Attacks by Tribal Rebels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rebels exploded bombs in the markets of
two towns in southeast Bangladesh, killing at least four people and
injuring 12, police said Friday.
   Police officials, contacted by telephone from Dhaka, said the
bombs were set off Thursday by members of rebel Chittagong hill
tribes who oppose local elections scheduled this month.
   The officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said at
least four people were killed in Khagrachari, 110 miles southeast
of Dhaka.
   At least 12 people were injured in a blast in the neighboring
town of Rangmati, they said.
   The Chittagong tribes have been fighting a 14-year-old bush war
to protest what they consider the erosion of tribal values by
Moslem settlers from other parts of the country.
   The government blames the tribes, who are mostly Buddhist, for
about 4,000 killings since the violence began.
   Last month, President Hussain Muhammad Ershad offered the rebels
amnesty and ordered elections for semiautonomous administrative
councils in the Chittagong region, which encompasses about 5,200
square miles of hilly jungle on the border with India.
   The rebels have refused to settle for anything short of total
autonomy and oppose the elections, scheduled June 25.
   Government officials say at least 5,000 tribespeople have fled
to neighboring India in the past two weeks to escape violence they
fear will break out during the election.
</TEXT>
