<HEAD>Twenty-three Burned in School Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-one students and two teachers at a technical
school were burned Friday when the aluminum they were casting
exploded, police said.
   The explosion occurred at the Mie Technical Development Center
in central Japan, about 190 miles west of Tokyo, as students were
heating aluminum rods.
   One student suffered third-degree burns, while the other
students and two teachers received first- and second-degree burns.
Two of those hurt were hospitalized, said a police spokesman.
