<DOCNO> AP890602-0117 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 1257EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-Alar     06-02 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Alar,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Manufacturer Says It Is Taking Chemical Off Market Immediately</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The manufacturer of Alar announced today it is
taking the chemical off the market immediately in this country
because of the furor over its use in apple products and public
concern about its health effects.
   In announcing the decision, the Uniroyal Chemical Co. insisted
that the chemical is safe, but said it has become ``the focus of a
needless controversy'' that is severely harming the apple industry
and ``causing doubt and confusion about the safety of America's
food supply.''
   The Environmental Protection Agency has concluded that
daminozide, as the chemical is technically called, causes cancer
and earlier this year urged that it be taken off the market.
   Alar is a growth regulator that enhances the appearance of
apples and increases their shelf life. The EPA estimates that it is
being used on 5 percent to 15 percent of the apple crop.
   Apple growers applauded the decision by Uniroyal.
   ``This action is most welcomed ... since it will allay any
remaining concerns consumers may have about small levels of Alar in
apples and apple products,'' said Larry Davenport, executive
director of the Processed Apples Institute.
   The apple industry in recent months has urged that Alar be taken
off the market because concern about its use has caused sharp drops
in apple and apple product sales.
   James A. Wylie, vice president and general manager of Uniroyal
Chemical, told a news conference that its customers who have
purchased Alar are being notified that they may return the product
and be reimbursed.
   The decision applies only to U.S. sales of the chemical. It
would not effect Uniroyal's sale of Alar outside the United States,
including in some countries such as Chile whose apple products are
exported to the United States.
   ``Daminozide is a safe product. It has been used safely for 20
years and with great benefit to American consumers,'' said Wylie.
He accused critics of Alar's use as waging ``a fear campaign'' that
has no justification.
   The chemical ``has become the focus of a needless controversy
that is causing doubt and confusion about the safety of America's
food supply _ a needless controversy that is hurting the apple
industry and the American public,'' said Wylie.
   Many growers have stopped using the product since concern about
it health effects gained widepread attention earlier this year.
Wylie, although not providing any specific production figures, said
sales of Alar in the United States have dropped as much as 75
percent.
   Earlier this year, a report by the Natural Resources Defense
Council, a private environmental group, concluded that young
children are particularly at risk from Alar and a variety of
pesticides used on fruits and vegetables because they consume large
amounts of apple products, other fruits and vegetables.
   Although government officials maintained that levels of Alar in
apples are safe, many parents questioned whether they should
continue to provide apple products to their youngsters. School
districts in a number of major cities for a time stopped providing
apples in school lunch rooms.
   Janet Hathaway, an attorney for the Natural Resources Defense
Council, said the Uniroyal decision represents ``a capitulation to
public opinion'' but that consumers could continue to be exposed to
the chemical because it will continue to be sold outside the United
States including in countries that export apple products to the
United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
