<FIRST>r i PM-Iraq-Kurds 1stLd-Writethru a0571 06-02 0683</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iraq-Kurds, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0571,0699</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Ask U.N. to Halt Iraq's Forced Relocations of Kurds</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 16th pvs, ``Iraqi officials...'' with 3 grafs to UPDATE
with reaction from Iraqi envoy. Pickup 17th, ``The Kurds...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraqi troops have resumed the forced
evacuation of thousands of ethnic Kurds, a Kurdish rebel leader
said today, calling for international help to stop the relocations.
   All 10,000 people who live in the northern Iraqi town of
Twasoran were forcibly evacuated by Iraqi troops on Wednesday,
according to a statement attributed to guerrilla leader Masoud
Barzani and read to The Associated Press by a spokesman who
insisted on anonymity.
   On Thursday, Iraqi government troops supported by tanks entered
the town of Qala Diza to begin its enforced evacuation, ``but the
people resisted the deportation order and went on a general
strike,'' the statement added.
   ``The whole region is now in a state of high tension, and we
feel that the army will massacre the civilian population,'' it said.
   Worldwide criticism earlier this year apparently forced the
Iraqi government to announce it was shelving a plan to forcibly
move the Kurdish population from Qala Diza and nearby villages to
crush the protracted Kurdish struggle for autonomy or independence.
   The Baghdad government originally had set April 25 as the
deadline for moving the Kurds out of Qala Diza, 15 miles west of
the Iranian border, before razing the city.
   The same Kurdish spokesman said last month the Iraqi authorities
had distributed leaflets and forms to the Kurdish population of the
region saying they would be transported to unknown destinations
within 20 days.
   The tough Kurdish warriors, known as Peshmerga, or ``those who
face death,'' were supported by Iran during the war with Iraq and
managed to seize control of large areas of their rugged mountain
homeland.
   But the Iraqi army has cracked down heavily on them since the
Aug. 20 cease-fire in the Persian Gulf war in a bid to crush the
rebellion.
   ``The scale of the new displacement program is alarming as it
involves the destruction of the remaining rural district towns in
Kurdistan and the forced resettlement of nearly 300,000 people,''
said the Barzani statement.
   It added that ``the affected people will be interned in camps
and towns, located outside traditional Kurdish areas, in southern
Iraq.''
   ``We appeal in the name of humanity to the U.N.
secretary-general, governments and national and international
organisations to intervene.''
   An estimated 500,000 Kurds have been forcibly moved from their
mountain villages within the past three years, mostly to tent camps
in the sweltering southern desert near the Kuwaiti and Jordanian
borders, diplomats reported.
   More than 4,000 Kurds were killed last year in an Iraqi poison
gas attack on the city of Halabja, an incident that caused an
estimated 100,000 Kurds to flee to neighboring Turkey and Iran.
   As many as 3,000 villages have been razed in an effort to cut
off the guerrillas from their supporters, the diplomats added.
   Iraqi officials admit they have carried out large-scale
relocations among the Kurds. But they deny Kurdish claims of
genocide and have said the moves were for security reasons and to
provide the Kurds with modern homes.
   There was no comment on today's report by officials in Baghdad.
But Iraq's ambassador to Paris, Abdul Razzek Al-Hashemi, denied
Kurds were being forcibly evicted from their villages, the official
Kuwait news agency reported today.
   KUNA, monitored in Nicosia, quoted the envoy as saying all
people in villages along the Iranian border were asked to move to
more secure areas. He said Kurds are being resettled in model
villages within their autonomous area and are not being moved to
other districts of the country, the agency said.
   The Kurds, who have been fighting the Baghdad government for
decades recently formed an alliance known as the Iraqi Kurdistan
Front to unite six groups. Barzani signed his appeal on behalf of
this front, the spokesman said.
   There are about 20 million Kurds living mainly in Iran, Iraq and
Turkey, with small pockets in Syria and the Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
