<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 1304EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SomethingFishy     06-02 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Something Fishy,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Hands Over Three Tons of Frozen Fish to Food Bank</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER MATTIACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Something was very fishy when the boxes said
it was orange roughy and government inspectors said it was mere
smooth oreo dory.
   The food bank that got it for free just said thanks.
   The Justice Department, acting under orders from U.S. District
Judge Paul A. Simmons, turned over 248 cases, or about three tons,
of frozen fish fillets to the Greater Pittsburgh Community Food
Bank on Thursday.
   Acting U.S. Attorney Charles D. Sheehy said the fish was seized
by U.S. marshals April 3 because it was mislabeled as expensive
orange roughy when it was actually less-expensive smooth oreo dory.
He said the two fish look and taste alike.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Amy Reynolds Hay said Food and Drug
Administration agents were tipped in March that the mislabeled fish
was being stored for an unidentified shipper at the New Federal
Cold Storage warehouse in Pittsburgh. She said it arrived Feb. 10.
   Government officials filed a civil forfeiture complaint against
the shipment on March 30, charging that the fish had been
mislabeled in interstate commerce, a violation of the Federal Food,
Drug and Cosmetic Act.
   When no one claimed the fish, Simmons ordered it forfeited to
the government and donated to a food bank, officials said.
   Sheehy said the McKeesport-based food bank supplies nearly 300
food pantries, shelters, soup kitchens, home-delivery programs and
community sites in Allegheny County.
   Sheehy said New Federal Cold Storage waived its charges when it
learned the fish was being donated to charity.
</TEXT>
