<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Pikul     06-02 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Pikul,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Wall Street Analyst Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GOSHEN, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joseph Pikul, a former Wall Street
securities analyst who was convicted in March of murdering his
second wife, died this morning, his attorney said. He was 54.
   Pikul's doctor told his third wife that Pikul died of heart
failure stemming from cancer of the liver and small intestine,
attorney Ronald Bekoff said.
   Pikul, confined in the Orange County Jail without bail following
his second-degree murder conviction, was admitted to Arden Hill
Hospital in poor condition after fainting last Friday, said his
third wife, Mary Bain Pikul.
   An autopsy was planned, but hospital officials did not know when
it would be done. Neither hospital nor police officials would
comment of the nature of Pikul's death.
   A jury convicted Pikul of murdering his 44-year-old second wife,
Diane, on Oct. 24, 1987. Pikul said he killed his wife when she
attacked him with a knife after a quarrel over an unfamiliar brand
of condoms he'd found under her bed.
   Prosecutors said her beating and strangulation were motivated by
Pikul's fear of losing the couple's two children and by Mrs.
Pikul's threats to blackmail him because she had pictures of him
wearing women's clothing. Police say Pikul was wearing women's
undergarments when he was strip-searched after his arrest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
