<FIRST>r a PM-Congressman-Degree     06-02 0162</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congressman-Degree,0166</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Congressman Receives Honorary Doctorate 31 Years After Admission
Denied</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TROY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state university that 31 years ago refused
to admit John Lewis because he was black awarded the congressman an
honorary degree today.
   Lewis, D-Ga., was given the honorary doctor of laws degree by
Troy State University Chancellor Ralph Adams. Lewis, who made no
remarks during spring commencement, was applauded by some 700
graduates and audience members.
   Lewis is a native of Pike County, where Troy State is located.
He has said that in 1958 he applied for admission to what was then
Troy State College, but never received a response from the then
all-white school.
   Lewis said he joined the civil rights effort after sending a
letter about his experience to the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr., who
already was a recognized leader in the movement.
   Officials at Troy State have said they had no record of Lewis'
application or others from that period.
</TEXT>
