<FIRST>u w PM-GOP-Lukens 1stLd-Writethru a0515 06-02 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-GOP-Lukens, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0515,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lukens Says He Won't Resign Despite Calls By GOP Leaders</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Tops with 4 grafs with Lukens statement; SUBS penultimate graf
for first reference to Jarrell.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede COLUMBUS, Ohio</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ohio Republican Rep. Donald E. Lukens said
today that despite calls for his resignation by GOP leaders, he
will stay in Congress while he appeals his conviction a week ago of
having sex with a 16-year-old girl.
   ``If I have caused pain and embarrassment to my family, friends
or supporters, I apologize,'' Lukens said in a statement released
at his Capitol Hill office. ``But I refuse to allow the lies and
deceit of one delinquent individual to ruin me. I am now fighting
for my life.''
   Lukens' statement contended his accuser had a ``10-year record
of psychological problems and illegal activity'' but the court
refused to listen to the evidence.
   ``My legal counselors assure me that prospects for a reversal in
my case are excellent. Only at that time will I make my final
decision regarding any future political activity,'' he said.
   Lukens, 58, was convicted May 26 of a misdemeanor charge of
contributing to the delinquency and unruliness of a minor following
a five-day trial in Franklin County Domestic Relations Court. A
jury found Lukens guilty of having sex with a girl at his Columbus
apartment Nov. 6 when she was 16.
   Ohio Republican Party Chairman Robert Bennett and GOP leaders
from Lukens' home district on Thursday urged Lukens to resign from
Congress and from the Republican State Committee.
   Meanwhile, a Columbus television station reported Thursday that
a teen-age girl said she also had sex with Lukens in 1985 when she
was 15.
   WSYX-TV said the girl, identified only as ``Paris,'' had been
sought by the grand jury to testify in Lukens' case but was not
found. The station said Lukens paid the girl for sex on five or six
occasions.
   Franklin County Prosecutor Michael Miller told the AP the girl
interviewed on television had refused to cooperate with the
investigation that led to the charges against Lukens. He said he
didn't plan to reopen the investigation.
   A conviction of a misdemeanor does not prohibit a congressman
from remaining in office or seeking re-election.
   But state GOP chairman Bennett said he informed Lukens' office
Thursday that he will not be on the party's ticket in 1990. He said
he spoke with Lukens Wednesday night and conferred with party
leaders in the congressman's western Ohio district before making
the decision.
   ``I think he is a bad apple for the Republican Party,'' Bennett
said. ``He has lost the support of the entire Republican leadership
of his district.''
   Don Birgel, chairman of the Butler County GOP in Lukens'
district, said Lukens should resign because ``a party is known by
the leaders it keeps.''
   Lukens wasn't bitter at party leaders, but doesn't plan to take
their advice, said William Jarrell, Lukens' chief of staff.
   ``This is a ... move where the party distances itself from
Lukens. They have their own pressures they have to react to,''
Jarrell said. ``Congressman Lukens came into politics as as a
fighter, and right now he is ... fighting for his life.''
</TEXT>
