<FIRST>u w PM-Thornburgh-Gray 1stLd-Writethru a0579 06-02 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Thornburgh-Gray, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0579,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attorney General Says Leakers May Be Fired</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: ADDS three grafs to update with Biden and Thornburgh comments.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Richard Thornburgh said today
that any Justice Department employees found to have leaked
information about an investigation into the office of Rep. William
Gray, D-Pa., would face the risk of being fired.
   ``They have no place in the Department of Justice,'' Thornburgh
told the Senate Judiciary Committee.
   Thornburgh came to Capitol Hill to discuss the role of the
American Bar Association in the judicial selection process.
   But Chairman Joseph Biden, D-Del., immediately asked Thornburgh
about a report that FBI agents visited Gray concerning an
investigation involving his office.
   Thornburgh said he has requested the No. 2 man in the Justice
Department, Edward Dennis, to investigate how the information
reached the news media.
   ``He will have available to him whatever resources are necessary
to pursue these reports,'' Thornburgh said.
   The attorney general said that if the ``perpetrators'' were
discovered it was likely that ``they will be fired immediately.''
   Thornburgh was critical of ``our friends in the news media'' for
airing reports of the investigation. He also said he wished that
journalists would help find the leakers.
   ``It's extremely difficult to pursue these investigations
without the cooperation of those in the news media,'' he said. ``I
can say without fear of contradiction that if we did have the
cooperation of the news media in these investigations, every leaker
in town would be gone before sundown.''
   Thornburgh said it was possible that there may have been
criminal conduct involved in unauthorized disclosures in the news
media. He did not elaborate on that theme.
   Prompted by Biden, Thornburgh promised to report back to the
Judiciary Committee on the results of the investigation and tell
the panel what methods it had used to come up with its findings.
   Biden urged Thornburgh to assign the investigative task to the
department's Office of Professional Responsibility.
   He noted that Dennis formerly was a U.S. district attorney in
Philadelphia and said he would not advise ``putting Mr. Dennis, a
fine, honorable man, in the position of having to investigate
people he hired.''
   At one point in the proceedings, Thornburgh described the news
media as ``aiders and abetters'' of unauthorized disclosures of
sensitive information. He told reporters in a hallway later,
though, ``It was perhaps an ill-chosen word.''
</TEXT>
