<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Shipyard     06-02 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Shipyard,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Businesswoman Pledges Up to $100 Million for Shipyard</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GDANSK, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Polish-American businesswoman has
pledged to invest up to $100 million in a deal that could rescue
the imperiled Lenin Shipyard, where Solidarity was born, a union
spokesman said Friday.
   Barbara Piasecka-Johnson, heir to the Johnson &amp; Johnson
pharmaceutical fortune, told shipyard officials and Solidarity
leader Lech Walesa on Thursday that she intended to form a joint
venture with the yard, said Piotr Konopka, Walesa's spokesman.
   The government announced six months ago that it planned to close
the yard because it was not profitable.
   But Walesa said the decision was politically motivated and
promised to find a way to save the yard, where Solidarity was
founded during a strike in 1980. The government said it would not
block a plan to restructure the yard if financial support could be
found.
   Under the joint venture, the yard would continue to build ships
with the goal of making a profit for Mrs. Piasecka-Johnson and the
shipyard, Konopka said.
   Mrs. Piasecka-Johnson said in a telephone interview that she was
``very pleased'' with the talks.
   ``I think it is a good time to invest in Poland,'' said Mrs.
Piasecka-Johnson, who lives near Princeton, N.J. ``The shipyard has
a great potential to produce wonderful ships and I thought it would
be a great thing to do. The shipyard workers are wonderful.''
   The partners would form an enterprise called the Gdansk Shipyard
Co. Ltd., in which she would hold 55 percent of the shares and the
shipyard 45 percent, Konopka said.
   He said the enterprise plans to obtain the necessary guarantees
to operate from the Polish finance minister and begin operating on
Jan. 1.
   Solidarity was formed in the shipyard after an 18-day strike.
Solidarity became the East bloc's first independent trade union.
   The government banned the union in a martial law crackdown in
December 1981. It was legalized again on April 5 as part of an
accord reached after the government and opposition held talks.
</TEXT>
