<SECOND>PM-Cancer Boy, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0498,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Father Returns with Cancer-Stricken Boy; Mother Freed from Jail</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with judge allowing boy to travel
to Texas for treatment; Picks up 4th graf, `Deutsch returned ...'; DELETES
grafs 8-12, `Deutsch gave ...' to tighten.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cancer-stricken boy who had been ordered into
a hospital over the objections of his parents was released back
into their custody today in an agrement under which he will be
taken to a cancer clinic in Texas.
   ``I pray God the youngster will be able to obtain such treatment
that is good for him,'' said Family Court Judge Leon Deutsch, who
announced the settlement. ``I pray God he will make a complete
recovery.''
   The boy, his mother and a lawyer for the city are to make the
trip Sunday to the M.D. Anderson institute at the University of
Texas in Houston.
   The agreement was reached with the city, the parents and the
judge, who on Thursday returned the 4-year-old boy to
Memorial-Sloan Kettering Cancer Center, from which his father took
him in violation of a court order.
   The father, Steven Pagan, 36, surrendered with his son, Darian,
on Thursday after hearing that his wife, Migdalia, had been jailed
because of his action.
   Deutsch returned Darian to the custody of the city's Child
Welfare Administration and Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center.
He ordered an examination of Darian but specifically prohibited
doctors at Sloan-Kettering from administering any treatment without
his consent.
   The dispute began when the parents objected to a planned
chemotherapy treatment, which could be painful.
   The judge imposed a 10-day suspended sentence against Pagan for
contempt of court and freed Mrs. Pagan, 35, who had spent the last
two nights in jail.
   ``Their feelings are confusion, relief and apprehension,'' said
the parents' lawyer, Steven Mandel. ``They still have a child with
leukemia and this is something no parent should have to go to
through.''
   Darian was hospitalized last Friday under an order from Deutsch
that was requested by the Child Welfare Administration because
hospital officials said the boy was not getting the treatment he
needed.
   The city became involved in the case after doctors from
Sloan-Kettering called them and said Darian was in imminent danger
if he did not receive a radical form of radiation and chemotherapy,
which the parents had resisted.
   The Pagans, who live in Brooklyn, are Jehovah's Witnesses, a
religion that opposes blood transfusions. But Mandel said their
religion did not play a part in the court case.
</TEXT>
