<FIRST>r w AM-ConventionalForces     06-02 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Conventional Forces,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Levin Suggests Reducing U.S. Forces in South Korea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A member of the Senate Armed Services
Committee on Friday suggested reducing U.S. forces stationed in
South Korea and requiring the Japanese to foot the full bill for
keeping American troops in Japan.
   ``The United States can no longer sustain a disproportionate
burden of maintaining a common defense for the free world,'' said
Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich. He is chairman of the Armed Services
subcommittee on conventional forces and alliance defense.
   In an interview with reporters, Levin also proposed deferring
the funds for construction of a new base in Crotone, Italy, to
house the 401st Tactical Wing.
   Last year, the United States accepted Spain's demands that the
Air Force withdraw its 72 F-16 jet fighter bombers, approximately
3,600 troops and 600 civilians from Torrejon de Ardoz, just east of
Madrid.
   Italy has agreed to provide a new home for the wing at a cost
for the NATO allies of about $830 million. The United States is
expected to pay about $26 million.
   ``It makes pure common sense to defer the authorization and
appropriation for a new base when it may turn out those troops are
going to be gone from Europe altogether,'' Levin said referring to
President Bush's proposal this week to cut NATO and Warsaw Pact
forces.
   During the 40th anniversary meeting of the alliance, Bush
proposed a ceiling of 275,000 on U.S. and Soviet ground and air
force personnel, which would require a reduction of about 30,000
U.S. troops and about 325,000 Soviet troops.
   Levin said he will make his proposals in the form of a ``sense
of the Senate'' resolution which reflects the Senate's sentiment
but has no legal authority.
   Specifically, Levin is proposing that the Bush administration
discuss with South Korea a timetable ``for a mutually acceptable
... partial reduction of our forces'' and a plan to replace the
U.S. commander who has operational control over Korean forces with
a South Korean general.
   The Michigan Democrat estimated that the more than 40,000 U.S.
troops could be reduced to about 10,000.
   Levin also suggested that Japan pay the total cost for
stationing U.S. troops there and pick up part of the tab for basing
troops elsewhere in Asia. Currently, Japan pays for between 60 and
70 percent of the total cost, or about $2.5 billion, Levin said.
</TEXT>
