<DOCNO> AP890602-0143 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 1440EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Not-So-HotFudge     06-02 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Not-So-Hot Fudge,0622</SECOND>
<HEAD>Venerable Ice Cream Parlor, Inventor of Hot Fudge Sundae, Under New
Ownership</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gourmet ice cream king Joey Crugnale didn't see
any future in chopped ham and pickle sandwiches.
   Old women called up and implored him to reconsider. After a
wearying morning of shopping, they wanted to come in to Bailey's,
peel off their white gloves and have a dainty sandwich or a hot
fudge sundae _ as they always had done.
   But Crugnale had made a fortune with a yuppie, trendy, gourmet
ice cream chain called Steve's (named for a chap Crugnale had
bought out) and had begun a yuppie, trendy, gourmet pizza chain
called Bertucci's.
   So he decided to ignore his older customers and apply the trendy
formula to Bailey's, a 116-year-old chain of candy and ice cream
stores that had invented the hot fudge sundae, reportedly kept
files on the preferences of prominent customers, and supplied
chocolates to three U.S. presidents.
   It didn't work, as a sadder-but-wiser Crugnale himself admits.
Now, the chain's new owners, who bought him out last fall, are
trying to bring it back.
   While he was owner in 1987 and 1988, Crugnale eliminated the
traditional sandwiches _ chopped ham and pickles, peanut butter and
bacon, datenut bread and cream cheese. He made the stores brighter,
airier, more modern, instead of dark and cool with mahogany and
marble. He fired many longtime employees.
   ``Joey Crugnale, he didn't like old things, so he just threw
them out,'' said Frank Wyman Jr., a former Bailey's owner.
   Crugnale bought the seven stores and a candy factory in January
1987 for a reported $1.5 million. When he sold it 20 months later
for an undisclosed price, it was down to two stores, both in the
suburbs.
   ``I think the company lost its focus and it became more of a
luncheon stop as opposed to an old-fashioned candy store and ice
cream parlor,'' said one of the new owners, Michael Mazzaferro.
``We want to restore it to its roots.''
   While they are not ready for rapid expansion, Mazzaferro and his
two brothers, whose family has been in the candy business for
decades, said they hope soon to reopen stores in Boston and
Cambridge, perhaps through franchising.
   Bailey's dates to the 1870s, but its most famous history was
written in this century. Sarah Dow, bookkeeper for founder John
Bailey, took over his shop in 1900 when he retired and is credited
with inventing the hot fudge sundae.
   ``She put 6 ounces of ice cream in a five-ounce dish and poured
1{ ounces of hot fudge on top of it, and it dripped down onto the
silver dish,'' Wyman said with reverence. ``Beautiful concept.
Beautiful product.''
   Later, Bailey's supplied mail-order chocolates to Theodore
Roosevelt, Calvin Coolidge and John F. Kennedy. Joe Kennedy, the
late president's father, was one of those who kept his candy
preferences on record at the flagship store at the edge of the
Boston Common, which had lost its lease and gone out of existence
before Crugnale bought the chain.
   Crugnale, 37, who built Steve's Ice Cream from one store to a
chain of 26 before selling out in 1983, says his experience before
he bought Bailey's made him overconfident.
   ``I thought I was superman _ I did Steve's, I could do
anything,'' he said.
   Though humbled by his failure with Bailey's, Crugnale has
bounced back by expanding Bertucci's into a chain of 12 pizzerias
in Massachusetts and Rhode Island.
   Bailey's ``was a mistake from the beginning,'' he said. ``But
I'm not ashamed of it. I learned a lot from it.''
</TEXT>
