<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-OilFire     06-02 0176</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Oil Fire,0181</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Platform Burning in Caspian Sea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet fireboats have been trying for four days to
put out a fire on a Caspian Sea oil platform, which was rocked by a
series of explosions that sent flames 80 feet into the air, Pravda
reported Friday.
   A fireboat rescued all 24 workers aboard the deep-water platform
when it exploded about 100 miles from Baku, the capital of the
southwestern republic of Azerbaijan, the newspaper said.
   Part of the metal structure fell into the sea after the second
of three blasts on the No. 2 platform in the oil field called
``April 28,'' Pravda said.
   A storm that whipped up 30-foot waves and winds up to 65 mph
made firefighting especially dangerous for boats and helicopters
trying to save the men and equipment, the newspaper reported.
   It did not say when the fire started.
   On Friday, four fireboats and 28 water guns still were battling
the blaze on the platform, which normally produces thousands of
tons of oil a day, Pravda said.
</TEXT>
