<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 1614EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-SpendingBill     06-02 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spending Bill,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Hopes to Finish Domestic Spending Bill Next Week</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate set its sights Friday on finishing
a $3.3 billion ``dire emergency'' spending bill next week after the
legislation bogged down under a load of amendments.
   In about three hours Friday, lawmakers worked their way through
several non-controversial amendments, ranging from resuming food
aid to Haiti to financing University of Wyoming research of last
summer's fires at Yellowstone National Park. The session followed a
nearly 14-hour day Thursday.
   The Senate then recessed until Tuesday, when it will consider
several proposals likely to spark lengthy debate. They include
provisions delaying the start of catastrophic care programs for the
elderly and repealing a tax law regulating employee benefit
programs.
   Senate Appropriations Committee Chairman Robert Byrd, D-W.Va.,
has shown impatience with the pace of work on the bill. After
another senator thanked colleagues for coming to the floor for
debate, Byrd responded, ``That's where we ought to be. We're
getting paid for it.''
   The so-called dire emergency spending bill, first requested by
President Bush in March, is designed to finance agencies running
low on funds for fiscal 1989's final four months.
   It includes $1.2 billion for cost-of-living benefit increases
and health care for veterans, $892 million for loans for college
students, and money for foster care, food stamps, the expenses of
fighting last year's Western forest fires and other programs.
   But as routinely happens with spending measures, the legislation
has attracted provisions that has little to do with programs
running out of money and much to do with lawmakers seeing a chance
to help their states or favorite causes.
   Thus, the Senate approved a provision Friday urging the
Agriculture Department to buy more apples to help an industry hurt
by findings that alar, a growth enhancer sprayed on the fruit, can
cause cancer. The measure was sponsored by Sens. Brock Adams,
D-Wash., and Slade Gorton, R-Wash., who represent one of the
country's top apple growers.
   An amendment by Sen. Malcolm Wallop, R-Wyo., was adopted
directing the spending of $800,000 for the study of last summer's
Yellowstone fires, some of which would be conducted by the
University of Wyoming.
   Also approved was a provision by Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla.,
permitting up to $12 million worth of U.S. food aid to go to Haiti.
Most assistance to that country has been halted because of human
rights abuses there, but Graham said improvements have been made.
</TEXT>
