<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Urban     06-02 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Urban,0610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man With `Disquieting' Ears Running for Parliament Against Solidarity</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   His catchy televised campaign video makes
fun of his ears and calls them ``disquieting.''
   It's not your typical political message, but former government
spokesman Jerzy Urban _ a man Poles love to hate _ is carrying out
his fight for a parliament seat with his trademark style of
combining irreverence, self-mockery and sarcasm.
   The point man for seven years in the government's propaganda
campaign against the Solidarity trade union, Urban was among the
first Polish officials to announce his candidacy in Sunday's
elections for parliament and the new Senate.
   Despite eight years of loyal service to the communist
authorities, justifying martial law, and belittling Lech Walesa as
``the former head of a former union,'' Urban _ now information
minister _ is running as an independent.
   It is the kind of provocative behavior that irritates much of
Poland's population but keeps people tuned in to see what he will
do next.
   Facing Urban for the Warsaw seat is popular actor Andrzej
Lapicki, who has received Solidarity's endorsement. The opposition
says its polls show Lapicki ahead by 7-to-1.
   But the outcome could be much different because of the large
number of ballots expected to be cast by Poles abroad, whose votes
all are counted in the district.
   There are about 140,000 eligible voters in the district itself
and some 600,000 abroad. Many may feel compelled to vote the
government way because they work in embassies or as contract
workers in communist or Middle Eastern countries.
   Poles got to know Urban when, as the government's spokesman, he
conducted weekly news conferences that were televised nationwide.
He was promoted to head state television and radio the day
Solidarity became legal again, April 17.
   In the early days of his campaign, Urban used coupons in
official newspapers to collect the requisite 3,000 nominating
signatures, angering the opposition. He also managed to get letters
printed and inserted into most mailboxes in his district.
   His distinctive appearance makes him easily identifiable.
   He is a small, round man with a perfectly circular bald pate and
distinctively large ears. A humorous music video on Urban that
appeared on state TV _ which Urban controls _ delighted in calling
attention to his ears.
   As a popular singer sang refrains of, ``Strange ears had he,
strange hears had he,'' viewers could see Urban as a child,
teen-ager and young man; circles drawn around his ears on the
photographs made them look even larger.
   ``Everyone knows who I am,'' Urban said at a campaign meeting
with students.
   The first few editions of the new opposition newspaper Gazeta
Wyborcza contained so many articles concerning Urban that one
letter writer opposed to Urban felt compelled to remind editors to
avoid ``Urbanophobia.''
   A longtime journalist and satirist who was associated with Prime
Minister Mieczyslaw Rakowski's liberal party weekly Polityka, Urban
became government spokesman in 1981. He gave his first news
conference the day martial law was imposed in December of that year.
   As government spokesman, Urban frequently cited polling data
showing more than half the population disapproved of him but that
his news conferences were the highest rated weekly show on
television.
   Ryszard Straus, a longtime aide in the government spokesman's
office, said Urban believes polls showing him behind are
exaggerated.
   In a country where many of the rulers are gray and humorless,
Urban stands out. Some argue that he is provocative to draw public
ire that otherwise might be directed at others.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890602-0154 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 1703EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Scandal     06-02 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Scandal,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>Recruit Scandal Started with Him; He Goes Free</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Japan, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Recruit scandal scuttled many careers and
toppled a government, but authorities said Friday that the man
first investigated for alleged participation will not face charges.
   The Yokohama District prosecutor's office announced it will not
indict Hideki Komatsu, former deputy mayor of Kawasaki, on bribery
charges, Kyodo News Service and television reports said.
   Officials could not be reached for comment Friday evening.
Komatsu, who was fired as deputy mayor two days after the Asahi
published its story, also could not be reached.
   The Recruit scandal emerged last summer when the Asahi Shimbun
newspaper reported that Komatsu allegedly had bought stocks in a
real estate firm before they were offered publicly and sold them at
a huge profit after they were listed.
   Reporters were tipped off by police who said they were
investigating Komatsu.
   He was sold stock in Recruit Cosmos, a subsidiary of the
conglomerate Recruit Co., apparently to sweeten a land deal in
Kawasaki, just south of Tokyo.
   In the following months, Recruit Co. helped about 160
influential politicians, bureaucrats and businessmen to make such
lucrative deals. Prosecutors have charged 17 people with bribery or
violating laws on securities or political donations.
   Friday evening news programs, after reporting Sousuke Uno's
election as prime minister to replace Noboru Takeshita's
scandal-tained government, showed an official of the Yokohama
prosecutor's office saying Komatsu would not be indicted.
   The official said Komatsu accepted the stock but that the act
fell short of bribery because Komatsu could not have anticipated
that the shares' price would rise so dramatically.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
