<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     06-02 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seventeen Sinhalese Slain in New Violence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen tied up 17 Sinhalese and shot
them to death in a series of attacks nationwide that appeared to be
orchestrated, military officials said Friday.
   The bodies of eight young men, their hands tied behind their
backs, were found Thursday by workers at a plantation in the
central Sri Lankan city of Beragala, the officials said, speaking
on condition of anonymity.
   Beragala is 45 miles northeast of Colombo.
   Four bodies were found Thursday in the southern town of Matara,
72 miles south of Colombo, and five bodies were found in Kurunegala
district, 36 miles northeast of the capital, they said.
   They said all the men were killed in similar fashion but did not
give details.
   Independent sources said the executions were carried out by
pro-government vigilante groups that previously killed members of
an anti-government Sinhalese extremist organization. The sources
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The ultranationalist Sinhalese militants are opposed to the
government's peace overtures to Tamil rebels who are fighting to
set up an independent nation in the country's northern and eastern
areas.
   Meanwhile, police in Colombo fired tear gas shells Friday to
stop about 500 Moslem demonstrators from marching to the Indian
High Commission, or embassy.
   The marchers were protesting the alleged inaction of Indian
peacekeeping troops during clashes between Moslems and Tamil
militants in eastern Sri Lanka last month. At least 12 people died
in the clashes.
   The peacekeeping troops are stationed in the northern and
eastern regions to enforce law and order under the terms of an
India-brokered peace accord of July 1987 that aimed to end the
Tamil rebellion.
   Tamils, mostly Hindus, make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16
million people and claim they are discriminated against by the
Buddhist Sinhalese majority in jobs and education.
   Sinhalese comprise 75 percent of the population and dominate the
government and the military. Moslems make up 7 percent of the
population.
   The nearly 7-year-old Tamil separatist campaign has claimed more
than 9,000 lives. At least 3,500 people have died in the Sinhalese
backlash.
</TEXT>
