<FIRST>r i AM-SAfrica-CrowdKilling     06-02 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-Crowd Killing,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>12 Sentenced For Mob Killing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twelve blacks convicted of
involvement in the mob killing of a black police officer were
sentenced on Friday to prison terms of up to eight years and parole.
   Fourteen defendants in the highly publicized case were sentenced
last week to hang.
   Only one of the 26 defendants was found to have physically
contributed to the death of officer Lucas Sethwala, who was stoned
and set on fire on Nov. 13, 1985, in Paballelo, a black township
outside Upington in a remote area in northwestern South Africa.
   One defendant was convicted of attempted murder and the other 24
of murder under the doctrine of common purpose, which holds
individuals responsible for the actions of a crowd if they are part
of the group.
   The day of the killing about 3,000 blacks gathered on a soccer
field in the township to protest rent increases and other actons by
township authorities.
   Police dispersed the crowd, and most went home peacefully. About
300, however, regrouped and attacked Sethwala's home, according to
testimony.
   Judge Jan Basson said the killing was politically motivated and
part of a conspiracy to attack township authorities.
   Of the 12 people sentenced Friday, two were sentenced to eight
years in prison and four to six years; the others received
suspended sentences.
   Defense lawyers have said they will appeal the case.
</TEXT>
