<FIRST>r a AM-Presbyterians     06-02 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Presbyterians,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>Presbyterians Ponder How Christians Can Meet Issues Of 21st Century</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Presbyterian church must tackle such
complex issues as the effect of medical technology on the quality
of life if Christians are to face the uncertainties of the future,
a prominent educator told church leaders Friday.
   ``There is no question that the 21st century will be different
from the 20th,'' Roger Heyns told a symposium of the Presbyterian
Church (U.S.A.).
   For example, he said: ``It is probably not intelligent to resist
technological development. It is possible, however, to question
whether the determination to prolong life, regardless of the
quality of that life, is a desirable consequence of our
technological capacity to do so.''
   Heyns, former chancellor of the University of California at
Berkeley and later president of the American Council on Education,
was the keynote speaker for ``Continue the Journey: Symposium on
the Future'' being held this weekend on the eve of the church's
201st General Assembly.
   The week-long assembly begins Tuesday and will involve 622
voting delegates and an estimated 10,000 participants and observers
overall.
   The church, which traces its roots in the New World back more
than 400 years, has nearly 3 million members. Its first General
Assembly, marking the beginning of a new church organization in a
young nation, was held in Philadelphia in 1789.
   Among the items on the agenda for the voting delegates is the
selection of a new church moderator, or head.
   In his speech, Heyns said the future holds ``instability and
uncertainty' because of ``current domestic problems of enormous
complexity, such as AIDS, homelessness, and the continued presence
of an inequitable distribution of wealth.''
   ``The church has both a conservative and a radical role'' to
play in dealing with such problems, he said, because the church
must help form moral standards equal to the changes that will come.
To do that, he said, churches must stay in touch with reality by
listening both to God and to people.
   ``They get into serious trouble when they get out of touch with
either,'' he said.
   He also said the values set through the church must be flexible.
   ``For the church to be vital and relevant, the subject of what
is important to conserve and what is important to change must be
under constant study and lively debate,'' he said.
</TEXT>
