<HEAD>Rescuers Search for 21 Trapped in Cave-In and Fire</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MLA3</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescuers hampered by rain and
shifting ground searched on Friday for at least 21 people still
missing since landslides and a fire struck a remote gold-mining
community, officials said.
   The military and civil defense officials said 11 people were
killed in the twin disaster last Tuesday. A regional mines official
said the count included three men whose bodies had not been
recovered.
   Heavy rains caused a caused the collapse of a maze of tunnels on
the slopes of Mount Diwalwal in Davao del Norte province in the
southern Philippines. A blacksmith's charcoal fire was overturned,
starting a fire that destroyed at elast 180 shanties of miners and
traders, officials reported.
   Mario Luis Jacinto, regional director of the Bureau of Mines in
Davao City, said more than 500 people initially reported buried in
the landslide had been accounted for by late Thursday.
   ``The problem is ground movement,'' he said. ``Rock masses have
not settled down and working there is very dangerous.''
   Jacinto said cracks showed on the tunnel walls as early as five
hours before the cave-in, giving most miners enough time to get out.
   Landslides are common in this area 530 miles southeast of
Manila. Tens of thousands of gold prospectors have tunneled through
Mount Diwalwal since the early 1980s.
