<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-US     06-02 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-US,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Change in Relations Expected Under Uno</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Japan Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANICE FUHRMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Sousuke Uno will continue existing
policies toward the United States and other countries, and will not
ease his tough response to U.S. trade actions against Japan,
officials said Friday.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Taizo Watanabe pledged ``consistency
and continuity'' in foreign policy from the new administration.
   Parliament chose Uno, 66, as the prime minister Friday and he
promised political reforms to avoid a recurrence of the Recruit
bribery scandal, which forced the resignation of Noboru Takeshita.
   Watanabe said Uno, foreign minister for the 19 months of
Takeshita's tenure, ``has been a cornerstone of Japan's
relationship to the United States.''
   Uno will represent Japan at the Paris summit of seven
industrialized nations in July and may visit the United States
before then.
   He has had tough words about the U.S. designation of Japan as a
potential target of trade sanctions. Using the new American trade
law to force concessions from Japan is ``like negotiating with your
fists up,'' he told a news conference Friday.
   The prime minister, a former head of Japan's Trade Ministry,
said he told U.S. trade representative Carla Hills in Paris earlier
this week that ``Japan and the U.S. are allies and allies are
supposed to trust each other.''
   ``We don't think Uno's position will change now that he has
become prime minister,'' Watanabe said.
   At the Paris meeting of the Organization for Economic
Cooperation and Development, other leading industrial powers issued
a statement implicitly criticizing the U.S. decision to name Japan,
Brazil and India as possible targets for retaliation under its
trade law.
   Japan's ambassador to the United States, Nobuo Matsunaga, will
leave Washington on Monday for a week of consultations with the new
government in Tokyo, Watanabe said.
   Although he said such consultations were routine when a new
government took over, Matsunaga was the only Japanese envoy called
home.
   The ambassador will brief officials on ``the current situation
in the United States and overall U.S.-Japan relations,'' Watanabe
said.
   ``Japan's relationship with the United States is on a sound
basis,'' he said. ``We are determined to solve any economic or
politial problems. No problems are insoluble.''
