<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 1957EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Suriname     06-02 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Suriname,0319</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Seize Power Station, Threaten to Blow it Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARAMARIBO, Suriname (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guerrillas seized a hydroelectric
power station and threatened to blow it up unless President
Ramsewak Shankar agreed to meet them.
   Shankar met senior government officials in the National Assembly
on Friday to discuss what action to take, including sending the
army to take back the station.
   About 40 guerrillas, led by a notorious rebel leader known only
as Barabas, occupied the unguarded Afobaka hydroelectric power dam
on Thursday, then demanded by telephone to speak with Shankar or
other top government officials. Other threats they made were to cut
power to the capital or open the dam's flood gates.
   Before taking over the station, the rebels hijacked a busload of
26 workers of the Suriname Aluminum Co. returning from a shift at
the power plant. The rebels threw the workers off the bus and drove
off with it.
   In a televised speech Thursday night, Shankar called the
situation serious and said measures would be taken to resolve it.
He did not elaborate.
   Hit-and-run activity by the rebels has increased during the last
three weeks in the area around the power station, 125 miles south
of Paramaribo, capital of this Dutch-speaking South American nation
of 400,000 people.
   The attack came as the assembly was debating an amnesty bill in
a move to end the guerrilla war that began in 1986.
   Guerrillas led by Ronnie Brunswijk originally demanded the
ouster of junta leader and army commander Desi Bouterse, but
continued attacks against the army after Bouterse allowed free
elections in November 1987 and then stepped down.
   Brunswijk has pledged to negotiate peace with the government,
but Barabas and other renegade rebel leaders have continued attacks.
   Bouterse retained his army command and is still considered a
major power broker in Suriname, which gained independence from the
Netherlands in 1975.
</TEXT>
