<FIRST>r a AM-Citizens'Arrest     06-02 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Citizens' Arrest,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Workers Charged With False Imprisonment of Teen-age Theft Suspects</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AURORA, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two auto salvage workers who caught three
13-year-olds in a theft face false imprisonment charges after tying
up one of the boys and handcuffing and stuffing the other two into
a car trunk, police said.
   John Voth, owner of Action Auto Wrecking, said the Wednesday
night incident grew out of several years of frustration at having
thieves pilfer more than $100,000 worth of parts from his business.
   ``These guys are coming out here and taking me apart and I'm not
getting any help from anybody,'' Voth said. ``This has been
reported to police as an ongoing problem for several years. What
went on out here was only as a last resort.''
   Officers went to the isolated lot late Wednesday and found
lights on, a gate open and people running through the yard, said
police spokeswoman Mary Schumacher. Police then contacted Voth who
said employees Larry Wayne Henson, 29, and his brother, Richard
Henson, 32 had caught three boys stealing radiators and other car
parts.
   The Hensons had one boy tied up, but the two who Voth said they
had handcuffed escaped from the trunk of a junked car, apparently
with the help of a fourth person, Schumacher said.
   One of the youths later phoned police about the incident from
his home, Schumacher said.
   Larry Henson was issued a criminal summons for false
imprisonment and assault, and Richard Henson for false
imprisonment, Schumacher said.
   The three juveniles were charged with largency from yards.
</TEXT>
