<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 1700EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Thornburgh-Leaks     06-02 0628</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thornburgh-Leaks,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attorney General Threatens Firings Over Leaks, Chides News Media</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh threatened
Friday to fire Justice Department leakers but also criticized the
news media as ``aiders and abettors'' in publicizing unauthorized
information on a controversial story.
   He expressed the wish that journalists would share with federal
officials the names of their sources on the story and said that if
reporters would name anonymous sources, ``every leaker in town
would be gone before sundown.''
   Thornburgh, on Capitol Hill to testify on another matter, was
questioned about possible leaks leading to recent stories saying
Rep. William Gray's office personnel practices are under Justice
Department scrutiny.
   Gray, of Pennsylvania, the fourth-ranking House Democrat, has
complained vigorously about leaks and has asked for appointment of
an independent counsel to look into the matter.
   The attorney general has rejected that demand, but he told the
Senate Judiciary Committee he has appointed the No. 2 man in the
Justice Department, Edward Dennis, to seek the source of
unauthorized disclosures.
   ``He will have available to him whatever resources are necessary
to pursue these reports,'' Thornburgh said. He said that if the
``perpetrators'' were discovered it was likely ``they will be fired
immediately.''
   Thornburgh described ``our friends in the news media'' as
``aiders and abettors'' in the case but later said, ``That was
perhaps an unfortunate choice of words.''
   He raised the possibility that criminal laws may have been
violated in the release of word about the investigation but said
the news media appeared to be merely exercising their rights under
the Constitution.
   Thornburgh declined to say what laws may have been violated but
did not rule out the possibility of prosecuting the leakers.
   ``It's extremely difficult to pursue these investigations
without the cooperation of those in the news media,'' he said. ``I
can say without fear of contradiction that if we did have the
cooperation of the news media in these investigations, every leaker
in town would be gone before sundown.''
   Asked later what he meant by cooperation, Thornburgh said,
``Consenting to be interviewed and disclosing the source of the
leak.''
   Jane Kirtley, executive director of the Reporters' Committee for
Freedom of the Press, took strong issue with Thornburgh's words
about reporters and anonymous sources.
   ``News gathering is protected by the First Amendment and to say
that this is something the news media should not be engaging in is
trampling on the First Amendment,'' she said.
   ``What I find so troubling about his remarks is the notion that
the news media has a responsibility to keep the government's
secrets for the government. That's the antithesis of what is the
news media's responsibility.''
   ``He is trying to do what the Reagan administration did so
brilliantly _ to make it appear you are unpatriotic if you don't
cooperate with the government on these investigations,'' Kirtley
said.
   Thornburgh was on Capitol Hill to report to the Judiciary
Committee on a long-running dispute with the American Bar
Association over judicial selection.
   Committee chairman Joseph Biden, D-Del., however, immediately
asked him about published reports of an investigation into
personnel practices within Gray's office.
   The reports based on news leaks surfaced as Gray is running for
the House leadership post of majority whip.
   Urged by Biden, Thornburgh promised to report back to the
Judiciary Committee on the results of his deputy's investigation
and to tell the panel what methods had been used.
   Biden urged Thornburgh to assign the investigative task to the
department's Office of Professional Responsibility.
   He noted that Dennis formerly was a U.S. district attorney in
Philadelphia, where Gray is the congressman, and said he would not
advise ``putting Mr. Dennis, a fine, honorable man, in the position
of having to investigate people he hired.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
