<FIRST>r w AM-Byrd-Cambodia     06-02 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Byrd-Cambodia,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senator Urges Agreed, Non-Secret Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., urged the Bush
administration Friday not to arm non-communist guerrillas in
Cambodia secretly but rather to seek an accord with Congress on an
open U.S. policy there.
   ``There is much at stake here and it seems inadvisable to engage
in secret deals, secret policy, secret aid, and repeat the mistakes
of the very recent past,'' Byrd told the Senate.
   ``A policy review is clearly in order,'' said Byrd, the former
majority leader who now chairs the Appropriations Committee.
   ``If we are to re-engage in Southeast Asia let us do so,'' he
said. ``But let us do so only after thorough, open debate, with
discussions of options and the careful formulation of a new U.S.
policy in concert with other nations that wish to bring long-term
peace and stability to Cambodia.''
   Vietnam announced last April 1 that it will end its 10-year
occupation of Cambodia and withdraw all of its military forces by
next Sept. 30.
   American and Asian policy makers fear that in the resulting
vaccuum, forces of the radical Khmer Rouge may regain power and
resume the massacre widely believed to have claimed ther lives of
more than one million Cambodians during their 1973-1978 rule.
   During the years of the Vietnamese occupation, the United States
has helped in the international effort to feed the estimated
300,000 refugees on Cambodia's border with Thailand and, since
1985, has provided some non-lethal aid to non-communist factions in
the country.
   Byrd noted published reports this week that the Bush
administration is considering mounting a covert operation to supply
non-communist forces in Cambodia with rifles and other weapons.
   A principal beneficiary of such aid would likely be Prince
Norodom Sihanouk, a previous ruler of the country, who is seeking a
leading role in the government of post-occupation Cambodia.
   But some congressional leaders fear that military aid will fall
instead into the hands of the Khmer Rouge which is allied with
Sihanouk in efforts to topple the Vietnamese-supported government.
   Byrd said that U.S. hopes for an independent, sovereign and
non-communist Cambodia cannot be achieved through secret arms
transfers.
   ``It is inconceivable to me how anyone could think that a new
military aid program in Southeast Asia could be successful or
sustainable without building a strong national concensus to support
it,'' Byrd said.
   ``There is no short cut, no easy back door which can circumvent
and make unnecessary the building of a knowledgeable consensus for
new long-term U.S. policies in a region which has been purposefully
bereft of such policies since our involvement in Vietnam ended so
catastrophically,'' he said.
   ``Southeast Asia is fraught with too many memories, too much sad
history, too much spilled blood, for the United States to back into
a commitment, with no sense of where that commitment may lead,'' he
said.
   Byrd said that the current situation in Cambodia suggests that
``active, inventive, international diplomacy mgiht be considered
and might be fruitful.''
   ``An active American diplomatic role might well find a receptive
audience, and that is an option that I believe would find the
greatest amount of support from the American people,'' Byrd said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
