<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 1716EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador     06-02 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador,0556</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cristiani Wants Regional Effort to End Salvadoran War</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Alfredo Cristiani, in
his first full day in office, called Friday for a regional effort
to end his nation's leftist revolution and said it was as crucial
as dismantling the Nicaraguan rebels.
   Also Friday, insurgents denied they owned a huge arms cache
displayed as materiel captured from rebels. The exhibition is
``psychological warfare,'' they said.
   Jose Napoleon Duarte, the staunch U.S. ally who retired after
five years as president, traveled to Washington for cancer
treatment Friday. Duarte, 63, is dying of liver cancer.
   And the army's monthly duty orders, published Friday, show a key
clique of colonels consolidated its power.
   Cristiani, leader of the rightist Arena party, gave a press
conference in the presidential palace.
   He said the nine-year Salvadoran revolution is a regional
problem and should be dealt with in the context of the 1987
Esquipulas II regional peace plan.
   Under the plan, the five Central American presidents agreed in
February to promote the demobilization of Contra rebels based in
Honduras.
   Cristiani acknowledged the Contra plan ``has a head start. We
have no problem with that going ahead. But we would like to see
equal treatment given to the Salvadoran problem and progress there
too.''
   He reiterated accusations that Nicaragua's leftist regime helps
arm the Salvadoran rebel Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front.
   Nicaragua says it provides only moral support to the guerrillas,
known as FMLN.
   Cristiani said he will bring up the issue of alleged Nicaraguan
intervention during a Central American summit tentatively scheduled
for July.
   ``We hope that Nicaragua will cut its links with the FMLN,'' he
said.
   The armed forces Tuesday exhibited nearly 400 Soviet-designed
AK-47 assault rifles, 50 Soviet-made grenade launchers and piles of
other munition. Military spokesmen called it the biggest logistical
blow to the rebels in years.
   But the insurgents, on their clandestine radio, said it was a
show staged to implicate Nicaragua and ensure continued U.S.
military aid. El Salvador receives more than $1 million a day in
U.S. economic and military assistance.
   According to the army's June orders, the graduating class of
colonels known as ``La Tandona'' consolidated its power, retaining
or gaining command of seven of the eight army brigades. The
colonels are not likely to modify significantly the current
strategy of ``low intensity conflict.''
   The selection of Cristiani's defense minister deeply divided the
armed forces last week.
   Cristiani and other senior Arena party officials favored
hard-line air force commander Gen. Rafael Bustillo, according to
military and political sources. Col. Rene Ponce, in charge of the
joint chiefs of staff, also aspired to the portfolio.
   Because their rivalry threatened to split the armed forces,
sources said Gen Humberto Larios was chosen as a compromise
candidate. But he is considered a stopgap.
   Bustillo, who it is thought would escalate the conflict sharply
if he had charge of defense, reportedly is supported by key
colonels who do not belong to the ``tandona.''
   Ponce leads the ``tandona,'' and command changes announced
Friday make it likely he eventually will win the contest for the
Defense Ministry, which is expected to change hands in about six
months.
</TEXT>
