<FIRST>r i AM-SatanicVerses     06-02 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Satanic Verses,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iran's President Calls For More Anti-Rushdie Protests in Britain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Ali Khamenei of Iran urged
Moslems in Britain on Friday to stage more demonstrations against
British author Salman Rushdie and denounced the arrest of 84
protesters in London last weekend.
   ``We support the movement of our Moslem brothers in Britain, and
encourage them to follow up on their freedom of speech,'' the
official Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in Nicosia, quoted
Khamenei as saying in his Friday sermon at Tehran University.
   ``The great movement of British Moslems is the perfect example
that Moslems have been awakened by the message of the Islamic
revolution, and no power can stop this awakening.''
   Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, Iran's revolutionary and spiritual
patriarch, issued a religious edict on Feb.14, calling on Moslem to
kill the Indian-born writer. He said Rushdie blasphemed Islam in
his novel ``The Satanic Verses.''
   Demonstrations in central London by about 20,000 Moslems from
around Britain flared into violence last Saturday. Six police
officers were hurt and 84 protesters were arrested.
   Protesters waved anti-Rushdie banners and demanded his death.
They asked that blasphemy laws be changed so Rushdie's novel could
be challenged in court.
   Tehran-London ties were cut following Khomeini's death call.
   In Madrid, a Spanish business group that includes small
booksellers issued a statement Friday strongly criticized three
major department store chains for failing to put on sale the
Spanish edition of ``The Satanic Verses.''
   The Confederation of Small and Mid-Size Businesses said the
stores of the El Corte Ingles, Garcia Celso and Galerias Preciados
chains acted out of fear and condemned the action as
``incomprehensible and representative of a total lack of commercial
ethics.''
   In separate statements, the three chains denied that they
jointly decided not to sell the book. They affirmed their right to
choose what they sell, but said no definitive decision had been
taken.
</TEXT>
