<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-NATO     06-02 0145</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-NATO,0149</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shevardnadze Praises, Criticizes Bush Arms Proposal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze on Friday
praised President Bush's latest arms control proposal as serious,
constructive and largely approaching the Soviet position.
   But he complained that 100,000 troops of other NATO powers on
West German territory are not included.
   The proposal has ``a definite imprint of new times,''
Shevardnadze said in an interview with Soviet correspondents
carried on the official news agency Tass the same day Bush returned
home from a European visit.
   NATO adopted Bush's suggestion to propose a ceiling of 275,000
troops for the United States and the Soviet Union in Europe. The
plan also calls for certain arms cuts to equal levels.
   Shevardnadze noted the NATO and Warsaw Pact proposals now agree
on tanks and armored vehicles, and their suggestions for limits on
artillery and combat helicopters are very close.
