<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 2023EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Argentina     06-02 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Argentina,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Official Calls New Argentine Government Anti-Semitic</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel expects a large influx of Jews from
Argentina ``because the new regime is anti-Semitic,'' the
immigration minister said Friday.
   Rabbi Yitzhak Peretz, the minister, told a new conference
growing numbers of Argentine Jews had approached the Jewish Agency
in Buenos Aires.
   His reference was to the government of President-elect Carlos
Menem, a member of the populist Peronist Party, who is of Syrian
descent. Peretz did not elaborate on the statement or provice
evidence to support it.
   Menem was elected last month and is scheduled to take office in
November.
   The daily Jerusalem Post quoted Jewish Agency officials as
saying they expect immigration from Argentina to double this year
to about 3,000, but the newspaper said the main reason was the
severe economic crisis, not anti-Semitism.
   Argentina's currency has lost all but a fraction of its value
and inflation is about 70 percent a month. At least 14 people were
killed in food riots this week.
   Many Jews planning to immigrate to Israel ``can't afford a plane
ticket to another country and we have to help them with basic needs
such as clothes and suitcases,'' the newspaper quoted a Jewish
Agency official as saying.
   The demand for agency assistance to leave Argentina has been so
great that applicants must wait three weeks before even meeting
with a staff member, the official was quoted as saying.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
