<FIRST>r i AM-UN-IranResistance     06-02 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Iran Resistance,0590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iranian Resistance Says Hundreds Left U.S. to Fight Khomeini</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of Iranian exiles left the United
States during the past year and went to Iraq to join the fight
against Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's regime, leaders of Iran's
main resistance group said Friday.
   About 1,000 anti-Khomeini Iranians rallied outside the United
Nations in a demonstration organized by the Washington-based
People's Mujahedeen (holy warriors) of Iran.
   There has been a power struggle in Iran to select a successor to
Khomeini, the nation's 86-year-old spiritual leader who is
recuperating in a Tehran hospital from abdominal surgery.
   Mujahedeen leaders said Iran's ecomony is in a shambles after
the eight-year war with Iraq, and government repressions continue
with hundreds of executions.
   ``It proves Khomeini's regime has no chance to stay in power,''
said 30-year-old Parvanah of Irvine, Calif., who declined to give
her last name to protect relatives still in Iran.
   She said, ``Khomeini is the Hitler of our generation, and I am
going to fight him'' along with her 31-year-old husband Toraj. They
have two daughters, 5 and 10 years old.
   She said she and her husband would join the Iraq-based National
Liberation Army, the fighting arm of the People's Mujahedeen, and
expected to meet friends who had already joined that force.
   ``I know personally dozens of them from Orange County,'' Calif.,
who went to Iraq to fight Khomeini's government, she added.
   ``I will do anything that they need of me _ anything to help the
National Liberation Army free my people and overthrow Khomeini,''
said Sadaf Ebrahimi, 23. She said she and her husband, Faramarz,
plan to leave for Iraq within days.
   ``There are a lot of people joining the National Liberation Army
here; I know dozens of them at the University of Texas at Austin''
who volunteered, she said.
   Alireza Jafarzadeh, an organizer for the People's Mujahedeen,
said ``I know personally hundreds by name who have gone in the past
year, and definitely there are more than that.''
   The Iranians said they were making their own arrangements to get
visas to travel to Iraq and declined to provide details.
   Spokesman for the People's Mujahedeen said the volunteers travel
independently and join the resistance army when they arrive in Iraq.
   Jafarzadeh said that is why there are no exact figures on the
number of exiles who have left America.
   The National Liberation Army has an estimated 15,000 fighters.
   Jafarzadeh said when the Iranians arrive in Iraq they undego
training for weeks or months, depending on their skills and the
tasks they will carry out. They then are placed in various army
units and the assignments are not based on what country they came
from, he said.
   The National Liberation Army, established in 1987, conducted an
offensive last July called ``Eternal Light'' and claimed two
Iranian border cities were captured.
   It said its fighters then withdrew and asserted that during the
campaign they killed or wounded 55,000 Iranians and suffered only
1,000 casualties.
   Iran said it trounced the opposition army, killing or capturing
thousands. Iran's ambassador to the United Nations said Iran
sustained 40,000 casualties.
   London-based Amnesty International and a U.N. human rights
investigator said Iran embarked on a ``wave of executions'' of
political prisoners after that campaign, with most of the victims
being Mujahedeen sympathizers.
   The Iran-Iraq ended last year with a cease-fire proposed in
Security Council Resolution 598.
</TEXT>
