<FIRST>r i AM-Italy-PriestSlain     06-02 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy-Priest Slain,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>Priest Shot to Death in Mafia Stronghold</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: 'ndrangheta is cq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REGGIO DI CALABRIA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police patrolling a rugged
Calabrian forest used as a Mafia hideout on Friday found the body
of a priest who had performed the marriage of a fugitive mobster,
authorities said.
   They said they suspected that the priest, Giuseppe Giovanazzo,
53, was slain late Thursday as part of a vendetta, linked to
rivalries in the 'ndrangheta organized crime group or to another
feud in this sparsely populated southern region of Calabria.
   The 'ndrangheta is the Calabrian version of the Sicilian Mafia.
   In October 1985, Giovanazzo performed the marriage of a fugitive
mob suspect, the Italian news agency news ANSA reported. Several
months later the priest said in an interview that it wasn't his
business to ``ask the penal record of someone getting married.''
   Giovanzzo's body was found in a small car in Polsi, a mountain
village in the Aspromonte forest. He had been shot in the face with
a shotgun.
   Police regularly patrol the forest in search of organized crime
suspects as well as kidnap victims. Kidnapping for ransom is
considered one of the 'ndrangheta's main ways of getting cash.
   ANSA said the priest taught religion classes at an elementary
school in Locri, on the Calabrian coast.
   He also helped with pilgrimages to a sanctuary in honor of the
Virgin Mary at Polsi, it said, adding that he was heading to the
sanctuary when he was killed.
</TEXT>
