<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Sudan     06-02 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Sudan,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>Goverment Plane Bombs Air Strip While Relief Plane Delivers Food</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Sudanese government plane bombed a
landing strip in southern Sudan while a U.N. mercy flight was
unloading famine relief supplies, wounding three civilians, U.N.
officials said Friday.
   One woman's legs were mangled, said Charles LaMuniere, a U.N.
emergency relief official.
   In Kenya, Sudan's foreign minister said his government would
begin peace talks June 10 with rebels fighting for autonomy in the
south.
   Rebel leader John Garang, a former army colonel, offered to
extend a temporary truce through the end of June if progress was
made at the talks.
   Garang, who spoke to reporters during a visit to Geneva, accused
the govrnment of violating the truce by bombing the airstrip.
   A multi-agency relief operation is distributing food in southern
Sudan, where 100,000 people are threatened with famine caused by
the civil war.
   A U.N. flight landed at the rebel-held city of Torit on Thursday
and was delivering supplies when the Sudanese bomber attacked, said
John Usher of the U.N. Children's Fund
   As the bomber turned for a second run, the U.N. plane took off
and escaped. Usher said the Sudanese plane dropped 12 bombs.
   The $132 million aid project seeks to distribute food to remote
areas before villages and refugee camps are cut off by floods
during the rainy season. Last year, about 500,000 Sudanese died of
war-irelated starvation and disease.
   UNICEF director James Grant protested the bombing to Sudan's
U.N. ambassador, Amin M. Abdoun.
   Grant said later that he believed the attack was not ordered by
top government authorities. He asked for an investigation and
assurances there would be no repetition.
   Sidahmen Elhusain, the Sudanese foreign minister, said in
Nairobi he had no knowledge of the bombing except what he had heard
in news reports. He called it ``an isolated incident.''
   Torit fell to the Sudan People's Liberation Army on Feb. 26 and
has become a major redistribution center for relief supplies.
</TEXT>
