<HEAD>US Won't Let PLO Reopen Washington Office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department said Friday it has no
plans to let the Palestine Liberation Organization reopen the
Washington office the Reagan administration shut down in 1987.
   The Washington representative of the Arab League, Ambassador
Clovis Maksoud, told reporters earlier Friday that he had asked the
State Department to permit the PLO to reopen the office.
   Maksoud said it was ``mind-boggling'' for the United States to
maintain a dialogue with the PLO, begun last December, while
refusing the organization permission to reopen its office here.
   The State Department, responding to press inquiries about
Maksoud's statement, said Congress in 1987 prohibited the
establishment of any PLO office in the United States.
   ``The reestablishment of the (PLO) public information office
would not be consistent with the terms of this law,'' the
department said.
