<FIRST>r a AM-MutilatedBoy     06-02 0662</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mutilated Boy,0678</SECOND>
<HEAD>Angry Citizens Demand Laws to Stop Sex Offenders</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents of 3rd graf.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HAL SPENCER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OLYMPIA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderous applause greeted a police
officer Friday when he told a packed legislative hearing that the
only ``cured'' sex offender he knows is the rapist he shot to death.
   Tacoma policeman Stan Mowre was among witnesses at a hearing
where state senators unveiled legislation they said would crack
down on violent sex offenders. The measure was sparked by public
outrage over the sexual mutilation May 20 of a 7-year-old Tacoma
boy.
   The child, whose mother attended the hearing, was raped, choked,
and his penis severed in a wooded area near his home. The boy was
released from Mary Bridge Hospital in Tacoma on Wednesday in
satisfactory condition.
   Earl Kenneth Shriner, 39, is being held on charges of attempted
murder, rape, and assault in the attack on the boy. He has pleaded
innocent. Authorities say Shriner has a history of sexual violence.
   Most sex offenders are incurable, Mowre told the state Senate
Law and Justice Committee. ``There's only one that I know that was
cured, and that's the (rapist) I shot and killed in the line of
duty,'' Mowre said.
   Helen Harlow, the mother of the mutilated boy, spoke briefly and
calmly to the committee, telling lawmakers that sex offenders need
longer jail terms, special facilities, and long post-release
supervision.
   The public has a right to know who these people are when they
are released, said Ms. Harlow, and repeat offenders ``are going to
be harassed by the public as they should be.'' That remark drew
loud applause from the crowd.
   She said she still didn't understand why the system failed to
protect her child, and why a man with a history of violence against
young people was permitted to roam with no supervision.
   Officials have said that after Shriner served a 10-year prison
term for assault, authorities who considered him a sexual
psychopath could not get him committed to the state's systems for
the mentally ill because his past was too violent. And although he
was diagnosed as mildly retarded, his IQ was too high to qualify
him for homes for the developmentally disabled.
   In testimony Thursday before a House panel, Chase Riveland, head
of the state Department of Corrections, said people who suffer
developmental disabilities and mental illness ``frequently fall
between the cracks'' of the state's criminal and health systems.
   Ms. Harlow and others applauded the proposed legislation, which
includes doubling prison sentences for first-degree sexual assault
involving mutilation to 12 years for a first offense and
increasingly longer for repeat offenses.
   It also provides for post-release supervision from 10 years to
life, depending on the offender's record.
   Committee Chairman Kent Pullen, a Republican who co-wrote the
measure, said he wants a special session to pass the bill and
appropriate money to pay for the estimated 500 additional offenders
who would flood the already overburdened criminal justice system.
   Gov. Booth Gardner, a Democrat, said he was not opposed to a
special session if the legislation was appropriate. ``We want a
solution that would stand the test of time, not a solution that is
just window dressing'' he said.
   Friday's hearing was as much a venting of outrage over sex
crimes as a look at the proposed legislation.
   Lawmakers and one expert witness discussed whether castration is
better than special drugs to quell offenders' sexual urges, which
led one unidentified onlooker to stand and shout: ``Surgical is
better.''
   ``I'm not mad as hell. I'm enraged,'' said Ida Ballisiotes of
Seattle, whose daughter, Diane, was raped and killed in September
by a work-release inmate who had been classified as a sexual
psychopath.
   ``I don't want to hear again that this person or that person
fell through the cracks. I want the cracks filled,'' she said, on
the verge of tears. ``Our daughter was as innocent as that little
boy. I'm glad he lived. She didn't.''
</TEXT>
