<FIRST>r w AM-SovietRocket 1stLd-Writethru   06-02 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Rocket, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0648,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Says No Sign Of Debris From Soviet Rocket</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS grafs 4-5: ``In a,'' with State Department word of contacts
with Soviets.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet satellite booster rocket re-entered
the atmosphere over the U.S.-Canadian border with no sign that any
debris reached the ground, a State Department spokesman said Friday.
   The Soviet news agency Tass reported the launch Wednesday and
said in a later dispatch that the third stage of the Proton rocket
booster, which had put three satellites into orbit, descended over
the U.S.-Canadian border.
   There was ``no indication that any debris of any kind hit the
ground,'' said State Department spokesman Richard Boucher. He said
the descent of such boosters is a routine occurrence and that they
almost always burn up in the atmosphere before reaching the ground.
   In a statement released later, the department said U.S. and
Soviet officials ``have been in contact'' about the matter, but the
agency did not identify which officials or at what level.
   ``The Soviets offered to address any U.S. concerns which may
arise regarding the matter,'' the statement said.
   Capt. Thomas Niemann of the U.S. Space Command at Colorado
Springs said the Soviet rocket booster was tracked back into the
atmosphere at 2:54 p.m. EDT Wednesday at 48.5 degrees north and
about 96 degrees west, which would place it over Minnesota's border
with Canada.
   Command spokesman Dugald Gillies said the agency keeps track of
7,000 objects orbiting around the earth. He said man-made objects
fall out of orbit about once a day but rarely draw much attention
unless the re-entries occur over populated areas at night so they
can be seen. Debris very rarely reaches the ground, he said.
   Tass said the rocket launch was designed to test elements of a
global space navigation system being created to track civil
aviation aircraft and vessels of the Soviet maritime and fishing
fleets.
</TEXT>
