<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Irreverence     06-02 0584</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Irreverence,0602</SECOND>
<HEAD>Writer Makes Daring Proposals on Solzhenitsyn, Stalin Victims</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Congress, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A deputy galvanized the new Soviet parliament on
Friday by proposing to restore citizenship to Alexander
Solzhenitsyn and to inscribe the names of millions of Stalin's
victims on the walls of KGB headquarters.
   Yuri Karyakin, an outspoken writer from Moscow, also proposed
removing the body of Soviet founder Vladimir I. Lenin from its
hallowed mausoleum on Red Square and burying it.
   Addressing President Mikhail S. Gorbachev by name and the entire
Congress of People's deputies, Karyakin demanded, ``Return our
Russian citizenship to a person who dared to speak the truth first
about Stalin's system, who was the first to call on himself and on
us not to lie, to the great writer of Russia, to the great humanist
Solzhenitsyn.''
   Some of the 2,250 deputies in the Kremlin's Palace of Congresses
applauded the appeal by the 58-year-old, gray-bearded deputy from
the Academy of Sciences.
   Solzhenitsyn wrote extensively about the bloody terror of
dictator Josef Stalin's rule from 1924-1953, but his most biting
novels were never published in the Soviet Union.
   He was branded a traitor and stripped of his citizenship in
1974, expelled, and now lives in Vermont.
   Solzhenitsyn, who won the Nobel Prize for Literature in 1970, is
best known in the West for his books ``Gulag Archipelago,'' ``One
Day in the Life of Ivan Denisovich'' and ``Cancer Ward.''
   Only ``One Day in the Life of Ivan Denisovich'' has been
published in the Soviet Union, but a literary journal plans to
excerpt ``Gulag Archipelago,'' a chronicle of Stalin's labor camps,
by year's end.
   No immediate reaction to the Solzhenitsyn proposal came from the
Soviet leadership, but on Thursday, Vadim A. Medvedev, a member of
the ruling Politburo, said in an interview that Solzhenitsyn was
against Soviet power and Lenin and that ``Gulag Archipelago'' was
``anti-Soviet.''
   Two deputies _ Moscow populist Boris N. Yeltsin and Lithuanian
Communist Party chief Algirdas Brazauskas _ said in interviews they
supported Karyakin's call.
   Karyakin also said the secret police headquarters, called the
Lubyanka, should bear a reminder of those who suffered under Stalin.
   ``If we have not lost our memory, if we have not killed our
conscience, then we must write on the building on Lubyanka square
the names of 40 million _ we do not know the exact figure _ who
died because of and in connection with the orders of Lubyanka,'' he
said.
   A citizens group, Memorial, is campaigning _ with Gorbachev's
backing _ for a monument to be built to Stalin's victims. Stalin
killed millions through his forced collectivization of agriculture
and executions of real or imagined enemies.
   To a grumbling audience, Karyakin stood before a huge, white
statue of Lenin and said Lenin wanted to be buried beside his
mother in St. Petersburg, later renamed Leningrad, but his will was
ignored and his body was placed in a stone mausoleum after his
death in 1924.
   Lenin's widow, Nadezhda Krupskaya, opposed putting Lenin in an
above-ground mausoleum where his body could be viewed, but Stalin
and other party leaders overruled her.
   Yeltsin said he opposed the suggestion to remove Lenin's body
and bury it in Leningrad because the mausoleum is a ``symbol of our
revolution'' and should not be touched.
   In April, members of the Communist Party's policy-making Central
Committee condemned a similar suggestion.
   Millions of Soviets visit the mausoleum each year to show their
reverence to the founder of the Soviet state.
</TEXT>
