<FIRST>u a AM-RobberyTrial 3rdLd-Writethru a0714 06-02 0559</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Robbery Trial, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0714,0568</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Convicts Two Men In Largest W.Va. Bank Robbery</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with more details of how killing
was carried out, motive. Picks up 10th graf pvs, `Before the...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury convicted two men Friday of
robbing $286,000 from a bank and threatening potential witnesses,
and one was found guilty of murdering a partner who the robbers
feared would sell them out.
   Sentencing was set for Aug. 14 for John P. McCoy of Slaters
Branch, Ky., and Doyle David Moore of Lovely, Ky. They were found
guilty of being two of the four men who held up the Matewan
National Bank branch at Kermit on Jan. 3, 1987, in what was
described as West Virginia's biggest bank robbery.
   During six days of testimony, prosecutors relied heavily on
Harold D. ``Boonie'' Runyon, who pleaded guilty to conspiracy as
part of a plea bargain and admitted taking part in the robbery.
   Runyon testified that he and McCoy, described as the ringleader,
shot and killed another of the robbers, Russell Davis, atop a
mountain in eastern Kentucky after learning that Davis met with
federal officials in Florida.
   ``He was a threat to us,'' Runyon had said when he entered his
guilty plea. ``There was no reasoning with him. We took him to a
hill and shot him.''
   U.S. Attorney Michael Carey said the four robbers split the
money evenly, but that after Davis was killed, Runyon and McCoy
split his share. No money has been recovered.
   Davis had met with federal officials shortly after the robbery
about a counterfeit charge pending against him in Kentucky. Carey
said Davis had told McCoy and Runyon about the meeting, then
demanded the rest of his share from the bank robbery.
   McCoy and Runyon, fearing Davis would call attention to himself
and get arrested, killed Davis to silence him, Carey said.
   McCoy, 43, was convicted of robbery, conspiracy, threatening
federal witnesses and killing a potential government witness,
Russell Davis, another of the robbers. He faces up to life in
prison and a $2 million fine.
   Moore, 27, was convicted of robbery, conspiracy to commit
robbery and threatening a witness. He was found not guilty of
threatening another witness and of conspiring with McCoy to
threaten others, and was not charged in the death of Davis. He
faces up to 40 years in prison and a $750,000 fine.
   Before the trial began, prosecutors said that the suspects
plotted from jail to kill other potential witnesses _ people who
had heard them discuss the crime _ and flee to the Caribbean. One
potential witness died of undetermined causes last month, but
prosecutors ruled out foul play.
   Defense attorneys argued to jurors that the government witnesses
were not to be trusted, especially Runyon, because of his plea
bargain. Runyon said under cross-examination that he pleaded guilty
with the hope that he would avoid Kentucky's electric chair for his
role in killing Davis.
   ``They say Boonie Runyon had no reason to lie. With over 2,000
volts of electricity flowing through his body after his head had
been shaved ... that is a powerful motivator. That is a powerful
motivator to lie,'' said J. Michael Curtis, representing Moore.
   West Virginia doesn't keep records on bank robberies, but
officials said they could not remember a bigger one.
</TEXT>
