<FIRST>u i AM-Pope-Scandinavia 1stLd-Writethru a0696 06-02 0574</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pope-Scandinavia, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0696,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>PRECEDE TRONDHEIM</HEAD>
<HEAD>John Paul Travels North, Warns Against Materialistic Society</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout with trip to Tromsoe; no pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TROMSOE, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II preached against a
godless world Friday and visited his northernmost flock in the Land
of the Midnight Sun.
   In a city better known for nightclubs than devotion, thousands
of people braved a 39 degree chill and gray skies that hid the sun
as the pontiff led evening prayers.
   ``We are gathered this evening in the long bright twilight of
the north, in the light of the unsetting sun which so clearly
symbolizes Christ,'' John Paul said. He wore a white overcoat and
spoke in English.
   Tromsoe, an island in a fjord surrounded by snowcapped peaks, is
at 70 degrees latitude, 217 miles inside the Arctic Circle. It is
the northternmost outpost of the church, with 680 Roman Catholics.
   ``I'm surprised so many people came, but we don't get many
famous people here,'' said a young woman in blue jeans and a ski
jacket.
   John Paul spoke from a wooden altar erected in the market square
beside a bronze statue of a whaler with a harpoon. This cod-fishing
center of 48,000 people has 15 nightclubs and has been dubbed ``The
Land of the Midnight Fun.''
   On the second day of his Scandinavian pilgrimage, John Paul
first visited the bustling fjordside port of Trondheim.
   Small but enthusiastic crowds lined the streets as he arrived on
a clear, crisp day. A band played ``Down by the Riverside.''
   In an interview with Norwegian television, the pope said he felt
at home in Norway, not like an outsider in an overwhelmingly
Lutheran country with only 27,800 Catholics.
   He was asked asked why the church does not allow women to be
priests and suggested the questioner read a document on women he
issued this year. It ruled out women priests because of tradition
and because Christ was a man.
   In visiting Norway, the pope has stressed the long Christian
tradition in Scandinavia before it broke with Rome four centuries
ago.
   Addressing an ecumenical prayer service and later a Mass in what
was the center of Catholicism in pre-Reformation Scandinavia, John
Paul mentioned St. Olav, his son Magnus the Great and other early
Christians who played important roles in Norwegian history.
   ``As Christians we proclaim a wisdom that recognizes and upholds
the priority of ethics over technology, the primacy of the person
over things, the superiority of spirit over matter,'' he said.
   ``Before us lies the duty of opening a new Christian chapter in
history in response to the many challenges of a changing world.''
   ``Christians understand what is at stake,'' John Paul declared.
``The history of our own century clearly shows that where no
transcendent norm is acknowledged people are in danger of
surrendering themselves to forces which take command of society
without concern for individuals and their freedoms.''
   Meetings with Lutheran leaders have been a high point of the
Norway visit, producing frank exchanges on what separates Lutherans
from Rome.
   A 62-year-old Lutheran, Anne Krigvoll, said she traveled 50
miles to see John Paul in Trondheim because, though she has
differences with him, ``he too is interested in the real values,
the spiritual values.''
   The pope's 10-day tour moves to Iceland on Saturday. He also
will visit Finland, Denmark and Sweden before returning to Rome
next Friday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890602-0194 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 2137EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Obit-Lichine     06-02 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Lichine,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wine Expert Who Educated Many Americans Dies in France</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BORDEAUX, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wine expert Alexis Lichine, who informed
many Americans about French wine through popular books about
viniculture, died at his vineyard north of here. He was 75.
   The Russian-born American, whose books included ``Alexis
Lichine's Encyclopedia of Wines and Spirits,'' died Thursday at
Chateau Prieure-Lichine in Cantenac. The cause of death was not
immediately released.
   Roger Suger, president of the Margaux wine syndicate and owner
of the Chateau Malescot-St. Exupery, said: ``He was our ambassador,
our bridgehead to America.''
   Jean-Paul Kauffmann, editor of L'Amateur des Vins de Bordeaux, a
quarterly magazine specializing in Bordeaux wines, said: ``At each
meeting, I was impressed by the Falstaff side of this man who spoke
loudly and strongly.''
   Lichine was married and divorced five times, including once to
actress Arlene Dahl. He was born Dec. 3, 1913, in Moscow the son of
a White Russian lawyer and banker. As Russia struggled its way
toward revolution, the family fled to the United States, and later
to France.
   Lichine was educated in Paris and at the University of
Pennsylvania. During the war, he was an aide to Gen. Dwight D.
Eisenhower, commander of the allied forces in Europe, and was an
intelligence officer. He returned to the United States in the 1930s
and went into the wine importing business.
   In 1951, he bought the Chateau-Prieure Cantenac vinyard, later
changing its name to Chateau-Prieure Lichine.
   His books went through multiple editions and revisions. He
contributed articles to numerous American magazines, including
Esquire, Vogue, Harper's Bazaar and the New Yorker.
</TEXT>
