<DOCNO> AP890602-0195 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 1918EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     06-02 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hail, High Winds Hit Northeast, Southern High Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Hail and damaging winds accompanied thunderstorms that developed
Friday along a cold front curving through the Northeast, and in New
Mexico, Texas and Oklahoma.
   High wind swept through the city commons in Fitchburg, Mass., 45
miles west of Boston, toppling trees, power lines and two church
steeples and forcing the evacuation of a damaged housing complex
for 200 elderly people, officials said.
   A thunderstorm moving through eastern Pennsylvania produced golf
ball size hail at Pennsville, dime size hail at Deepwater, and wind
gusts of up to 62 mph. Thunderstorms in New Jersey brought wind
gusts of up to 60 mph at Mantloking.
   The threat of severe weather from thunderstorms stretched from
northeastern North Carolina to southeastern New York state and
southern New England and from eastern New Mexico and the western
half of Texas to southern Nebraska and eastern Colorado.
   A thunderstorm southwest of Amarillo, Texas, produced dime-size
hail at Canyon, Texas, and three isolated funnel clouds were
sighted near the Mississippi River in eastern Arkansas.
   Showers and thunderstorms clustered over much of the
south-central states, from central Gulf Coast region to Tennessee
and southern Arkansas. A mid-morning thunderstorm in northeastern
Alabama produced dime-size hail and wind gusts to 62 mph at Gadsden.
   Showers and thunderstorms also extended from Vermont and eastern
New York state through eastern Pennsylvania and western Virginia
into Kentucky.
   Heavier rainfall totals for the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT
included an inch and a third at Muscle Shoals, Ala., an inch and a
quarter at Burlington, Vt., nine-tenths of an inch at Plattsburg,
N.Y., and two-thirds of an inch at Knoxville, Tenn.
   Norfolk, Va., tied its record high for the date with 97 degrees.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 43
degrees at Yellowstone Park, Wyo., to 100 degrees at New Bern, N.C.
The low for the nation Friday morning was 28 degrees at Gunnison,
Colo.
   The forecast for Saturday called for scattered showers and
thunderstorms across much of the nation from the Atlantic Coast to
the southern high Plains, the central Rockies and the northern
Plateau west of the central Rockies. Showers and thunderstorms
should be most numerous from Montana and Wyoming to Oklahoma and
Missouri, and across the lower Ohio Valley. Fair to partly sunny
skies were predicted across the West and over south-central Texas,
the upper Mississippi Valley, Florida and southern Georgia and the
northern Atlantic Coast states.
   Temperatures were predicted in the 90s from southern and central
interior California across much of Texas to the southern Atlantic
Coast. Highs elsewhere should generally be in the 70s and 80s,
except for 60s from Idaho to Nebraska and the Dakotas, and over
Wisconsin, Upper Michigan and northern Minnesota.
</TEXT>
