<FIRST>r i AM-Mexico-Drugs     06-02 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Drugs,0445</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mexican Authorities Announce Arrests of Two Drug Gangs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities said Friday they had smashed two
cocaine- smuggling operations linked to Colombia's infamous
Medellin cartel.
   Javier Coello Trejo, deputy federal attorney general, said one
gang was led by Magdalena Pineda Trindad, a Guadalajara woman said
to be a representative of the drug cartel in Mexico.
   He said federal agents arrested 14 people in one gang this week
and seized 3,685 pounds of cocaine destined for the United States.
He said they also seized houses, ranches, 16 bank accounts, four
currency exchange companies, a hotel, drug laboratory, jet plane
and heavy construction equipment used to build air strips.
   Coello told a news conference seizure of the currency exchange
houses and bank accounts struck the core of the gang's
money-laundering operation. Federal agents also seek U.S.
cooperation in investigating several bank accounts in the United
States, he said.
   ``We have touched the heart of drug trafficking: the money,''
Coello declared.
   The gang used computers and sophisticated communications
equipment to intercept telephone calls and operate clandestine air
control centers for drug planes from Colombia, he said.
   Coello said the 14 suspects were two Colombians, a Chilean and
11 Mexicans, including a banker who allegedly helped launder money.
He said they face various charges involving drugs, guns and money.
   The case developed from two arrests at a checkpoint set up in a
border drug interdiction operation earlier this year, according to
Coello.
   He said the arrests and seizures occurred over four days in
several locations of northern and central Mexico, with the biggest
drug caches found in the northern states Coahuila, Tamaulipas and
Jalisco.
   Police accountants were sorting through records to determine the
value of the seized assets, he said.
   Coello said the gang manufactured a synthethic drug called
``Ecstasy'' in the clandestine lab. He said a nationwide search was
under way for Ms. Pineda Trindad, the alleged leader, who was
believed to be about 50 years old and had led the life of an
affluent businesswoman.
   The second gang, also based in Guadalajara, was led by a
Colombian named Jaider Curiel Choles, the deputy attorney general
said. He described Curiel Choles as ``the principal Medellin cartel
contact in Mexico.''
   Federal Judicial Police arrested Curiel Choles and 16 others in
a series of raids this week, Coello said, conficating 35 pounds of
cocaine, a house in Guadalajara, several bank accounts, two
vehicles and several weapons.
   He said the gang trafficked in marijuana and LSD as well as
Colombian cocaine bound for the United States.
</TEXT>
