<FIRST>u i AM-Sakharov 1stLd-Writethru   06-02 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sakharov, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0734,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sakharov Condemns Soviet Actions in Afghanistan</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 7th graf, `On a...' to CORRECT age</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Congress, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Andrei Sakharov has defied the Kremlin and the KGB
secret police, and on Friday he faced a new kind of foe _ outraged
representatives in the country's new elected Congress.
   The raucous parliamentary fray, carried on national television,
involved Sakharov's condemnation of Soviet actions in the war in
Afthanistan.
   After the angry exchange the frail human rights activist told
Western reporters, ``I can take it.''
   A veteran wounded in the war and now a member of the Congress of
People's Deputies demanded an explanation for a statement Sakharov
made in an interview with a Western newspaper: that Soviet pilots
in Afghanistan were ordered to kill comrades in danger of being
captured by rebels.
   In a booming voice, Sergei Chervonopisky accused Sakharov of
defaming the memory of the 15,000 Soviet soldiers killed in
Afghanistan.
   There was thunderous applause in the Kremlin's Palace of
Congresses for the passionate speech by the former paratroop major
who lost both legs in the war and said his artificial limbs were so
painful ``I wouldn't wish them on my enemies.''
   On a signal from President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, the 68-year-old
Sakharov, a member of the Congress, was given the floor to respond.
In a halting voice, he repeated his criticism of the Kremlin's
decision in December 1979 to send troops into Afghanistan to help
the Marxist government. The Soviets withrew their forces last
February under a U.N.-sponsored pact.
   Sakharov called the Soviet Union's conduct in Afghanistan ``a
war of annihilation against an entire people.'' It was his
outspoken opposition to the Soviet intervention that led to his
arrest in January 1980 and almost seven years in internal
banishment in the closed city of Gorky.
   Sakharov told the Congress that in the interview mentioned by
Chervonopisky about Soviet pilots he was repeating information he
had heard on foreign radio stations and the allegations were being
investigated.
   Many deputies reacted furiously, shouting and clapping their
hands to interrupt him.
   When a woman elected from the Central Asian republic of
Uzbekistan took the microphone to shout that Sakharov should be
ashamed, an overwhelming majority of deputies, including members of
the ruling Communist Party Politburo, rose in a standing ovation.
   Sakharov sat impassively in his chair as a series of deputies
took the floor to denounce him or accuse him of lying.
   Sakharov told Western reporters later that he had expected a
hostile reception, and he said he could have spoken better.
   He expressed one regret: not giving what he called a a more
complete description of ``all the crimes of the Soviet army'' in
Afghanistan.
   Sakharov, a nuclear physicist, won the Nobel Peace Prize in 1975.
</TEXT>
