<FIRST>r a AM-BusAccident     06-02 0201</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bus Accident,0206</SECOND>
<HEAD>One Killed, 35 Injured In School Bus Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LYONS, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A school bus returning from a field trip
plunged off a mountain road and overturned Friday, killing a
sixth-grade pupil and injuring 35 other schoolchildren.
   Most of the injuries were minor, said Sgt. Larry Tolar of the
State Patrol in Denver. The injured were being transported by
helicopter and ambulance to hospitals in Longmont, Boulder and
Denver, he said.
   The name of the victim, a 12-year-old boy, was not released
pending notification of relatives.
   The bus, with 41 children aboard, went off Colorado 7 three
miles southwest of Lyons in the Front Range foothills, Tolar said.
It plunged about 20 feet down an embankment and overturned onto
rocks beside South St. Vrain Creek.
   The bus, descending the canyon road, left long skid marks before
it ran off the highway. Apparently no other vehicles were involved.
   Tolar said other details about the accident, which occurred at
2:20 p.m., were not immediately available.
   The children were sixth-graders from Whittier Elementary School
in Boulder, said Ann Burton of the Boulder Valley School District.
They had gone to Highlands Camp near Allenspark on a one-day field
trip, she said.
