<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 2145EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-BrazilArt     06-02 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil Art,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Paintings of Brazil in 1864 Get First U.S. Showing Sunday</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto WX56</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Novelist Charles Dickens said no painter could
ever reproduce the brilliant tints of Brazilian hummingbirds, but
in 1864 American artist Martin Johnson Heade had a try. The results
get their first public showing since then at the National Gallery
of Art beginning Sunday.
   The 16 paintings Heade called ``The Gems of Brazil'' were sold
to Sir Morton Peto, a British collector, in 1865. After that, there
is no record of them until they turned up in an anonymous
collection in 1981. Soon afterwards they were bought by Richard
Manoogian, a Detroit industrialist.
   Paintings from his collection will be shown in Washington until
Sept. 4; at the M.H. de Young Memorial Museum in San Francisco
Sept. 23-Nov. 26, the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York Dec.
19 through Feb. 25, 1990 and the Detroit Institute of Arts, March
27 through May 27, 1990.
   The show is titled, ``American Paintings From the Manoogian
Collection,'' includes important works by Mary Cassatt, John Singer
Sargent, Thomas Eakins and other 19th Century American artists.
   Franklin Kelly, curator of collections at the Corcoran Art
Gallery, says Heade was the only major U.S. artist in the century
to make an important contribution to both landscape and still life,
and ``The Gems of Brazil'' include both.
   Kelly calls the paintings the most complex and ambitious of
Heade's career, which might have made him famous in this country if
they had been seen.
   Heade became interested in Brazil through a friend who was a
diplomat and an acquaintance of Brazil's last emperor, Pedro II. He
also painted a view of Rio de Janeiro, now in the Pennsylvania
Academy of Fine Arts, on the first of three trips he made to South
America.
   Pedro was interested in natural history and the arts, and Kelly
thinks he may have had something to do with the hummingbird idea.
   Heade took the paintings to Britain to get colored lithographs
made of them. A dozen years before, ornithologist John Gould had
exhibited 1,500 stuffed hummingbirds at the London Zoological
Garden. Queen Victoria said it was ``impossible to imagine anything
so lovely.''
   Dickens wrote: ``The most vivid colors of the painter's palette
cannot duplicate their ever-varying tints.''
   Heade made a try on canvas that Kelly calls among the most
original and beautiful works in 19th century American painting. But
he had to give up on the lithographs _ he could not get the colors
he wanted. The paintings were sold in London.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890602-0201 </DOCNO>
