<FIRST>r i AM-Argentina 1stLd-Writethru a0693 06-02 0652</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0693,0669</SECOND>
<HEAD>Food Riots Over, Political Question Is Can Alfonsin Remain?</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to ADD background. Pickup 10th pvs, `Almost
daily...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An opposition politician said
Friday that President Raul Alfonsin should leave office before the
December transition date because of ``social disintegration''
marked by food rioting.
   Fourteen people were killed this week when crowds looted
supermarkets and grocery stores. Provincial and municipal
authorities have taken emergency steps to feed the needy. No
violence was reported Friday.
   Alvaro Alsogaray, an economist and leader of the center-right
Union of the Democratic Center, said Alfonsin should step down
before Dec. 10, when he is scheuled to be succeeded by
President-elect Carlos Menem of the Peronist party.
   The Peronists defeated Alfonsin's cetrist Radical Civic Union in
the May 14 national elections. The Union of the Democratic Center
finished third.
   Alsogaray, in an inteview with Radio Continental, said
Argentina's ``road is well marked: social disintegration,
dissatisfaction and anguish.''
   ``Hyperinflation that understands nothing of politics will
continue marching on its own, and the new government will find
itself confronted by a situation of great complexity.''
   Alfonsin took office in December 1983 for a six-year term
following elections that ended rule by military dictators since
1976. Alfonsin was barred by the consitution from seeking
re-election.
   He has said he would consider stepping down before Dec. 10, and
his party and the Peronists have been discussing an early transfer
of power, but they have been unable to reach an agreement.
   Some cities and town set up soup kitchens for adults and hot
lunch programs for students in an effort to head off further
violence. They also regulated supermarket prices of flour, milk,
pasta and other basic products.
   The nation remained under a state of siege, but few looting
incidents and no clashes with police were reported Friday.
   Several thousand paramilitary police remained on duty in the
northern city of Rosario, but businesses opened normally and
schools resumed classes for the first time since the Monday when
rioting broke out.
   Earlier this week the country's biggest labor union and the most
influential business group suggested Alfonsin step down early.
Ex-President Arturo Frondizi said Alfonsin should resign
immediately.
   One of the biggest obstacles to an early transfer-of-power
agreement is the economy, which for May will register an alarming
70 percent rate of inflation or higher. The beef- and
grain-exporting nation is also plagued by a budget deficit and a
$59 billion foreign debt.
   Almost daily, the austral devalues against the dollar. The
official price, set by the Central Bank on Tuesday, is 175 to 1.
However, foreign exchange houses won't sell dollars at the price,
and black market traders demanded up to 330 to 1 on Friday.
   The rate as recently as Feb. 3 was 18 to 1. It was the plunge in
value of the austral that fueled inflation and record interest
rates and touched off the economic crisis.
   The nation's biggest farm groups also have little sympathy for
Alfonsin, whose election in October 1983 replaced a brutal military
dictatorship and was expected to herald a return to prosperity as
well as democracy.
   ``The crisis is the direct consequence of a failed political
economy,'' the Rural Society group of large ranchers said in a
statement.
   In an effort to ease economic bottlenecks caused by a weeks-long
shortage of austral bills, the Central Bank issued 50,000-austral
notes Friday.
   The austral was worth $1.20 when it was introduced in June 1985.
Today it is worth less than a penny, and the 50,000-austral note is
worth $285 at the official rate. It sells for just $151 on the
black market.
   Also Friday, the United Leftist front demanded the government
lift the 30-day state of siege declared Monday and free the several
hundred people who remain in jail after being detained for looting
or allegedly provoking disturbances.
</TEXT>
