<FIRST>r a AM-WrongWright     06-02 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wrong Wright,0483</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vermont House Speaker Says He Hopes People Get His Name Wright</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vermont's House speaker says he isn't
concerned that Wright's wrongs may lead some to the wrong Wright.
   House Speaker Ralph Wright says he was talking with an
eighth-grader Thursday about a program for troubled youths Wright
runs in Bennington.
   ``Yeah, I've heard of you. You quit yesterday,'' the boy told
the Vermont speaker.
   No, that was Jim Wright, the speaker of the U.S. House and no
relation to Ralph. The cloud of ethics violations under which the
Texan quit has left Vermont's Wright hoping folks get it right.
   For months now, Vermont newspapers have been running headlines
saying ``Wright Under Investigation;'' ``Speaker Wright Faces
Ethics Charges;'' ``Wright Denies Wrongdoing.''
   And Ralph Wright said there undoubtedly are some Vermonters who
thought he was the one in trouble.
   Now, with Jim Wright's resignation, Ralph Wright refers to
himself as ``the last Speaker Wright left in America.'' The
National Conference of State Legislatures confimed that Ralph
Wright is now the only House speaker in the nation.
   Vermont's Wright got a chuckle in April when someone sent him a
clipping from a Maine newspaper. The Washington-datelined story
with a headline about Wright facing a troubling ethics inquiry was
accompanied by a small photograph of the Vermont speaker.
   Perhaps adding to the confusion are that both speakers are
white-haired, have a distinctive manner of speaking, frequently
wear glasses and are said to be skilled political horse-traders and
highly effective at moving their agendas.
   Sometimes the confusion has come in handy. On a trip to
Washington late last year, Wright stopped by to see David Karvelas,
the chief of staff for freshman Rep. Peter Smith, R-Vt. Told that
Karvelas was in a meeting with other administrative assistants,
Wright says he got a quick response when he sent word with a page
that ``Speaker Wright'' was there to see Karvelas.
   Aside from the name confusion, Ralph Wright said of Jim Wright's
resignation, ``There's not a lot funny about it. It's sort of a
tragic thing.''
   As for any connection that voters might draw, Vermont's Wright
said, ``I don't know how much of that rubs off or lasts. It
probably doesn't amount to a hill of beans.
   ``I'll take responsibility for anything I do, but not for
anything done by somebody who by accident has the same name or the
same title.''
   One of the questionable deals pointed to by the House Ethics
Committee in the case of Texas' Wright had to do with collecting
unusually high royalties on a book sold mainly to special interest
groups.
   Vermont's Wright said he doubted he would ever get in similar
trouble. ``I wouldn't write a book,'' he said. ``Nobody would be
interested in reading it.''
</TEXT>
