<FIRST>u a AM-Eastern 1stLd-Writethru a0680 06-02 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0680,0563</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Announces Pay Cuts, No Vacations for Non-Union Workers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf with 7 grafs to UPDATE with details of buyout
proposal that would make Carlucci chairman. Picks up 4th graf pvs, ```We're
going...' A version moved on financial wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN WINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strike-slowed Eastern Airlines said Friday it was
requiring non-union employees to work more hours for the same pay,
cutting management pay by 20 percent and eliminating vacations for
the rest of the year.
   The austerity measures were announced as a federal bankruptcy
judge in New York kept alive hopes by striking employees that the
enfeebled airline might be purchased by a friendly investor they
are backing with their own money.
   At a hearing, U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland gave the
investor group led by Chicago commodities trader Joseph Ritchie
until 2 p.m. EDT Monday to further refine a revised buyout
proposal, based on discussions with the airline and its major
creditors.
   The proposal would make former Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci
chairman of the airline, Eastern's lead attorney, Harvey Miller,
told the bankruptcy hearing. Carlucci would succeed Frank Lorenzo,
chairman of Eastern's parent Texas Air.
   David I. Shapiro, the court-appointed examiner for Eastern, told
Lifland he was impressed by a new version of the plan under which
Eastern's unions would give $210 million in concessions, and risk
$175 million to $200 million of their wages over six months by
paying out any excess over target expenditures set by the airline.
   ``It is an insurance policy,'' said Dan Ashby, a pilots union
spokesman. ``It's a good-faith gesture to show we want to return
Eastern to profitabiliy.''
   Eastern sought protection from creditors under the bankruptcy
laws five days after pilots and flight attendants joined its
striking Machinists union March 4, virtually grounding the airline.
   Eastern officials said the austerity program for non-union
employees, which they described as temporary, would help Eastern
emerge from bankruptcy reorganization.
   ``We're going to be as tight as we can, as lean as we can and as
productive as we can during this period,'' Thomas J. Matthews,
senior vice president for human resources. ``Probably the term that
best describes this is belt-tightening.''
   The Miami-based carrier said the changes were needed because of
financial difficulties created by the 3-month-old strike and its
bankruptcy proceedings.
   Eastern spokesman James Ashlock described the changes as
austerity measures aimed at satisfying creditors as the airline
moves ahead with its plan to reorganize as a smaller carrier.
   Under the program, full-time agents and clerical workers will be
scheduled 50 hours a week for 40 hours of pay through Dec. 1.
Management also will work at least 50 hours a week.
   Salaries of corporate officers, including Eastern President Phil
Bakes, will be reduced 20 percent through the end of the year and
10 percent for the first six months of 1990.
   No vacations will be allowed through the end of the year, and no
vacation credit will be accrued from March to December of this year.
   The company's proposals for pilots and flight attendants will be
discussed when negotiations with the unions representing those
groups resume next week, Matthews said.
   Eastern is operating with 4,500 to 5,000 employees, most of them
in management positions, down from 30,000 before the strike.
</TEXT>
