<FIRST>r a AM-CrackMurders 1stLd-Writethru a0695 06-02 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crack Murders, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0695,0548</SECOND>
<HEAD>Florida Jury Recommends No Death Penalty in Four Drug Murders</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with jury recommending life for
all defendants. Picks up 8th graf, `All three ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three reputed drug gang members should be
spared from the electric chair and sentenced to life in prison for
murdering four people in a crack cocaine war, a jury recommended
Friday.
   The defendants, all from Miami, were convicted Thursday in the
murders of three men and a woman whose naked bodies were found
Sept. 20 at a home in suburban Pleasant Grove. The attackers bound
and gagged the victims before shooting them in the head and
slashing their throats.
   The jury that convicted the defendants after 10 hours of
deliberations took 50 minutes to decide to recommend life without
parole for at least 25 years for Timothy ``Red'' Robinson, 22, and
Michael ``Mac'' Coleman, 27. Each had been found guilty of four
first-degree murder counts.
   Six of the 12 jurors voted for the death penalty, but that fell
short of the needed majority.
   The vote was 11-1 for the same life sentence in the case of
Darrell ``Yoge'' Frazier, 25, found guilty of one first-degree
murder count and three counts of second-degree murder.
   Circuit Judge Nicholas Geeker is not bound by the jury's
recommendations. He set a sentencing hearing for July 25 so lawyers
can make arguments to him.
   Assistant State Attorney Michael Patterson would not comment.
The prosecutor had recommended death for all three defendants,
telling jurors it was a cold, calculated, premeditated crime for
money.
   Mothers of all three defendants appealed to the jury for mercy.
   ``Of all the evidence and testimony I've heard, nobody's
testified Darrell killed anyone,'' his mother, Alma Frazier, told
jurors. ``I don't believe he could have killed anyone.''
   She revealed that another son, Bruce ``Jit'' Frazier, 21, a
fugitive in the case, phoned her two months ago.
   ``I told him to turn himself in,'' Ms. Frazier said. ``Everyone
wants to see it come to an end. It's like a nightmare.''
   All three mothers said their sons had tough childhoods in
Miami's Liberty City, an impoverished black neighborhood agitated
by racial disturbances four times in the 1980s.
   Mary Robinson painted a picture of a chaotic family life,
raising seven children with little support from an abusive husband
she eventually divorced.
   Dolly Leverson said her son Coleman was considered a top
basketball prospect but dropped out of school after the 10th grade.
She said she did not believe he committed the murders because in
previous brushes with the law he had always admitted his
involvement, but this time he has maintained his innocence.
   Coleman was the only defendant to testify during the sentencing
hearing.
   ``I still say I did not commit any crime, as God is my
witness,'' Coleman said. He noted genetic tests failed to link him
with the rapes of two victims, one of whom survived the attack.
   Coleman and Robinson were convicted of two rape charges. Each
defendant also was convicted of one count of attempted murder, six
of kidnapping, one of conspiracy to traffic in cocaine, two of
robbery and one of breaking and entering.
</TEXT>
