<FIRST>r i AM-Peru     06-02 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrilla Attacks Kill 10</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten people were killed, including a child hit
by a stray bullet, and four policemen were wounded in guerrilla
attacks throughout Peru on Thursday and Friday, authorities said.
   Police said members of the Mao-inspired Shining Path group
overran a peasant community in an attack Thursday in the Andean
mining state of Pasco, 115 miles northeast of Lima, and killed two
village officials and two other people.
   In a nearby community, two guerrillas died in a shootout with a
military patrol and a child was killed by a stray shot, authorities
said.
   One policeman was killed and four were wounded in an attack by
insurgents early Friday on a police outpost in Aija, 160 miles
north of Lima in Ancash state, a mountainous area frequented by
foreign backpackers. A state bank and municipal buildings were
bombed in the attack.
   In Lima, a street vendor was killed Thursday night when caught
in a cross fire between police and guerrillas who were trying to
set fire to buses in a plaza.
   Twelve miles north of the capital, insurgents set fire to a bus
after forcing the passengers and driver to get off.
   A police sergeant was shot dead on the street Friday by leftist
guerrillas who fired from the back of a passing pickup truck in a
Lima suburb.
   A leftist insurgency has sundered Peru since the Shining Path
took up arms against the government in 1980, with more than 14,000
people killed.
</TEXT>
