<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-BirthControl     06-02 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Birth Control,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Hints at Need To Check Population Growth</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranian President Ali Khamenei on Friday
indicated a need to check population growth but he did not advocate
birth control _ an issue that has sparked debate among Iran's
Moslem theologians.
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency quoted Khamenei as
telling thousands of people at the weekly prayer meeting in Tehran,
``Don't make an excuse of the Prophet (Mohammed) if you want to
have more children.''
   He said Islam initially encouraged large families because there
were only about 100,000 people in the Arabian peninsula, where the
religion was founded.
   ``But this does not mean that for the rest of history every
Moslem family is obliged to have 8, 10 or 12 children,'' he said.
   IRNA, monitored in Nicosia, also said the government was trying
to encourage people to use contraceptives, but there is no national
plan to reduce the birthrate. Iran's annual population growth of
3.7 percent is among the highest in the world.
   The agency quoted Khamenei as saying he would not ``reject or
insist on'' birth control.
   IRNA said Iran's population now exceeds 50 million and it is
expected to double in 20 years.
   Supporters and opponents of birth control have debated the issue
in the news media.
   Some theologians said the government could implement controls
without violating Islamic law. They said the Koran calls on people
to achieve happiness, and if contraception is a way to gain
happiness it is permissible.
   Others arued that contraception is against the will of God on
grounds the birth of a child is an act of God.
</TEXT>
