<FIRST>r a AM-LukensReax     06-02 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lukens Reax,0523</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reaction Mixed to Lukens' Decision to Stay in Office</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES HANNAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIDDLETOWN, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. Donald Lukens' decision to
stay in office despite being convicted of having sex with a
teen-age girl drew mixed reactions in his hometown Friday but did
not surprise state political leaders.
   ``I think it's ludicrous on his behalf to think that the public
... still trusts him,'' said Ron Shumard, a Republican from
Middletown. ``The public trust and his behavior are not compatible
for him to carry on that kind of office.''
   Lukens said in a statement Friday he would retain his seat as he
fights the misdemeanor conviction of contributing to the
delinquency and unruliness of a minor.
   Declaring ``I am now fighting for my political life,'' the
58-year-old Republican said he would not allow ``the lies and
deceit of one delinquent individual'' to ruin him.
   Lukens, who is divorced, was convicted of having sex at his
Columbus apartment on Nov. 6 with a girl who was then 16. He faces
sentencing this month in Franklin County Domestic Relations Court,
but is appealing the verdict.
   ``I don't think he should be left in there at all,'' said David
Lenharr of Middletown, who described himself as a Democrat but said
he has voted Republican in the past. ``He don't deserve to
represent our district.''
   But Joe Ferguson, another Democrat, said the congressman should
not be forced to step down.
   ``He ain't done more than a lot of other guys have done,''
Ferguson said. ``He just happened to get caught. I don't hold that
against him.''
   On Thursday, Ohio GOP Chairman Robert Bennett and GOP leaders
from Lukens' district joined in a call for the congressman to
resign.
   ``I think he is a bad apple for the Republican Party,'' Bennett
said. ``He has lost the support of the entire Republican leadership
of his district.''
   Bennett said the party has no power to forcehis resignation, but
can withhold its support if he seeks re-election in 1990.
   Rep. Chalmers Wylie of Columbus, the senior Republican in Ohio's
congressional delegation, repeated a call he made hours after
Lukens' conviction last Friday for Lukens to ``do the gentlemanly
thing and resign.''
   ``He's just prolonging the agony. That cannot help the interest
of the institution of Congress or `Buz' Lukens,'' Wylie said.
   Wylie said he had been told by a House Ethics Committee member
last week that the panel would take up the matter of Lukens
conviction. Wylie declined to identify the member.
   Donald Birgel, chairman of the Butler County GOP in Lukens' home
county, said Lukens' announcement was predictable.
   ``The issue is the people of this congressional district want a
certain morality level of all the political leaders. Eeverything
involved in this case is not an acceptable level of morality for a
congressman and that's why we feel he should resign.''
   Birgel added, however, that calling for Lukens' resignation ``is
the most distasteful thing I've ever had to do in my adult life.
It's depressing.''
</TEXT>
