<FIRST>u w AM-NancyReagan 1stLd-Writethru a0759 06-02 0717</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nancy Reagan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0759,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former First Lady Gets First Welcome Back To Washington</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 17th graf pvs, bgng: ``CBS reporter...'' to correct reference
to Adams; picks up 18th graf pvs, bgng: ``At that...''</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto WX51</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   WASHINGTON (ap) _ Former First Lady Nancy Reagan was welcomed
back to Washington for the first time Friday with a shower of hugs,
kisses and friendly barbs about ``the good old days'' from friends
and former staffers.
   Dressed in a signature red Aldofo dress, but arriving bit late
without the crack advance team that had once plotted her every
move, Mrs. Reagan attended an elegant afternoon tea party, eager to
catch up on the four months that have gone by since she and
President Reagan bid Washington adieu.
   ``I've got a big scoop for you _ I've gained four pounds!'' the
still-thin Mrs. Reagan exclaimed to one reporter as she swept
through the group of well-wishers.
   Mrs. Reagan was in Washington to address a Library of Congress
symposium on first ladies' memoirs, and she promised that her own
book _ expected out in the fall _ will be a page-turner.
   ``I'm going to say everything I couldn't say for eight years,''
she vowed.
   Sporting her Secret Service nickname ``Rainbow'' on her shoulder
identification tag, the former first lady worked the crowd of about
100 with old-time political savvy, sharing lengthy hugs and
animated conversations with many, among them her former maid, Anita
Costelo.
   She assured those present that she and the former president
``absolutely'' love their California life, and that they are both
``wonderful.''
   But it is a different world. With a mischevious grin, Mrs.
Reagan confessed to a group of reporters, ``I even miss you.''
   Among those present was a long list of former staff members,
including first hairdresser Robin Weir, chiefs of staff Joe Canzeri
and Jim Rosebush, social secretaries Linda Faulkner and Mabel
Brandon, press secretaries Elaine Crispen and Jennefer Hirshberg,
personal secretary Jane Erckenbeck, speechwriter Landon Parvin and
press aides Wendy Weber Toler and Betsy Koons.
   Mrs. Crispen said the fest was partly devised as a reunion, and
partly to celebrate the first lady's July 6 birthday, and who was
counting which one?
   Her nebulous age in the White House _ in fact, she will be 68
next month _ was the stuff of gentle ribbing.
   Washington Post reporter Donnie Radcliffe welcomed Mrs. Reagan
on behalf of her former press corps, recalling those days when
journalists bore in on her image as a clothes horse, high-priced
china purchaser and White House decorator extraordinaire.
   ``Who would have ever thought eight years ago, we'd be talking
about the good old days?'' Ms. Radcliffe quipped, evoking an
energetic and affirmative nod from Mrs. Reagan.
   The reporter reminded Mrs. Reagan that she'd ``always acted your
age _ when you could decide what it would be'' and of the times
when ``you couldn't do a thing with your hair because it messed up
your crown.''
   Mrs. Reagan's alleged influence in high-stakes foreign policy
wasn't ignored, nor was her grand rivalry with Soviet first lady
Raisa Gorbachev.
   Ms. Radcliffe kidded Mrs. Reagan that after her famous
tete-a-tete with Soviet foreign minister Andre Gromyko, the
official had ``gone right home and told Raisa about it, which is
why you became such good friends.''
   CBS White House correspondent Jacqueline Adams added that
reporters really did miss Mrs. Reagan's backstage talents for
dealing with troublesome White House appointees _ ``especially at
the time of John Tower.''
   At that, Mrs. Reagan laughed so hard she hid her face in her
hands.
   Ms. Radcliffe also advised Mrs. Reagan that the group had
arranged a VIP tour of the Bush White House for her _ ``but we
figured you didn't need any more pictures of you bouncing on the
Lincoln bed.''
   And the assembly had intended to get a present for her, ``but
they were all out of puppies,'' Ms. Radcliffe joked in a reference
to a current preoccupation of the new first lady, Barbara Bush.
   After Mrs. Reagan was presented with a small, needlepointed
pillow adorned with her ``Rainbow,'' nickname, she assured the
group:
   ``I've missed all of you. We both have. It's wonderful to be in
our own home, but if you miss us, that's nice too.''
</TEXT>
