<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon-Cyprus     06-02 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Cyprus,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Claims Responsibility for `Cyprus Operation'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIAD KAHWAJI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A previously unknown group claimed
responsibility Friday for a plan to shoot down a helicopter
carrying Christian army commander Gen. Michel Aoun to Cyprus.
   ``The March 14 organization announces its responsibility for the
operation our six strugglers arrested in Cyprus recruited
themselves to accomplish,'' said a statement delivered to the
privately owned Sohofia news agency in west Beirut.
   Six Lebanese were arrested in Cyprus' south coast tourist resort
of Larnaca on May 26 and on Monday, after two scuba divers came
across two Soviet-made SA-7 missiles and their launchers in
watertight packing off the coast.
   Aoun, 54, who also heads a Christian military Cabinet in
Lebanon's dual government, had been expecting an invitation to
attend last week's Arab summit conference in Casablanca, Morocco.
   He would have been likely to travel by helicopter from his
blockaded Christian enclave to Larnaca to catch a flight to
Casablanca, but the invitation never materialized.
   The March 14 organization apparently was named after the date
Aoun's gunners based around Yarze pounded mostly Moslem west Beirut
for the first time in one of the heaviest barrages unleashed during
an 11-week confrontation with Syrian troops and Druse Moslem
militiamen.
   By police count, 39 people died in the March 14 shelling duels.
A total of 360 people have been killed and nearly 1,400 wounded in
the latest round of Lebanon's 14-year-old civil war.
   There was no way of authenticating the typewritten Arabic
statement saying the six Lebanese detained in Cyprus planned to
``execute the just verdict of the people against Yarze's butcher
Michel Aoun ... for the massacre he committed on March 14.''
   Aoun's headquarters were in the Defense Ministry compound at
suburban Yarze, five miles east of Beirut, when the artillery
battles erupted March 8.
   In Friday's statement to Sohofia, a non-partisan local news
agency specializing in Lebanese affairs, the March 14 organization
described itself as a ``group of nationalist unionist non-sectarian
strugglers.''
   The six Lebanese are being held in Nicosia, the Cypriot capital,
on charges of conspiracy to commit murder and illegal possession of
arms and explosives.
   Aoun is opposed by the rival Moslem Cabinet of Acting Prime
Minister Salim Hoss. The two Lebanese governments _ have been
contesting power since September, when outgoing President Amin
Gemayel named Aoun to head a temporary military Cabinet to rule
pending Parliament's election of a new head of state.
   Syria, which keeps 40,000 troops in neighboring Lebanon under a
1976 Arab League peacekeeping mandate, considers the country within
its sphere of influence and backs the Hoss government.
</TEXT>
