<FIRST>u a AM-CottonClub 1stLd-Writethru a0730 06-02 0704</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cotton Club, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0730,0718</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Cotton Club' Witness Blurts Out Details of Confessions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with star witness giving surprise testimony,
stopping hearing; tightens throughout. No pickup. Note offensive nature
of content in 2nd and 12th grafs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A preliminary hearing in the ``Cotton Club''
murder case was halted Friday after the star witness blurted out
surprise details of defendants' alleged confessions, prompting
defense attorneys to cry foul.
   The witness, William Rider, said two defendants bragged about
killing producer Roy Radin and one of them said, ``He enjoyed
shooting the big fat Jew.''
   The lawyers accused prosecutors of purposely hiding the
incriminating statements, which had to be disclosed under
California discovery laws. Deputy District Attorney David Conn
insisted that he had disclosed ``the gist of the statements,'' but
Municipal Court Judge Patti Jo McKay said that was not enough.
   She stopped testimony and ordered prosecution investigators to
appear in court Monday to reveak what they know about Rider's
planned testimony. If more is uncovered, she said she would grant
the defense a continuance to prepare.
   Rider, whose previous disclosures triggered the filing of
charges in the six-year-old murder, is considered the prosecution's
most important witness. He ties defendants Alex Lamota Marti and
William Molony Mentzer to the actual killing and implicates chief
defendant Karen DeLayne Greenberger.
   The prosecution contends Mrs. Greenberger, a reputed drug
dealer, arranged Radin's murder after they fought about her share
of profits from ``The Cotton Club.'' She had introduced Radin to
former Paramount Pictures chief Robert Evans, who was dealing with
Radin in his attempts to finance the film.
   In Rider's earlier statements, he also said he was told that
Evans was involved in the Radin slaying.
   Rider, who was chief of security for Hustler Magazine publisher
Larry Flynt, said he had hired Mentzer and Marti as bodyguards. He
said both men boasted to him in May or June of 1983 about the Radin
murder.
   In June, he said, Mentzer and Marti brought him a newspaper
article about the discovery of Radin's body, said it proved they
were telling the truth and offered more details.
   ``Mr. Marti said that in reference to Mr. Mentzer getting the
courage to shoot Mr. Radin, that he had to drink a bottle of wine
before. Mr. Marti shot first and emptied his gun into Mr. Radin and
Mr. Mentzer followed suit,'' said Rider.
   ``What else did Mr. Marti say?'' asked Deputy District Attorney
David Conn.
   ``Just that he hated Jews and he enjoyed shooting the big fat
Jew,'' said Rider.
   Judge McKay had ordered that every person entering the courtroom
be searched before Rider, who is Flynt's former brother-in-law,
arrived with his retinue of burly bodyguards.
   The halt in testimony came on the same day that former TV star
Demond Wilson contradicted his earlier testimony, denying that
Radin had expressed fear of danger because of his involvement in
``The Cotton Club.''
   Wilson's startling flip-flop came moments before he ended three
days on the stand. After Wilson left, Mrs. Greenberger's attorney,
Edward Shohat, asked the judge to throw out the actor's testimony.
   ``You're dealing with a witness who would say anything that's
convenient at the time,'' he said. But the judge denied the motion.
   Wilson, the former star of TV's ``Sanford and Son,'' was one of
the last people to see Radin alive. He testified Wednesday that
Radin, a New York theatrical producer, expressed fear for his life
because of negotiations to finance the movie.
   ``He asked me to follow and just watch and see if anything
happened,'' Wilson said then. ``He said that there might be some
trouble. He said that something might happen to him as a result of
his association with the film thing ... `The Cotton Club.'''
   But Wilson changed that account Friday.
   Under rapid fire cross-examination by attorney David Kenner,
Wilson said: ``I didn't hear him talk about `The Cotton Club.'''
Then he amended his remark, saying: ``I had heard him talk about it
but it was a pipe dream. He was talking about a film. Sometimes
films weren't even named.''
   Also charged in the case is Robert Ulmer Lowe, who is fighting
extradition in Maryland.
</TEXT>
