<FIRST>u a AM-SniperTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0758 06-02 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sniper Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0758,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `Ducharme, 25, ..., to CORRECT to Smithfield
sted Springfield.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Suspect Convicted in New England Sniper Shootings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who said he began by shooting at
streetlights but switched to people when it ``got boring'' was
convicted Friday in a series of snipings that terrorized
communities in Rhode Island and Massachusetts.
   A Superior Court jury found Russell J. Ducharme II guilty on 30
of 36 counts, including eight counts of assault with intent to
commit murder and seven counts of conspiracy to commit murder
during late 1986 and early 1987.
   He was also found guilty of a series of arsons and break-ins in
the summer of 1987.
   He faces a maximum sentence of two life terms in prison plus 355
years.
   Ducharme, 25, of Smithfield was acquitted of six charges,
including four counts of breaking and entering, one count of first
degree arson and one count of stealing a firearm.
   Ducharme and his companion, Peter T. Trepanier, 25, of
Burrillville, began shooting at streetlights, but switched to
shooting at people after that ``got boring,'' Ducharme said during
the 16-day trial.
   Four people were injured in the attacks along the border of
Massachusetts and Rhode Island, which ended only after Gov. Edward
DiPrete called out the National Guard to patrol the area.
   Judge Dominic Cresto continued bail at $520,000 with surety. No
sentencing date was set. Trepanier was convicted in February on
similar counts and awaits sentencing.
   Cresto set a June 21 hearing on motions for a new trial.
   The verdict came late in the fourth day of deliberations, after
Cresto denied a motion for a mistrial.
   ``We're tired and we're satisfied,'' said prosecuting attorney
Eva Marie Mancuso. Defense attorney J. Joseph Nugent declined to
comment.
   At trial, Nugent contended that police improperly coerced a
confession in which Ducharme admitted he and his friend were
responsible for the shootings, housebreaks and arsons.
   Ducharme was arrested Oct. 8, 1987, after Trepanier walked into
the Woonsocket police station and confessed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
