<FIRST>u a AM-MassachusettsStorm 1stLd-Writethru a0747 06-02 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Massachusetts Storm, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0747,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wind Batters Massachusetts City, Killing One</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to UPDATE with dead woman crushed by steeple,
identity, other injuries, details, quotes. Picks up penultimate graf pvs,
`He said...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FITCHBURG, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   High wind described as a small twister
swept through the city center Friday, crushing a woman to death
under a church steeple, injuring several other people and knocking
down trees and power lines. ``It's an ugly scene. There are wires
down all over the place,'' said Mayor Jeffrey A. Bean.
   A housing complex for 200 elderly residents was evacuated
because of structural damage, Bean said.
   Sandra R. Cressey, 53, of Fitchburg was in her car when it was
``literally crushed'' by a wooden steeple that fell from the First
Parish Unitarian Universalist Church, said Vicky Greene, a nursing
supervisor at Burbank Hospital.
   Cressey was pronounced dead at the hospital, where she had
worked for more than 20 years as a director of clinical services,
said hospital spokesman James Leach.
   A mother and her three children were in another car that was hit
by the steeple, but left Burbank Hospital without being treated,
Greene said.
   A church spire atop the Faith United Church also toppled,
sending chunks of brownstone from the church flying into the
street. Both churches are within 150 yards of each other on the
Fitchburg common.
   Fire officials said other people were trapped in cars by a maze
of fallen wires in the center of this largely working class city of
39,000 people 45 miles west of Boston.
   A 19-year-old man and a 24-year-old man were treated and
released for injuries sustained from debris flying in the air, said
Vicky Greene, a Burbank nursing administrator. She said a
3-year-old boy, who was in a car with his father when a branch hit
their windshield, caught a piece of glass in his eye.
   Mark Romano, 28, said he saw a 400- to 500-pound dumpster lifted
30 feet off the ground and deposited 25 feet away from its original
spot in the Congregational Church parking lot next to his house.
   Then, Romano said, he saw the black funnel-shaped cloud touch
down on one of the church steeples, pull it off and dump it on a
parked car nearby.
   Fire officials, the Fitchburg Civil Defense Office and witnesses
reported seeing a small twister touch down amid torrential rain
Friday afternoon.
   A National Weather Service spokesman in Boston said the nature
of the storm was still being investigated Friday night.
   Earlier, Gene Auciello, meteorologist at the weather service
office at Boston's Logan International Airport, said it was
unlikely a tornado had struck.
   He said the wind blast was probably a downburst from severe
thunderstorms passing through the state. Storms were developing
along a cold front curving through the Northeast.
   Fitchburg and nearby Gardner, which also suffered downed trees
and wires in winds clocked at up to 80 mph, declared a state of
emergency, said Douglas Forbes of the Massachusetts Civil Defense
Agency.
</TEXT>
