<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 1106EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i PM-Greece-Elections Adv08   06-02 0803</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Greece-Elections, Adv 08,0826</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv08</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thurs PMs June 8 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Papandreou Fights For Political Life in June 18 Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK QUINN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Swept into power eight years ago promising
radical changes for Greece, Premier Andreas Papandreou is battling
for his political survival in elections June 18.
   The 70-year-old leader is beset by allegations of widespread
corruption among senior members of his ruling Panhellenic Socialist
Movement (PASOK) and accusations that he failed to implement many
socialist reforms he espoused when first elected in 1981.
   He's also in the midst of divorcing his American-born wife of 38
years to take up with a former airline stewardess half his age.
   But friends and foes alike admit that Papandreou, an economics
professor in the United States before returning to political life
in Greece, is far from beaten. He still retains an oratorical flair
and personal appeal that gave him 48 percent of the popular vote in
1981 and 46 percent in 1985.
   Papandreou is banking on support from Greece's rural areas,
where socialist policies have had more success than in the cities.
   ``Socialism, democracy, patriotism, peace, these were the goals
of the popular movement in our country,'' he told a recent rally.
``PASOK continues this popular movement today. Our enemy is not the
left, it is the right.''
   Opposition parties claim Papandreou has ignored many of the
accusations against him and tried instead to polarize the
electorate.
   He has also skirted the issue of his personal life, choosing
instead to allow his live-in companion, 35-year-old Dimitra Liani,
to accompany him on campaign trips.
   Papandreou's open affair with Ms. Liani has hurt his personal
popularity, but public interest in the relationship seems to be
dying down.
   ``People are tired about hearing about his personal life. People
want to talk about economic and social issues, people want to know
what's happening,'' said Theodoros Pangalos, deputy foreign
minister and a member of PASOK's executive council.
   Papandreou has said his affair with Ms. Liani hurt his standing
in the polls but added that he made it public because he was
committed to the tall blonde.
   ``I knew this would have a cost. But it was not a passing thing.
It was a relationship, it was a way of life,'' he said in an
interview with a Greek newspaper.
   He has also speeded up the divorce suit filed against his wife
Margaret, 66, in hopes of having it over with and, PASOK sources
say, to marry Ms. Liani before the elections.
   He has been married to the former Margaret Chant, of Elmhurst,
Ill., since 1951. They have four children and two grandchildren.
One of the children, 37-year-old George Papandreou, is a PASOK
member of Parliament. Mrs. Papandreou still lives in Greece.
   To improve his image and pick up support from leftist voters,
Papandreou has also promised to submit any agreement in current
negotiations on the future of four U.S. military bases in Greece to
a national referendum if he wins the elections.
   But economic problems and a seesawing foreign policy have eroded
popular support for the Socialists.
   Greece's response to international terrorism has also angered
some of the country's NATO allies. In December, the government
freed and put on a plane to Libya a Palestinian wanted by Italy for
a 1982 bomb attack against Rome's main synagogue that killed a
child. There have also been repeated delays in extraditing
suspected terrorist to the United States.
   Allegations of involvement in a multimillion dollar scandal
surrounding fugitive Greek banker George Koskotas has tested the
premier's appeal.
   Koskotas fled Greece in November after being indicted in a $200
million-fraud forgery and embezzlement scandal. Koskotas, the
chairman of the Bank of Crete, was arrested in the United States
and is jailed in Salem, Mass., awaiting an extradition hearing.
   He has alleged in interviews from jail that Papandreou and other
senior Socialist officials were given millions of dollars in
payoffs and authorized the looting of his bank.
   Papandreou, in turn, has accused the U.S. Central Intelligence
Agency and the ``American establishment'' of trying to orchestrate
his political demise.
   The main conservative opposition New Democracy Party, led by
Constantine Mitsotakis, has been hammering away at the government's
handling of the Koskotas scandal since it first surfaced more than
eight months ago.
   Although New Democracy leads PASOK by about 7 percentage points
in recent public opinion polls and is favored to win a majority in
the 300-member single chamber parliament, political analysts say
the 70-year-old Mitsotakis falls short against Papandreou in
popularity.
   This stems from his failure to defeat Papandreou in the 1985
elections and from from his alleged involvement in a series of
political intrigues in the mid-1960s. The socialists claim these
intrigues paved the way for the 1967-74 military dictatorship.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Thurs PMs June 8</NOTE>
