<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 1320EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a w PM-FoleyProfile Adv06-2Takes   06-02 1180</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Foley Profile, Adv 06-2 Takes,1204</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv06</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tuesday PMs, June 06</HEAD>
<HEAD>Tom Foley: A Democrat Who Can Charm Even Republicans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   By the typically bone-dry account of Sen. Alan
Simpson, all the next speaker of the House need do is ask, and the
Republicans will leave town.
   For the charm of Thomas Stephen Foley is so pure, says Simpson,
that he can ``tell you to go to hell, and make you look forward to
the trip.''
   Simpson, the assistant Republican leader of the Senate, didn't
say whether any one had ever received such an invitation from
Foley. But no one denies that the Foley, a Washington Democrat,
knows how to move people, if ever so gently, a little at a time.
   As House majority leader, Foley won nearly universal admiration
from both sides of the aisle for his scholarly command of issues,
personal cordiality and the patience of Job.
   Now, as the likely successor to Jim Wright, who is surrendering
both his speaker's throne and his House seat in the face of a
wrenching ethics investigation, the fatherly team player from
Spokane steps today into the job called the second-most powerful in
government.
   Though both trace their roots to Franklin Roosevelt's New Deal,
Wright was a lone wolf, Foley a faithful companion among political
peers. The ambitious Wright climbed through the ranks; Foley was
lifted and nudged through them, partly by his colleagues, partly by
political accident.
   A tireless negotiator, Foley wields power through
consensus-building and compromise. By contrast, Wright acknowledged
in his swan song to the House that he ``perhaps'' had been ``too
partisan, too insistent, too abrasive, too determined to have my
way.''
   Foley is no knee-jerk liberal _ and wouldn't have lasted in the
House if he were. Unlike most leaders whose seats are ``safe,''
Foley is from a distinctly Republican and conservative district
that has put him through many close elections.
   Though hand-picked for the House's elite by Wright and his
predecessor, former Speaker Thomas P. ``Tip'' O'Neill, Foley never
shared their penchant for partisan chest-thumping. O'Neill admired
Foley most for qualities he admittedly didn't possess himself _
meticulous craftsmanship of legislation, thorough command of the
issues, attention to organizational detail.
   ``Tom Foley,'' O'Neill once said, in both exasperation and
respect, ``is a man who can see three sides of every issue.''
   Sometimes more. Rep. Norman Dicks, D-Wash., tells about the time
that a colleague rushed to the House floor at the last moment and
implored Foley to tell him if there were any reasons he should vote
against the bill.
   The congenial Foley ``laid out seven significant reasons,''
Dicks recalled, and the member promptly voted ``no.'' Then, just as
the electronic tote board was switching off, the fellow noticed
Foley had voted ``yes.'' He was furious. Foley merely replied:
``You didn't ask me for all the reasons why the bill is good.''
   When Foley was first elected in 1964, younger members of
Congress were left with little to do but follow their leaders.
That's not how the House works today, and Foley is a beneficiary of
the post-Watergate revolt against the seniority system and the
diffusion of power.
   ``The reality is that in a modern, participatory Congress ...
the responsibility of leadership and the necessity of leadership is
to constantly involve members in the process of decision and
consensus,'' Foley says.
   According to Rep. Pat Williams, D-Mont., the troika of Wright,
Foley and soon-to-resign Democratic Whip Tony Coelho of California
has worked like this: ``Jim ... the captain, Tony the oar drummer
and Tom, the navigator. Democrats in the House and most Republicans
have great respect for the navigator.''
   Foley's office furnishings reflect his leadership philosophy.
Instead of the big, imposing desk preferred by most members of
Congress, Foley has a coffee table surrounded by enough sofas and
chairs to accommodate at least 18 visitors. His Belgian shephard,
Alice, can usually be found lounging on one of the carpets of
vibrant blues and reds.
   Another part of Foley's design for success comes from a lesson
he says he learned from Saint Exupery's ``The Little Prince,'' in
which the old courtier advises his charge that the way to get power
is to order people to do precisely what they wanted to do in the
first place.
   Whatever the tricks of his trade, the results are inarguable.
Foley and his coffee table have been at the center of some of the
most important legislation, invariably compromises, to emerge from
Congress in this decade.
   Just this year, Foley was host of the extraordinary talks that
in mid-April produced a budget agreement for the next fiscal year,
and he was pivotal in the bipartisan deal with the Bush
administration over Central America policy.
   A year earlier, he chaired the economic summit sessions that
followed the October 1987 crash of the stock market. Prior to that,
he engineered the final agreements on the Gramm-Rudman budget law,
and arms control policies shared by Congress and the White House.
   ``Tom Foley is just a very able, capable individual,'' says Bob
Michel of Illinois, the House Republican leader. ``He's well-liked
on our side, and he's also recognized as a very formidable
opponent, one who will state the case well, and is eminently fair.''
   ``He's a man of total integrity,'' said Senate Republican Leader
Bob Dole, R-Kan. ``He knows the players, knows the issues.'' And
this, from Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill.: ``I wish he were a Republican.
If he were, he could be a presidential candidate.''
   In a recent poll of senior congressional staffers, Foley was the
overwhelming choice as the most respected member of the House. And
a Republican colleague has long had a ``Foley for Speaker'' button
hidden in his desk.
   Throughout Wright's travails, Foley brushed aside such talk.
Still, he acknowledged: ``It's like asking somebody in the army
`Would you like to be general?' Sure.''
   Even that was something of a grudging confession from Foley, who
has been criticized more than once for lacking both personal and
partisan drive. He came to Washington in 1961 as an aide to Sen.
Henry M. Jackson, D-Wash., and likely would have served Jackson
until the senator's death if the boss hadn't given him a swift kick
into the elective current.
   Despite being urged by other state Democrats to run for the
House in 1964, Foley had virtually decided against it when Jackson
and Joseph Drumheller, a party bankroller, blew up at him, right at
the filing deadline, for passing the opportunity. Foley filed, and,
no small thanks to Lyndon Johnson's landslide, wrested away the 5th
District seat which had been held by Republicans for 22 years.
   He's been re-elected since, surviving close tests in 1976, 1978
and 1980, in the sprawling district, known as the Inland Empire,
stretching from the pine forests near the Canadian border to the
rolling wheat fields of the Palouse, near the Oregon line. It is an
area where conservatism still runs deep, where the pickup trucks
are adorned with bumper stickers reading: ``We Don't Brake for
Liberals.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890602-0224 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 1341EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a w PM-FoleyProfile Adv06-1stAdd   06-02 0664</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Foley Profile, Adv 06-1st Add,0676</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv 04</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday June 06</HEAD>
<HEAD>WASHN: about it.'</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``I don't have any trouble communicating with my constituency,''
says Foley. ``You seldom get elected if your constituency doesn't
like you. If you're out of touch, you will find out in the next
election.''
   His voting record is mainstream Democrat, with consistently high
marks from liberal and labor groups and low scores from the right.
But he's also earned an ``A+'' from the National Rifle Association
for his opposition to gun control legislation.
   ``I can be partisan and hold the Democratic position as well as
anyone,'' said Foley. ``My idea of partisanship is not making a
desk-pounding speech. I don't think that persuades anyone.''
   Besides, he says, ``It's hard for one party to just run over the
other. I think what's done around here that has some lasting value
usually has some element of bipartisanship about it.''
   Foley inherited his knack for getting along with Republicans
from his father, a Democrat and lawyer who managed to win election,
first as prosecutor, then as judge, in conservative Spokane. He
recalls with a grin that his GOP neighbors treated the family
``almost as practitioners of a strange religion.''
   He says his childhood was ``comfortable,'' but one in which his
father took pains to make sure young Tom understood the social
upheaval of the Great Depression by showing him the shantytowns,
the long unemployment lines and people waiting for a handout at the
back door of the hospital.
   After graduating from the University of Washington Law School in
1957, Foley seemed destined to follow in his father's footsteps. He
was a deputy city prosecutor for two years, and an assistant state
attorney general for another year. But then Jackson beckoned him to
Washington, D.C., where he became counsel for the Senate Interior
Committee.
   ``Some Democrats find him too fair,'' says Rep. Barney Frank,
D-Mass. ``He is a superb leader,'' but, in Frank's view, it's
probably a good thing that there aren't many others like Foley in
the leadership. ``We might cross the line that divides a political
body from a seminar,'' he said.
   Foley's wife, Heather, 48, a graduate of Georgetown University
Law Center, has managed his office without pay since 1970. They
have no children, but she rarely travels with her husband, staying
behind to tend to the administrative chores.
   Neither is big on the party circuit. Foley, 6-foot-4, exercises
alone or takes long walks with dog Alice to stay trim, sometimes
striding from his embassy row apartment to the Capitol, about 40
minutes. But, unlike most of his colleagues, he cares little about
organized sports.
   He is a fluent television performer, blessed with handsome
physical features, a near-photographic memory and a quick sense of
humor _ the only thing, unlike O'Neill or Wright, that he ever
fires from the hip. Once braced with a question about a state
prison inmate who challenged him in the Democratic primary, Foley
deadpanned that his opponent was running a ``guarded campaign.''
   His memory is a source for amazement among political circles. He
has been known to cite documents almost verbatim in legislative
meetings, and he almost never speaks from a prepared text. During a
visit to the Soviet Union, his hosts were so impressed by his
extemporized speeches that they speculated that his pocket
calculator was really a miniature TelePrompTer.
   Some believe Foley's destiny lies beyond the speaker's office. A
couple years back, former Democratic National Chairman Robert S.
Strauss declared ``There's no one in America, Republican or
Democrat, more qualified for the presidency than Tom Foley.''
   Dicks agrees, saying ``If we had a parliamentary system, Foley
would have been president a long time ago.''
   Meanwhile, many see him as just the right man to pull Congress
out of the partisan backwash from the John Tower and Jim Wright
battles. ``He's the great conciliator,'' said Dicks. ``He'll debate
people, but he doesn't leave people bloodied.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tues PMs, June 06</NOTE>
</DOC>
