<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 0704EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a AM-OrganicFarm Adv07-1stLd-Writethru b0322 06-02 1224</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Organic Farm, Adv 07 - 1st Ld-Writethru, b0322,1260</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv07</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wed AMs, June 7, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Idaho Farmers Show Escape From Pesticides Possible But Not Easy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 14-15, bgn, They shrank ..., to CORRECT farm size
to 103 acres and delete sugar beets, which family no longer grows; SUBS
30th graf, bgn, The work ..., to CORRECT carrot crop gross to $100,000</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FILER, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On a small patch of fertile ground in
southern Idaho, the Ihler family is quietly doing its part to
change the way America farms.
   When a growth-regulating chemical called Alar made headlines
this year as a potential health hazard and grocers yanked apples
from their counters, the Ihlers shook their heads with an
I-told-you-so smile.
   When their potato-farming neighbors panicked at a recent
government report questioning the safety of aldicarb, a widely used
insecticide, the Ihlers weren't surprised.
   ``Agriculture is in the dark ages,'' said Rick Ihler.
   The Ihlers _ brothers Rick and Terry and their father, Dick _
have preached for years that the path to agricultural enlightenment
lies in organic farming. Suddenly people seem to be listening _
even in conservative regions like these irrigated drylands, where
new farming ideas run up against deep-rooted traditions.
   Pesticides and chemical fertilizers, which brought farmers here
and across the country into the green revolution, now are getting
bad press.
   Consumers are clamoring for organic fruits and vegetbles. A
Louis Harris poll conducted in November for Organic Gardening
magazine said 84 percent of Americans said they would buy
organically grown food if it was available, and 49 percent would
pay more for it.
   More mainstream farmers _ jolted by consumers' concerns, rising
chemical costs and depleted soils _ are taking a second look at a
farming approach they once dismissed as a fad practiced by
sandal-wearing hippies.
   The lesson from the Ihlers' Holly Farms is that organic farming
can work, but it doesn't come easy.
   They've had to fight not only insects, weather and weeds, but a
firmly entrenched agribusiness establishment geared toward chemical
dependence.
   ``To farm organically is to buck the system,'' Rick Ihler said
recently, taking a break from planting carrots on a windy day.
``Organic farming is still considered off-the-wall in Idaho.''
   The Ihlers made the switch to organic farming in 1981. They had
been farming more than 4,000 acres, most of it on rented land. Like
many farmers, they depended on bank loans to make it from one
harvest to the next.
   ``We got fed up with it. All we were doing was financing the
banker's pocketbook,'' Rick said.
   They shrank their operation back to the 103-acre family farm and
set about finding natural substitutes for the manmade chemicals
they had been using.
   ``We learned from trial and error,'' Rick said. Today, they grow
carrots, peas, onions, barley, hay, potatoes, radishes and beans on
their irrigated acreage.
   Their methods range from low-tech to high; from spreading
composted sheep dung to dragging a high-voltage weed zapper behind
a tractor. They rotate crops, sow nitrogen-fixing plants such as
peas and clover, and use natural products such as kelp extracts and
micro-fungi.
   Dick Ihler, 56, a tattooed Korean War veteran who is clearly not
part of the sandal-wearing crowd, nevertheless acknowledges talking
to carrots and experimenting with pyramids and crystals as energy
sources for the crops.
   ``There are a lot of things you can't tell people, because they
won't believe you,'' said Rick.
   Not that they aren't asking. The Ihlers have received calls from
dozens of farmers wanting to know how to go organic. Organic
farming trade groups around the country are being swamped with
requests for information.
   Spurred by the recent pesticide scares, mainstream trade groups
and researchers also are pursuing ways to reduce farmers'
dependence on manmade pesticides and fertilizers.
   Yet organic farmers still are a tiny minority. Even in
California, where most of the country's organic produce is grown,
organic farms make up less than 1 percent of the total.
   In Idaho the numbers are even smaller.
   Dick Ihler grew up here, but he's still trying to convince some
neighbors he wasn't corrupted by the 16 years he spent in
California before moving back to the fammily farm in 1972.
   Holly Farms operates outside the traditional marketing and
distribution system. A typical Idaho potato farmer, for example,
must sell his spuds to one of a few big corporate processors. The
Ihlers have had to cultivate their customers as carefully as their
fields.
   ``We tried to sell our carrots to a local hospital. They
couldn't buy them, because of contracts with the big distributors.
The school system was the same,'' Dick Ihler said.
   Holly Farms now ships produce to 37 states. Customers include
food cooperatives, natural food stores, and an organic baby-food
maker in Vermont.
   ``We researched markets for five years before we ever planted a
crop,'' Rick said.
   Holly Farms uses a private certification program to back up the
farm's ``organically grown'' labels. They keep daily logs of what
is put on or in the ground. ``If you spit on the ground, you better
write it down,'' Dick said.
   They guard their property against errant chemicals used by
neighbors. When farmers upstream used fungicides on their fields,
the Ihlers treated their irrigation water to remove the chemicals.
They complained long and loud enough to local crop dusters that the
airplanes now make wide detours around their farm.
   The work has paid off. Holly Farms still operates under a
bankruptcy order protecting it from a bank that tried to call its
loans due, so the Ihlers are shy about giving figures on income.
But Rick said their carrot crop alone, which is about 60 percent of
their business, grossed $100,000 last year.
   The farm supports 14 people in three families. It also employs
18 seasonal workers and at least 50 at harvest time.
   The farm's reputation is growing, with a 1,200 percent increase
in sales during the past five years, Rick said. About 100 people
visit the farm each year, some of them pilgrims who camp out by the
stream to soak up the farm's ``energy high'' and drink carrot juice.
   The Ihlers praise organic farming, yet warn it won't work for
everybody.
   Even before the term organic was popular, their family farm was
relatively chemical-free, in contrast to much farm land, which Rick
said has been propped up with chemicals for so long it has lost its
natural resistance to pests.
   ``What does a drug addict do when you cut him off from his
heroin or cocaine? He goes through withdrawal symptoms,'' Rick
said. ``The land is like a living being. It goes through
withdrawal, too.''
   That and a lack of experience with organic methods have doomed
more than one would-be organic farmer, Rick said. ``So many farmers
don't want to do any homework,'' he said.
   One secret of organic farming is caring as much about the food's
quality as the consumer does, Rick said.
   When they discovered that their carrot bags were labeled with an
ink containing a potentially toxic chemical, the Ihlers recalled
all their carrots.
   ``Our sales jumped 300 percent after that,'' Rick said. ``People
saw our concern about quality.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   David Foster is the AP Northwest regional
reporter, based in Seattle.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed AMs, June 7</NOTE>
