<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     06-02 0739</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0771</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The productivity of American workers slipped
in the first quarter while unit labor costs shot up more than 6
percent on an annual basis, the government said in a report
analysts cited as proof both of a slowing economy and stubborn
inflation.
   The Labor Department's revised figures for the first three
months of the year showed a 1.1 percent decline in non-farm
business productivity at an annual rate, down from the 0.5 percent
gain reported in preliminary first-quarter data issued last month.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carl Icahn ended a long and contentious
association with Texaco Inc., selling a Wall Street-record 42.32
million share block of the oil company's stock.
   The shares sold for $49 each Thursday, making the entire block
worth more than $2.07 billion. Texaco spokeswoman Anita Larsen said
the shares were bought by the investment firms Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc., Salomon Brothers Inc. and Goldman Sachs &amp; Co.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   High interest rates depressed the rate of
private construction in April, but the government said that total
construction spending rose a weak 0.1 percent due to an upturn in
work on public projects.
   The Commerce Department on Thursday reported a total increase in
new spending to $414.9 billion on a seasonally adjusted annual rate
after declines of three consecutive months. That was 4.7 percent
above a year earlier.
   The last time construction spending fell for three straight
months had been just before the start of the 1981-82 recession.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Major U.S. retailers reported sluggish May
sales, fresh evidence that consumers have curbed spending because
of heavy debt loads.
   Tallies released Thursday varied depending on the type of
retailer, but industry-wide results looked weak, analysts said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OPEC ministers are getting ready to
negotiate a new oil production strategy, amid price and output
demands aimed at changing the current cartel accord that has seen a
rise in world crude prices.
   Ministers of the 13-nation Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries were gathering at their Vienna, Austria headquarters for
a mid-year meeting set to begin Monday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's plan to keep $50 billion in
borrowed S&amp;L rescue funds ``off budget'' to avoid swelling the
federal deficit was rejected by a House committee whose chairman
labeled the approach ``voodoo accounting.''
   With only one Democrat supporting Bush's plan, the House
Government Operations Committee voted 22-15 on Thursday to include
the initial $50 billion taxpayer share of the bailout as part of
the federal budgets for this year and fiscal 1990 and 1991.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Representatives of 151 governments in the
World Bank will make about $10 billion available over the next
three years to support Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady's plan
for cutting debt in the Third World.
   Under guidelines announced Thursday after more than two days of
closed-door board meetings, $375 million of that new money will be
available to apply to Mexico's existing $108 billion debt.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   KLM Royal Dutch Airlines says is part of an
investment group led by Los Angeles investor Alfred Checchi that
has submitted a friendly bid to buy NWA Inc., the parent of
Northwest Airlines.
   KLM spokesman Peter Wellhuener said Thursday the Dutch state
airliner has ``a commitment to an American investment group headed
by Mr. Alfred Checchi to take an indirect interest'' in the company
bidding for Northwest. No other details were released.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New York Stock Exchange has approved for
trading a portfolio of 500 stocks priced at about $5 million per
unit billed as the first of its kind to provide ownership of each
of the component equities.
   Each portfolio unit will include 126,000 shares of stock based
on the Standard &amp; Poor's 500 stock index, ranging from 3,100 shares
of Exxon Corp. to nine of the Monarch Machine Tool Co. based on
current caluclations.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices gained ground Thursday in a session dominated by a
record-sized transaction in Texaco shares just as the market
closed. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 10.48 points
to 2,490.63.
   The dollar finished mixed against major foreign currencies.
   Bond prices were little changed in advance of the government's
May employment report.
   Feeder cattle futures prices soared; grains and soybeans ended
mostly higher; copper futures prices dropped sharply while precious
metals rose; and energy futures were mixed.
</TEXT>
