<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 0213EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-RetailSales Bjt   06-02 0777</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Retail Sales, Bjt,0800</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chain Store Sales Growth Meager in May</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Retail Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Weak sales at many of the country's biggest store chains in May
suggests consumers have adopted a cautious attitude about spending.
   A rise in interest rates over the winter led to increases in
many adjustable rate mortgages, which may be discouraging consumers
from indulging in expensive goods that typically are bought on
credit.
   Higher prices for gasoline may have crimped purchasing power a
bit in May while some consumers may have decided to postpone
shopping trips so they could replenish savings depleted when they
paid tax bills in April.
   Sales tallies reported Thursday varied, depending on the type of
retailer, but industry-wide results looked sluggish, according to
analysts.
   ``I think they show the consumer is very cautious,'' said Carl
Palash, senior economist at McCarthy, Crisanti &amp; Maffei Inc.
``People are probably looking at their mortgage rates going up _
those who have adjustable rate mortgages _ and holding back on
spending.''
   Chains with a heavy emphasis on women's wear did better than
general merchandisers. Sales at some general-merchandise stores may
have been hurt by abundant rainfall in the Northeast during May.
   Women's apparel merchants have been reporting improving sales
all year as fashions get a better reception than those of the past
two years.
   Gains reported by several clothing retailers appeared better
than they really were because May's sales were compared with last
year's relatively low volumes.
   An analysis by Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. indicated most
sectors of the retailing business took in less in May than in April.
   The brokerage said its weighted average of 37 merchants' sales
at stores open at least a year rose 4.2 percent in May after
April's 7 percent gain.
   Drexel's index of sales at 14 department stores and discounters
rose 3.8 percent last month following a 6.9 percent April increase
and its index of 12 specialty apparel and shoe retailers went up
7.6 percent compared with 11.2 percent in April. The specialty hard
goods index, which includes sales of electronics, toys and
furniture, rose 3.4 percent vs. April's 3 percent rise.
   The results Thursday were from some of the biggest general
merchandise chains in the United States, plus apparel retailers.
Monthly retail sales from the government are more comprehensive and
include the take at other types of establishments such as auto
dealers, supermarkets and restaurants.
   Among those reporting were Sears, Roebuck and Co., the nation's
biggest merchant, which said sales in the four weeks ended May 27
rose 5.3 percent to $2.5 billion from $2.38 billion in May 1988.
Sales at stores open at least a year, called same or comparable
sales, rose 3.1 percent.
   Retailers and industry analysts consider same-store sales a more
accurate indication of a company's performance than totals that
include sales at new stores. Not every retailer discloses results
on this basis.
   Kurt Barnard, publisher of Barnard's Retail Marketing Report, an
industry newsletter, said Sears' results suggest customers are
losing enthusiasm about the nationwide chain's new low-pricing
policy.
   ``That does not augur very well for the success of their
so-called everyday low pricing strategy,'' said Barnard, estimating
that the retail giant must maintain 5 percent same-store sales
growth to keep its profits ahead of inflation.
   Sears introduced the strategy earlier this year in a bid to
compete with fast-growing chains such as Wal-Mart Stores Inc.,
which regularly reports double-digit sales growth.
   Wal-Mart, currently ranked No. 3, said May sales rose 25 percent
to $2.03 billion from 1988's $1.63 billion. On a comparable-store
basis, sales increased 11 percent.
   Second-ranked K mart Corp. reported a sales increase of 2.5
percent for the four weeks ended May 24 to $2.19 billion from the
previous year's $2.14 billion. On a comparable-store basis, sales
were off 0.6 percent.
   K mart earlier had predicted its take would be disappointing and
Thursday attributed the weakness to sluggish demand for clothes,
especially ladies' wear.
   At J.C.Penney Co., pre-Mother's Day sales of women's dresses and
fine jewelry were strong but men's sportswear sagged. Total store
and catalog sales edged up 1.7 percent to $1.02 billion in May from
$1.01 billion a year earlier. Same-store sales slipped 0.9 percent.
Penney's sales growth was better after subtracting from last year's
totals sales of now-discontinued items.
   Specialty apparel seller Limited Inc. said sales rose 9 percent
in May to $310.7 million from $285.4 million the year before.
   The Limited results excluded the revenue taken in at Lerner
Woman, which Limited has announced it is selling. Including Lerner
Woman, Limited's sales went up 18 percent in the month. On a
comparable-store basis, sales rose 11 percent in May.
</TEXT>
