<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 0227EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Texaco-Icahn Bjt   06-02 0817</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Texaco-Icahn, Bjt,0844</SECOND>
<HEAD>Speculation About USX Future After Icahn Sells Texaco Stake</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carl Icahn's sale of a record 42.32
million-share block of Texaco Inc. stock has fueled Wall Street
speculation about the takeover strategist's plans and whether they
involve an old target: USX Corp.
   Trading in USX stock was halted near the close of the New York
Stock Exchange session Thursday due to too many buy orders and not
enough sell orders after Icahn sold his Texaco stock. USX finished
the day up $2.62{ at $37.50 a share in NYSE composite trading.
   Icahn ended his long and often bitter involvement with Texaco by
selling his 17.3 percent stake _ which made him the company's
biggest shareholder _ for $49 a share or a total of $2.07 billion.
The block trade was the most expensive ever on the NYSE, according
to Catherine Maroney, a Big Board spokeswoman.
   Texaco closed down $2.12{ at $49 a share.
   ``We think the company has improved a great deal in a year and a
half and we like to think we played a small part in helping them to
do that, but we felt it was time to move on and we wish the company
and management well,'' Icahn said in a telephone interview.
   Icahn declined to comment further and it was not immediately
known how he planned to use proceeds of the stock sale and from a
special $8-a-share dividend Texaco paid all shareholders earlier
this year under a wide-ranging restructuring.
   Outsiders have estimated Icahn paid an average of $36.60 a share
for his stake, giving him a potential gain of $12.40 a share on the
stock sale alone. The stock sale plus the dividend puts Icahn's
profit at more than $$800 million, calculating from an average
share purchase price of $36.60.
   But there has been widespread speculation that Icahn, who
already has a major stake in USX, might make a play for the oil and
steel giant. He already has made one bid for USX _ a $7.2 billion
offer that he abandoned in early 1987 after the USX board rejected
it.
   Possibly heightening the speculation was the retirement
Wednesday of USX Chairman David M. Roderick, who led the company in
its battle against Icahn.
   The company underwent a major restructuring under Roderick,
including the writedown of $3 billion in mostly steel assets and
the $10 billion acquisitions of Marathon Oil Co. and Texas Oil &amp;
Gas Corp. The $9.9 billion in revenue from those companies last
year accounted for nearly two-thirds of USX total revenue of $16.9
billion and compared with $5.8 billion in steel revenue.
   There was no answer at USX offices in Pittsburgh when a reporter
called for comment late Thursday.
   Texaco spokeswoman Anita Larsen said Icahn's shares were bought
by the investment firms Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., Salomon
Brothers Inc. and Goldman Sachs &amp; Co.
   Ms. Larsen said the shares remained under restrictions set by a
January agreement between Icahn and Texaco, which was aimed at
ensuring the stock would not end up in the hands of a potentially
hostile suitor.
   Ms. Larsen said Texaco had no further comment on the sale.
   Icahn, who is chairman of Trans World Airlines Inc., acquired
about 24 million Texaco shares from Australian investor Robert
Holmes a Court after the 1987 stock market crash. TWA already owned
5.9 million Texaco shares and Icahn further increased its stake
following the purchases from Holmes a Court.
   Icahn complained that Texaco management was not doing enough to
raise the company's stock price and indicated he might mount a
takeover of the company. His threats complicated Texaco's attempt
to extricate itself from bankruptcy proceedings and a $10.35
billion damage judgment it was ordered to pay Pennzoil Co.
   Texaco's board rejected Icahn's later proposal for a $14.5
billion buyout and he failed to unseat the board in a proxy fight
at Texaco's annual meeting a year ago.
   He also fought with Texaco over the terms of its bankruptcy
reorganization plan. The company sought protection from creditors
to avoid posting a multibillion-dollar bond while it appealed the
1985 Pennzoil verdict, which resulted from Texaco's acquisition of
Getty Oil Co.
   After Texaco emerged from bankruptcy protection, Icahn bickered
with management over its plan to sell billions of dollars of assets
and pay stockholders the special $8 share dividend, or a total of
about $1.9 billion.
   These issues were resolved in the January standstill agreement,
which altered Texaco's ``poison pill'' takeover defense but also
limited how Icahn could sell his stock and barred him from making a
takeover attempt against Texaco for seven years.
   Thursday's Texaco block trade was the second-largest in terms of
shares, after the 1986 sale of 48.79 million-share block of
Navistar International Corp. That block sold for $10 a share, or
$487.9 million, and previously had been the most expensive single
block trade.
</TEXT>
