<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 0227EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-InsuranceRegulation     06-02 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Insurance Regulation,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>Consumer Groups Call For Tighter State Controls</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tighter state controls on the insurance
industry, including full monitoring and comparative disclosure of
prices for auto policies, were proposed by an independent agents
association and consumers groups.
   In unveiling a ``national model'' Thursday for state insurance
departments, the organizations called also for stricter ethics
standards for regulators, specified periods for the settlement of
claims, and the establishment of a nationwide computer network to
share consumer complaint data.
   The model, forwarded to the governors of all the states, was a
joint project of the Consumer Insurance Interest Group, an
independent advocacy federation headed by Esther Peterson, former
consumer adviser to Presidents Lyndon Johnson and Jimmy Carter, and
the National Association of Professional Insurance Agents, also
known as PIA National.
   The plan also was backed by the Consumer Federation of America,
the National Insurance Consumer Organization, and Public Citizen.
   Mrs. Peterson called it ``a yardstick that regulators and
legislators can use to enhance the effectiveness of insurance
regulation in their states.''
   PIA National President David L. Ream said ``both consumers and
insurance agents will benefit if minimum standards are implemented
in all the states. As a result, consumers would be able to receive
price comparison information more readily, and agents would have
greater assurance that the companies they place their customers'
business with are financially sound.''
   Highlights of the proposal:
   _Strengthen the size and quality of state regulatory agencies by
allocating to their budgets at least 10 percent of the premium
taxes insurers pay annually to the states. Most agencies now
operate with much smaller budgets, equivalent, on average, to 6
percent of the premium taxes collected.
   _Bar regulatory officials from entering the employment of
insurance companies for one year after leaving their official
positions.
   _Draw up specified time periods in which claims should be paid,
and maintain and disclose complaint information by company and line
of insurance.
   _Conduct routine financial examinations of companies to make
sure funds are available to pay claims.
   _Maintain ``readily accessible'' price information on personal
auto insurance, so conumers can make one-stop comparisons.
   _Appoint independent consumer advocates or councils for advice
on regulatory policies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
