<DOCNO> AP890602-0237 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 0231EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-StockBaskets Bjt   06-02 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stock Baskets, Bjt,0635</SECOND>
<HEAD>New York Stock Exchange Approves $5 Million Trading Unit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New York Stock Exchange has approved for
trading a ``basket'' of 500 stocks and billed as the first of its
kind in that it provides ownership of each of the actual component
stocks.
   Units of the portfolio _ valued now at about $5 million apiece _
will include 126,000 shares of stock reflecting those in the
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 stock index.
   Existing stock ``basket'' investments traded on the American and
Philadelphia stock exchanges represent the S&amp;P index itself, rather
than the actual shares that make up the index.
   The Securities and Exchange Commission, the federal agency that
regulates the nation's securities markets, must approve the new
instrument. NYSE officials said Thursday they hoped it would begin
trading in September.
   NYSE officials said their new stock basket, to be called the
Exchange Stock Portfolio, was designed for trading by large
institutional investors and not individuals.
   The number of shares of each company in the unit is weighted to
reflect the index. For example each unit would have holdings
ranging in size from 3,100 shares of Exxon Corp. to nine of Monarch
Machine Tool Co.
   ``You are a shareholder of a stock,'' Donald Solodar, NYSE
senior vice president of capital markets, told a news conference.
``You are not somebody trading in an index participation index. You
will have all the shares in your account.''
   The basket will include 462 NYSE-listed stocks and 38 traded on
the American Stock Exchange or the nation's over-the-counter
markets. NYSE officials said they would ask the other exchanges for
permission to trade their stocks in its portfolio.
   The value of the stocks currently in the index would be about $5
million, officials said. That compares with about $3,100 per unit
for stock baskets now traded on the Philadelphia and American stock
exchanges.
   Solodar said the new portfolio could help ease market volatility
that may be heightened by waves of computerized program trades, as
occurred during the October 1987 stock market crash.
   Program trading is a strategy by which speculators attempt to
profit from disparities between the prices of stock index futures
and options and the prices of stocks represented by the indexes.
   Because the strategy generally involves large numbers of shares
traded by Wall Street firms or institutional investors, it has been
blamed for causing or worsening big market price swings.
   The new product could add capital that market players could use
to try to balance a one-sided market, Solodar said. Trading will be
governed by a ``call market'' in which officials will be able to
point out signs of trading imbalances every 15 minutes.
   In a statement, NYSE Chairman John J. Phelan Jr. said studies
following the market crash recommended developing such an equities
portfolio that would include ownership of the stocks.
   ``The exchange stock portfolio approved today by the NYSE board
of directors incorporates those recommendations, and should meet
the needs of our customers,'' he said.
   The SEC in March approved the sale of stock baskets on the
Philadelphia and American exchanges. Those are priced according to
S&amp;P 500, which essentially allows investors to bet on the overall
direction of the stock market as a whole.
   Those products are based on the current value of indexes of
stocks and do not provide ownership of their shares. Investors
receive quarterly cash payments equal to a proportionate share of
any regular cash dividend declared on the component stocks of the
basket.
   The nation's two futures markets have challenged those baskets,
saying they are thinly disguised stock index futures and therefore
should be limited to futures exchanges.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890602-0238 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 0234EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-ObjectionableShows Bjt   06-02 0611</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Objectionable Shows, Bjt,0632</SECOND>
<HEAD>Researcher Finds Strong Consumer Distaste for Objectionable TV Shows</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A survey says most Americans would support
advertisers that withdraw commercials from TV programs that some
viewers find objectionable and would back a boycott of companies
that sponsor such shows.
   One in four people surveyed said the government should make it
illegal to show objectionable material on television, according to
the survey released Thursday by the consumer research firm
Oxtoby-Smith Inc.
   Respondents were asked to describe what they regarded as
objectionable and 74 percent cited excessive violence, 67 percent
sex, 60 percent profanity, 58 percent cited ``subjects that should
be private'' and 41 percent ethnic stereotypes.
   The survey comes as a number of individuals and groups upset
with what they say is excessive sex, violence, profanity or
stereotyping in TV programs have captured attention with calls for
advertisers to withdraw ads from those shows.
   Joseph Smith, president of Oxtoby-Smith, said those calls appear
to have ``touched a sensitive, pervasive and perhaps festering
public concern.''
   ``The naive supposition that the recent flurry of protest
against `objectionable' programming reflects the opinions of a
small but vocal minority on society's fringe simply isn't supported
by what we've learned,'' he said.
   But several advertising and television executives questioned the
significance of the poll's findings, noting that how a question is
phrased may have a lot to do with how it is answered.
   They said, for instance, that people who say they support
withdrawing ads from an ``objectionable'' show may disagree on what
is objectionable.
   ``It's a socially acceptable response. There are not many people
who would give a negative response to something like this,'' said
Paul Sonkin, vice president of network audience research at ABC.
   Thomas Winner, media director at the ad agency
Campbell-Mithun-Esty, said he didn't think there was much
significance in the poll results.
   ``If someone called, what would you say? And would you really
care about this if someone didn't call?'' he said.
   But David Smith, a marketing executive at his father's firm,
said the poll questions were designed to be ``as dispassionate as
possible.''
   The survey relied on telephone interviews conducted May 4-10
with a randomly-selected sample of 500 adults across the country.
The survey had a margin of error of plus or minus 5 percentage
points.
   Oxtoby-Smith, which has been in business since 1956 and has
counted Block Drug Co., Bristol Myers Co., MCI Communication Corp.
and Volvo among its clients, said it commissioned the poll on its
own and not for any client.
   Several major advertisers, including Tambrands Inc., Ralston
Purina Co. and Domino's Pizza Inc., have withdrawn advertising from
shows such as the Fox network's ``Married ... with Children'' and
NBC's ``Saturday Night Live'' because of such concerns.
   Sixty-eight percent of those surveyed said it was a ``good
idea'' for ``advertisers to stop advertising in programs some
viewers found objectionable'' while 72 percent said it was a good
idea for ``consumers not to buy products of advertisers in programs
they find objectionable.''
   Oxtoby-Smith said 49 percent of those surveyed said the amount
of objectionable material on television bothers them a lot.
   Twenty-five percent said the government should make it illegal
to show objectionable material, 36 percent said objectionable
material should be kept off the air but not necessarily through a
government ban and 69 percent called for restricting objectionable
material to late-night hours.
   The Rev. Donald Wildmon, executive director of the American
Family Association in Tupelo, Miss., which has encouraged
advertisers to withdraw from shows it finds offensive, said he was
delighted by the results of the poll.
   ``Our time has arrived,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890602-0239 </DOCNO>
