<FIRST>r f PM-HenleyPurchase     06-02 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Henley Purchase,0250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Henley Recapitalizing Subsidiary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAMPTON, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Henley Group Inc., which recently paid $165
million to become sole owner of an aerospace and industrial
products company, says it will invest $175 million to recapitalize
the business.
   Henley agreed in April to buy a 50 percent share of PA Holdings
Corp. from Wasserstein Perella &amp; Co. Inc. The purchase was
completed Thursday, Henley said in a news release.
   Henley and Wasserstein Perella paid a total of $1.2 billion to
the parent corporation of PA Holdings Corp. in August 1988, and
each received a 50 percent share in PA Holdings.
   Henley said Thursday it will invest $175 million to adjust PA
Holdings' capital structure, a project it expects to finish in July
or August.
   The company said it is recapitalizing PA Holdings in order to
bring its capital structure in line with Henley's business strategy.
   The investment consists of a $100 million capital contribution
and a $75 million payment for PA Holdings bonds.
   PA Holdings also will offer $250 million in bonds to the public,
and will restructure the $235 million in bonds issued last year
when Henley and Wasserstein Perella bought the company.
   PA Holdings will use proceeds from the public bond sale and
Henley's investment to repay approximately $400 million in
outstanding bank debts.
   PA Holdings' products include commercial and military aircraft
landing gear, aircraft flight and engine controls, and
friction-braking material for the automotive industry.
