<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 1028EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-EEC-Airlines     06-02 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EEC-Airlines,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>EEC to Be Vigilant on Airline Mergers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Community favors
deregulation of air transportation but it will strictly control
airline mergers, an EEC official said Friday.
   European Commissioner for Competition Leon Brittan said the EEC
will be ``vigilant'' in controling airline mergers in the run up to
a single European market for air transport in the 1990s.
   ``Increased concentration in a sector which is already
characterised by high barriers to entry must be watched
carefully,'' Brittan said in a speech to the International Air
Transport Association's Aviation Symposium in Marrakesh, Morocco. A
summary of the speech was made available in Brussels.
   Brittan said that Common Market air transport market should have
less regulation, less bureacracy, more competition and cheaper
fares. But the official added that liberalization must be
accompanied by strict enforcement of anti-trust rules.
   He said the EEC did not plan to adopt the ``laissez-faire''
attitude of the U.S. antitrust authorities who have allowed
numerous mergers of airlines in the United States following
deregulation of the U.S. industry.
   Brittan made his comments amid moves by some European airlines
to cooperate more closely.
   Scandinavian Airlines System offered in April to buy a minority
stake in Sabena, Belgium's state-owned airline. Sabena is currently
negotiating a possible alliance with British Airways and KLM Royal
Dutch Airlines.
   On Thursday, Iberia Airlines said that the Spanish national
carrier will probably merge with other European airlines in the
1990s.
   Brittan said that one of the EEC's main concerns would be to
preserve and promote the position of new carriers as well as
smaller regional and charter airlines.
   ``If all such carriers were to be swallowed up through various
forms of cooperation or conglomeration with larger airlines, the
competitive atmosphere would be rather bleak,'' he said.
   Brittan also said that the EEC would have to adopt rules giving
nationals of other EEC member states the right to own shares in
airlines anywhere in the Community.
   He said that currently restrictions on the ownership of airlines
are contained in the laws and bilateral air service agreements of
almost all the EEC members.
   Brittan also said that the EEC might tighten the conditions
under which airlines are still free to share capacity and revenue.
These so-called exemptions to the EEC's competition rules expire in
January 1991.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
