<SECOND>PM-Auto Incentives, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0030,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ford, GM Issue New Incentive Package</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th and 9th grafs: General Motors ... with 2 grafs to update
with today's Buick announcement, no pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A day after its previous plan expired,
Ford Motor Co. issued a new incentive package with rebates ranging
from $500 to $4,000 and interest rates as low as 2.9 percent for
two-year loans.
   The new package, announced Thursday, includes a wide variety of
Ford, Lincoln and Mercury cars and trucks.
   The plan comes in addition to one the company began May 20
covering subcompact cars. Both programs expire July 31.
   Automakers use incentives to shrink vehicle inventories. Car and
truck sales this year have been running behind last year's pace,
while production schedules have been changed only slightly.
   Analysts have speculated for months that carmakers may be forced
into widespread layoffs and plant shutdowns during the second half
of the year to further reduce inventories and give time for
retooling factories for the coming model year.
   Ford's announcement Thursday came the day after Chrysler Corp.
expanded its existing rebate program to include Jeep Cherokee and
Wagoneer models.
   There are no expiration dates on Chrysler incentives.
   Meantime, General Motors Corp.'s Oldsmobile Division announced
new incentives Thursday and its Buick Division followed suit today.
Olds ebates range from $800 to $1,500 and Buick's are between $500
and $1,500.
   Both programs also give buyers the option of cut-rate financing,
with interest rates as low as 2.9 percent on two-year loans. Other
incentives for other GM cars and trucks expire Monday.
</TEXT>
