<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   06-02 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Post Early Gains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were mostly
higher in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade as the
market continued a turnaround begun in the previous session.
   Thursday's strong advance was largely attributed to renewed
buying by traders who had sold the market in May in anticipation of
lower prices down the road. Prices indeed fell as growing
conditions improved, and the short-sellers returned as buyers.
   Rumors of Soviet purchases of U.S. corn lent additional support
to the markets this morning.
   Soybean prices got a further boost from indications of light
farmer selling overnight and stronger European markets for soybean
meal and oil.
   Forecasts for strong thunderstorms and hail in the ripening
wheat fields of the central Plains provided some early support to
wheat futures prices.
   In early trading, wheat was { cent to 1} cents higher with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.89} a bushel; corn was } cent
to 2} cents higher with July at $2.61} a bushel; oats were \ cent
to 1} cents higher with July at $1.72 a bushel; soybeans were 1
cent to 5 cents higher with July at $7.10} a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly lower in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .20 cent lower to .25 cent higher with June at
68.95 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent lower to .03 cent
higher with August at 77.90 cents a pound; live hogs were .13 cent
lower to .03 cent higher with June at 48.27 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were .27 cent to .47 cent lower with July at 30.05
cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled higher on Thursday, led by
limit gains in the feeder cattle market.
</TEXT>
