<FIRST>u f PM-Eastern 2ndLd-Writethru   06-02 0811</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0836</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Says It Will Make Temporary Changes In Wages, Benefits</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: NEW grafs 1-7 to UPDATE with details from Eastern spokesman;
picks up 5th graf pvs bg'ng, On Thursday, ... DELETES grafs 19-24 pvs,
bgng Shapiro dismissed... to tighten.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines said today it plans ``austerity
measures'' that will include temporary changes in wages and
benefits for its non-union employees and reassignment of some
management workers to permanently replace striking machinists.
   The company declined to elaborate but did state that the changes
were aimed at satisfying creditors of the strikebound airline,
indicating wage and benefit cuts were likely.
   In a brief statement, Eastern said the changes were needed
because of financial difficulties created by the 3-month-old strike
against the carrier and its bankruptcy proceeding.
   The company scheduled an afternoon news conference in Miami to
outline what it called changes in ``wages, vacation policies and
other benefits areas.''
   Eastern spokesman James Ashlock in Miami described the changes
as austerity measures aimed at satisfying creditors as the airline
moves ahead with its recently announced plan to reorganize as a
smaller carrier.
   Because Eastern aims to reduce its workforce to 17,000 employees
after having nearly 30,000 before the strike, middle-management
positions were likely to be targeted, Ashlock said.
   ``A lot of people will be offered other positions,'' he said,
noting that many middle-level management people have been
performing new jobs to replace the striking union workers.
   Eastern currently has 4,500 to 5,000 non-union employees, most
of them in management positions, who have been running the airline
since Machinists, pilots and flight attendants walked out on March
4.
   On Thursday, an investor group seeking to buy Eastern was given
a last chance by a federal bankruptcy judge and submitted a revised
plan.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland had given the group led
by Chicago commodities trader Joseph Ritchie until 6 p.m. EDT
Thursday to submit a business plan for Eastern to the airline and
to the committee representing its creditors.
   Ritchie said late Thursday he submitted a detailed business plan
and proposal just before the judge's deadline. He also said he
scheduled meetings with representatives of Eastern and its
creditors.
   ``I have now delivered a realistic plan for the rebirth of
Eastern that includes more-than-adequate financing, a firm
commitment to growth and the unanimous support of Eastern's
unions,'' Ritchie said in a statement.
   Lifland set another hearing for 2 p.m. today on the Ritchie
group's offer.
   The bankruptcy court wrangling is important because the strikers
want parent Texas Air Corp. to sell the airline, but Texas Air
Chairman Frank Lorenzo wants to continue to run Eastern but as a
smaller carrier. Lifland and David I. Shapiro, the court-appointed
examiner for Eastern, have considerable influence over what happens
next.
   Miami-based Eastern, one of the nation's most unprofitable
airlines, has been mired in a strike and Chapter 11 bankruptcy
protection for nearly three months.
   In a separate development, Eastern agreed Thursday to pay $3.1
million to several of its employee benefit plans to settle a
federal government complaint alleging the airline tapped those
plans to pay corporate expenses. The airline entered into the
consent agreement with the government without admitting or denying
that it had committed any wrongdoing.
   And on Capitol Hill, the Senate approved a non-binding
resolution urging the bankruptcy court to consider appointing a
special trustee to replace Lorenzo in running the carrier. On a
94-0 vote, lawmakers included the language in a $3.3 billion
spending bill for this year.
   At the bankruptcy hearing, Shapiro asked Lifland to give the
Ritchie group until Monday to discuss its offer with Eastern and
its creditors. Shapiro said he didn't believe the buyout proposal
was viable but he wanted to ``lean over backwards to be fair.''
   Leaders of Eastern's unions continued to hope that the airline
might be sold.
   ``Nothing's ever the last chance,'' Charles Bryan, head of the
striking Machinists union, told reporters outside the bankruptcy
courthouse in Manhattan.
   Shapiro said he had been poised to recommend that both Ritchie's
proposal and a rival offer from a group headed by former Piedmont
Airlines Chairman William Howard be dismissed. But, he said,
Ritchie and his associates dissuaded him at a meeting early
Thursday, saying they'd raised the minimum $100 million in equity
Shapiro had earlier demanded from any potential buyer.
   Although the group had met that requirement, it still lacked a
viable business plan for running the airline, Shapiro said.
   AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland said Thursday that 13 unions had
agreed to guarantee up to $5 million each to make the $50 million
available. The Eastern pilots and Machinists would determine the
use of the loan in the purchase of the airline, he said.
   Under the Ritchie proposal, Eastern's unions would have a
``substantial'' equity stake in the airline, Bryan said.
</TEXT>
