<FIRST>r f BC-HoneywellSemiconductor     06-02 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Honeywell Semiconductor,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Honeywell To Sell Semiconductor Unit To Atmel Corp.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETSY HENDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honeywell Inc. announced Friday it plans to
sell its Colorado Springs, Colo., semiconductor unit to Atmel
Corp., a privately held company based in San Jose, Calif.
   Terms of the agreement were not disclosed. Honeywell in November
announced it was looking for a buyer for the unit, which
manufactures custom and semi-custom integrated circuits primarily
for computer producers.
   Atmel is purchasing substantially all of the assets and assuming
certain liabilities of the semiconductor unit, which employees
about 1,100 workers, said Honeywell spokeswoman Susan Eich.
   Some jobs will be cut for the sale, which is expected to be
completed this summer. Of those still on the payroll, most will be
transferred to Atmel and some will be retained by Honeywell, Eich
said.
   Honeywell said Atmel will continue to supply products and
services to Honeywell and Honeywell customers.
   Atmel was founded in 1984 by George Perlegos, who has been
active in the semiconductor industry since 1972. The company
produces non-volatile, programmable memory and logic semiconductors
for both military and commercial markets.
   Perlegos said the acquisition will help his company's growth and
will help efforts to keep semiconductor manufacturing in the United
States.
   Honeywell is an international control company that provides
products, systems and services for the home and building,
industrial, space and aviation, and defense and marine markets. The
company has 78,000 employees worldwide, with 1988 sales of $7.1
billion.
   Honeywell, which got out of the computer business in 1986, no
longer needs extensive semiconductor operations, Eich said.
   ``We don't have a strategic interest in being in the merchant
semiconductor market,'' she said.
   Honeywell has a similar operation in Plymouth, Minn., which is
being kept. It produces integrated circuits exclusively for the
company's internal use.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
