<FIRST>r f AM-Mexico-Companies     06-02 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Companies,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Continues Sale Of Mexico's State-Owned Companies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGIO CARRASCO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Mexican government has sold 773
state-owned companies to private investors since 1983 and plans to
continue selling non-strategic industries, the Treasury Department
says.
   The department said in a news release Thursday that the
so-called privatization process ``guarantees a maximum benefit for
the federal government.''
   It said since President Carlos Salinas de Gortari took office
Dec. 1, a total of 17 of companies were sold to private investors.
   Salinas announced earlier this week his administration's plan
for national development, which includes the continued sale of
state-owned companies, a fight against inflation, liberalizing
regulations on foreign investment in Mexico and a tough negotiating
posture with creditor banks to lower payments on the $107.4 billion
foreign debt.
   The Salinas government, which marked six months in office this
week, has brought inflation down to about 20 percent annually, from
last year's rate of 51.7 percent.
   Last month, the government opened the economy to foreign
investment by allowing foreign ownership in many sectors previously
restricted to Mexican ownership and increased the amount of foreign
ownership allowed in others.
   The measure was designed to attract greater investments from
abroad.
   The government is now engaged in difficult negotiations with
foreign banks to lower interest and principal on the debt.
   When the preceding administration of Miguel de la Madrid
initiated the sale of state-owned firms in 1983, the government
owned 1,155 companies.
   Business leaders in Mexico have often criticized government
control of the economy and bureaucratic interference with private
enterprise.
   As part of this divestment campaign, Salinas announced plans to
sell the government's inefficient ferry system that serves routes
to the mainland from the Baja California Sur peninsula.
   Salinas said the ferry company has drained the government of $82
million a year to make up for its losses.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
