<FIRST>r f BC-NorthropChief     06-02 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Northrop Chief,0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chairman's Option Package Sweetened in Same Year as Reprimand</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northrop Corp. directors boosted the value of
stock options held by Chairman Thomas Jones last year, the same
year they reprimanded him for his handling of payments in South
Korea, the company's proxy statement reveals.
   Jones holds options to buy 1.2 million shares of Northrop stock
under an incentive plan. Last year, the board cut the exercise
price _ the price at which he is entitled to buy the stock _ from
$45.88 a share to $29.88 a share.
   The stock was selling for about $25 a share on Friday. But if
Northrop stock climbed back above $45.88 _ the 1987 high was
$52.62{ _ the change in the exercise price would add $19.2 million
to the value of Jones' options.
   The same proxy statement said Jones had been reprimanded for his
``management style.''
   The statement didn't explain, but the reprimand is widely
believed to stem from the company's payment of $7.8 million to
Korean businessmen and companies in an unsuccessful attempt to sell
Northrop's F-20 fighter jet to that country from 1984 to 1986.
</TEXT>
