<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 2133EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   06-02 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0539</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market swept ahead to new post-crash
highs Friday, responding to employment statistics that raised hopes
for an easier Federal Reserve credit policy and lower interest
rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 27.20 to 2,517.83,
topping the 2,502.02 reading of May 22 that marked its previous
peak since the collapse in 1987.
   For the week the average posted a net gain of 23.06 points.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by more than 5 to 2 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
1,141 up, 438 down and 436 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 229.14 million
shares, against 223.16 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in
those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter
market, totaled 266.30 million shares.
   The Labor Department reported that nonfarm payroll employment
increased by 101,000 in May _ only about half of the amount
projected by economists at leading brokerage firms.
   Janet Norwood, commissioner of the Bureau of Labor Statistics,
described job growth as ``very slow.''
   Traders seized on the data as evidence that the Federal Reserve
might soon relax its credit policy, seeking to cushion the economy
against the risks of a recession.
   Interest rates dropped sharply in the credit markets. Prices of
long-term government bonds, which move in the opposite direction
from interest rates, rose more than $10 for each $1,000 in face
value, putting their yields in the neighborhood of 8.5 percent.
   Since late March those yields have fallen about 80 basis points,
or hundredths of a percentage point.
   Texaco led the active list, up } at 49} on turnover of more than
25 million shares. The stock fell 2\ points Thursday as financier
Carl Icahn unloaded his holdings of more than 42 million Texaco
shares.
   Brokers were busy Friday reselling that stock to other investors.
   USX, meanwhile, slipped back 1 to 36{ after taking a 2]-point
jump Thursday. News of the Texaco transaction prompted speculation
that Icahn might be preparing a deal for USX, in which he also has
long held a large stake.
   Amgen climbed 3} to 44} in the over-the-counter market. On
Thursday the Food and Drug Administration gave Amgen approval to
produce and sell a genetically engineered drug for treatment of
anemia in kidney patients.
   Sun Microsystems, another OTC issue, fell 1{ to 19\. The company
said it expects to report a significant decline in earnings for the
fiscal quarter ending June 30.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market increased $32.13 billion, or
1.01 percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
gained 1.86 to 181.49.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index rose 3.53 to 372.99, and
S&amp;P's 500-stock composite index was up 3.55 at 325.52.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
climbed 6.42 to 451.63. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index closed at 360.47, up 4.46.
</TEXT>
