<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     06-02 0632</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls Sharply, Gold Mostly Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BART ZIEGLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell sharply Friday as U.S.
unemployment data indicated a slowdown in U.S. economic growth,
interest rates fell on the bond market and a Midwest bank lowered
its prime rate.
   ``The dollar came off rather dramatically today,'' said Bob
Morrissey, a senior currency trader with the Bank of Boston's New
York office.
   The May jobless figure showed a modest 101,000 new jobs in U.S.
non-farm payrolls, half the level expected by many analysts and one
sign that inflationary pressures are subsiding.
   Southwest Bank of St. Louis lowered its prime rate from 11.5
percent to 11 percent, although other banks did not follow suit.
   In addition, a rally on the bond market that sent long-term
interest rates to a 15-month low weakened the dollar, dealers said.
   Dealers said the unemployment figures heightened market
expectations that the Federal Reserve Bank may soon ease its
monetary policy in an effort to reverse the dollar's recent surge.
   Lower interest rates hurt the value of the dollar by making
yields on dollar-denominated investments less attractive to global
investors.
   ``If you consider the balance of risk between the Fed
maintaining its monetary policy or easing, it's clear that after
this latest set of figures the balance has shifted in favor of an
early easing,'' said Christian Dunis, a senior official at Chemical
Bank in London.
   But the Fed, he added, likely would wait for the release of
further economic data before acting.
   Francoise Soares-Kemp, a vice president at Credit Suisse in New
York, said the currency market ``was about as volatile as we've
seen in years.''
   She and other traders cited a 2 percent increase in the value of
the German mark as a key indicator of the dollar's decline.
   Ms. Soares-Kemp said currency swings were exaggerated because
many major traders stayed out of the market.
   In addition, she said, the fall was a reaction to the dollar's
steep runup of recent weeks. ``It went too far too fast,'' she said.
   In London, the British pound rose against the dollar to $1.5900
from $1.5730 late Thursday. Later in New York, the pound rose
further to $1.6040 from $1.5776 late Thursday.
   In Tokyo, the dollar closed at 141.80 Japanese yen, down from
142.52 yen Thursday. Later, in London, the dollar was quoted at
141.75 yen. In New York, the dollar fell to 140.50 yen from 142.41
Thursday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Thursday's rates, included: 1.9420 German marks, down from 1.9820;
1.6690 Swiss francs, down from 1.7005; 1.2055 Canadian dollars, up
from 1.2053; 6.5970 French francs, down from 6.7240; and 1,411
Italian lire, down from 1,436.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday,
included 1.9785 West German marks, down from 1.9835; 1.6850 Swiss
francs, down from 1.7040; 6.6470 French francs, down from 6.7185;
2.2180 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2370; 1,428.50 Italian lire,
down from 1,442.50; 1.2063 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2068.
   In Hong Kong, gold rose to a closing bid of $362.60 an ounce
from $360.97 bid at Thursday's close.
   In London, gold slipped to $362.25 bid from $362.50 Thursday.
Gold edged higher in Zurich to a late bid price of $362 a troy
ounce from $361.88 bid late Thursday.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery rose to $368.60 a troy ounce from $364.10.
   Republic National Bank of New York said gold was bid at $366.75
an ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, up from $362.05 late Thursday.
   Silver fell in London to a late bid of $5.21 a troy ounce from
$5.22 bid late Thursday. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for
current delivery rose to $5.298 an ounce from $5.198 Thursday.
</TEXT>
