<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 1741EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-USX Bjt   06-02 0679</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-USX, Bjt,0702</SECOND>
<HEAD>New USX Boss Mum On Icahn</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If new USX Corp. Chairman Charles A. Corry
thought his predecessor's troubles with takeover speculator Carl
Icahn were history, he got a jarring reminder less than 48 hours
after taking charge of the steel and energy giant.
   Icahn's sale of a record $2 billion block of Texaco Corp. stock
on Thursday immediately raised speculation that he might turn his
attention to USX, which he unsuccessfully pursued in 1987.
   Corry, who succeeded retiring Chairman David M. Roderick on
Wednesday, declined comment at a news conference Friday on the
possible impact of Icahn's stock sale.
   USX, which shot higher late Thursday after news of Icahn's
Texaco stock sale, finished down $1 at $36.50 a share Friday on the
New York Stock Exchange.
   But Wall Street analysts gave various reasons why they did not
believe a takeover bid was likely any time soon.
   Charles Bradford, of Merrill Lynch Capital Markets, cited $5.1
billion in long-term debt that could become due immediately upon a
change on control of USX. That would increase the cost of a
takeover beyond the $9.4 billion market value of its stock.
   ``I really doubt that's as big a poison pill as some people
think,'' said Bruce Lazier of Prescott, Ball &amp; Turben. ``If it's a
viable economic deal, the financing will be had.''
   Bradford also cited $2 billion in tax credits that the USX steel
division could forfeit if ownership changes.
   ``Icahn certainly is aware of those things and doesn't want to
lose them either. But there is a lot of other restructuring that
could be done,'' Lazier said.
   For example, USX could sell its Texas Oil &amp; Gas Corp. for $2.5
billion that could be used to repurchase stock, Bradford said. USX
also could appease any dissident shareholder by raising its
dividends and speeding the sale of its diversified businesses.
   Icahn has advocated selling the steel division and concentrating
on oil and natural gas production. Roderick has said USX may be
willing to sell the steel unit, the nation's largest steelmaker,
but has received no offers that it considers worthy.
   Icahn acquired some 29 million shares of USX, or around 11
percent of the outstanding common stock, beginning in 1986. Late
that year he proposed a takeover at $31 per share, but USX rejected
the proposal and threw roadblocks in his way, and he withdrew the
proposal in early 1987.
   Since then, Icahn has been a highly interested but satisfied
shareholder, according to Roderick's account of their frequent
discussions over lunch and dinner.
   The sale of Icahn's 42 million Texaco shares came one day after
Roderick, 65, retired and was succeeded as chairman by Corry.
   Any corporate raider might have to pay off USX's long-term debt
under the terms of the company's lending agreements. According to
the USX annual report, lenders could declare $5.1 billion in
long-term debt due immediately upon a change in control of the
company.
   Among the $5.1 billion is $738 million in revenue from the Yates
oil field of Marathon Oil Co. that is pledged as payment on
borrowings.
   The steelmaking USS Division also enjoys about $2 billion in tax
credits that could be forfeited if the parent USX sells off more
than 20 percent of the steel division or if more than half the
company's stock changes hands, Bradford said.
   Also, said Bradford, ``Keep in mind, USX has a staggered board
of directors. If you were to make a tender offer today and you got
it all you'd get only a third of the board seats next year.''
   The sale of Icahn's Texico stock the day after Roderick left
office may have been only a coincidence. Roderick has denied
speculation that he had an agreement with Icahn to delay takeover
activity until after his retirement.
   Roderick's reputation lends credence to the speculation,
Bradford said.
   ``Let's face it, Roderick's personality was that of a fighter.
He was a Marine Corps sergeant and a semi-pro boxer,'' he said.
``Corry's background is that of a lawyer.''
</TEXT>
