<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     06-02 0667</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precious Metals Prices Surge On Weaker Dollar, Jobless Report</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Gold and silver futures prices surged in late trading Friday,
reacting to a weaker dollar, a stronger oil market and expectations
for a drop in interest rates.
   On other markets, grain and soybean futures finished mixed, as
did livestock and meat futures.
   Gold settled $4.50 to $4.60 higher on New York's Commodity
Exchange with the most active contract, for delivery in August, at
$371.90 a troy ounce; silver was 8.8 cents to 10 cents higher with
July at $5.338 a troy ounce.
   The gains more than offset Wednesday's steep decline and
appeared to leave the gold market positioned for a further advance.
   The weakening of the dollar's value against the Japanese yen and
West German mark was the primary factor in the rally, prompting
investors to shift assets from dollars to gold.
   But the late surge in oil prices, a potentially inflationary
development, appeared to fuel some new investment buying of
precious metals, especially after the spot gold price rose above
technical resistance at about $365 an ounce. Spot gold settled at
$368.60.
   ``There are some ideas here that a short-term bottom has been
carved out,'' said Bernard Savaiko, a metal-market analyst in New
York with PaineWebber Inc. ``The market was very oversold and
looking for a technical bounce.''
   Expectations for a drop in interest rates were fanned by
Friday's national unemployment report, which showed job growth at
its lowest level in more than three years.
   Some observers say the slowdown in job creation could prompt the
Federal Reserve to ease up on interest rates in an attempt to
stimulate the economy, which could increase the threat of higher
inflation and spur more buying of gold as an inflation hedge.
   The late rally in oil prices on the New York Mercantile Exchange
was largely due to nervousness about the OPEC strategy meeting in
Vienna, Austria, analysts said.
   Little news came out of Friday's opening OPEC sessions, but many
of the traders who had sold the market earlier in the week were
reluctant to hold risky positions going into the weekend and turned
buyers late in the day.
   ``I would say a vacuum, a reluctance to sell, brought about
aggressive, nervous short-covering,'' said Jerry Samuels, an
analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 33 cents to 69 cents
higher with July at $20.14 a barrel; heating oil was 1.69 cents to
1.95 cents higher with July at 50.04 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .35 cent to 1.51 cents higher with July at 64.85 cents
a gallon.
   Corn and wheat futures prices rose slightly on the Chicago Board
of Trade amid rumors of Soviet purchases of U.S. grain.
   The Agriculture Department announced after the close that China
had purchased 200,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat and that more than
100,000 metric tons of U.S. corn had been sold to ``unknown
destinations,'' which usually means the Soviet Union.
   Soybeans ended lower on a continued easing of Midwestern drought
fears.
   Wheat settled unchanged to 3\ cents higher with July at $3.91\ a
bushel; corn was 1\ cents to 2\ cents higher with July at $2.62\ a
bushel; oats were 2{ cents to 3\ cents lower with July at $1.68\ a
bushel; soybeans were unchanged to 6 cents lower with July at
$7.06{ a bushel.
   On the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, live cattle were broadly
mixed and feeder cattle were lower, partly reflecting slack demand
on the cash markets. Pork futures were mostly lower in light,
featureless trading.
   Live cattle settled .70 cent lower to .35 cent higher with June
at 68.35 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .33 cent to .45 cent
lower with August at 77.62 cents a pound; live hogs were .32 cent
lower to .05 cent higher with June at 48.32 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were .12 cent to .30 cent lower with July at 30.30
cents a pound.
</TEXT>
