<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 1757EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Icahn Bjt   06-02 0721</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Icahn, Bjt,0742</SECOND>
<HEAD>Icahn: Raider or Manager?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There was a time when Carl Icahn's opponents
could easily pin the label ``corporate raider'' on the takeover
strategist. But four years after Icahn bought and began running
Trans World Airlines, his image has become less clear-cut.
   Icahn has pursued a string of companies over the years,
including Phillips Petroleum Co., Chesebrough-Pond's Inc. and B.F.
Goodrich Co. His bids were largely unsuccessful, but Icahn reaped
millions of dollars in profits and became known as a raider in the
process.
   Now there is speculation his next target will be USX Corp., the
oil and steel giant in which Icahn holds a large stake and
unsuccessfully targeted for takeover in 1987. Icahn's sale of a
record $2 billion block of Texaco Corp. stock on Thursday raised
speculation that he might turn his attention to USX.
   Icahn's tactics took a different turn after he defeated Texas
Air Corp. in the fight for TWA in September 1985.
   TWA management was convinced Icahn would dismantle the airline
and sell it off in pieces for a profit. Instead, he has taken steps
to build up the carrier and improve its financial health after
years of losses.
   In February 1986, Icahn announced the airline was buying Ozark
Air Lines, a smaller regional carrier. At the time, he said the
purchase would give TWA facilities and aircraft it needed but could
not have acquired any other way.
   In an attempt to further boost TWA's size and flagging finances
he bid $1.65 billion for USAir Group Inc. in early 1987, but his
target fought him off by acquiring Piedmont Aviation Inc.
   Icahn also has considered buying Eastern Airlines, last fall and
again after Eastern went into bankruptcy court reorganization in
March.
   Icahn also is building TWA from within, announcing earlier this
year the airline was expanding and updating its fleet with
brand-new Airbus Industrie planes.
   Icahn proved a tough manager at TWA, negotiating wage
concessions with the airline's unions. When the Independent
Federation of Flight Attendants walked out in March 1986 in a
dispute over Icahn's demands for givebacks, he began replacing
strikers and they were forced to call off the walkout nine weeks
after it started.
   But his management of TWA has not meant a completely new Icahn.
   In 1986, during the flight attendants' strike, Icahn planned a
hostile attempt to buy Viacom International Inc. He ended up
selling his 17 percent stake in Viacom back to the firm in exchange
for potentially lucrative stock purchase rights.
   Wall Street analysts said Icahn likely wanted to benefit from
the entertainment company's expansion plans, but couldn't juggle a
takeover bid and his TWA problems at the same time.
   By selling his stock back to Viacom, Icahn repeated transactions
he had made many times in the past, when companies repurchased his
stock at a premium price to remove the threat of a takeover. The
practice, known as ``greenmail'' on Wall Street, branded Icahn as a
raider years ago.
   The Texaco stock sale _ the most expensive block trade ever on
the New York Stock Exchange _ gave Icahn $2.07 billion and raised
questions about what he might do with the money.
   Icahn became Texaco's biggest shareholder in late 1987, and
immediately began fighting with management, charging it was not
doing enough to raise the company's stock price.
   He proposed a takeover of Texaco valued at $14.5 billion and
tried unsuccessfully to unseat the company's board in a proxy
fight. Icahn said that if he won control of Texaco, the oil giant's
assets would be sold and the proceed would go to Texaco
shareholders.
   However, after the company undertook a major restructuring that
included the sale of billions of dollars in assets and payment of
an $8 a share special dividend to stockholders, Icahn reached a
standstill pact in which he agreed not to attempt a Texaco takeover
for seven years.
   Icahn already has a major stake in USX. He made a $7.2 billion
bid for the company in early 1987, but gave up after the USX board
rejected it. When he made his bid, there were again charges he only
wanted to drive up the stock price and profit from it, but he did
not sell his shares when he abandoned the offer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
