<DOCNO> AP890602-0273 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 1800EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     06-02 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Rise</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ``Subroto,'' 11th graf, is cq as one name.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices rose Friday, led by a jump
in heating oil and gasoline prices.
   Analysts said the sharp rise in prices took them by surprise,
given the bearish undertone in the market in recent days as
investors nervously awaited OPEC's mid-year meeting.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the July contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark crude oil grade, ended 33 cents
higher at $20.14 a barrel. The August contract rose 41 cents and
other months were even higher.
   Among refined products, the July heating oil contract rose 1.95
cents to 50.04 cents a gallon and the unleaded gasoline contract
for July delivery jumped 1.51 cents to 64.85 cents a gallon. Other
contract months also gained.
   ``There was no news and no cash reason why the market behaved
like this,'' said James R. Fiedler, vice president in charge of
energy brokering for E.D.&amp;F. Man International Futures Inc. ``It
was most likely the rumor of a rumor story.''
   OPEC ministers are scheduled to open talks on Monday in Vienna
focusing on the cartel's production ceiling for the second half of
the year.
   Market observers said there was little news from Vienna, where
OPEC's eight-member monitoring committee met briefly and then
adjourned. The rally, they said, coincided with the end of the
meeting, which was intended to lay the groundwork for Monday's full
ministerial meeting.
   ``The question is why would it be so bullish,'' said Nauman
Barakat, vice president of energy investments at Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc. ``The fact that the meeting adjourned without any
contention and vitriolic statements by the Kuwaitis and the Saudis
indicates they want to find a compromise.''
   OPEC is expected to raise its output ceiling by at least 1
million barrels a day over the current 18.5 million barrels to
stabilize prices at around current levels.
   But Kuwait's insistence on a higher quota has pitted it against
its Persian Gulf neighbor, Saudi Arabia, the largest OPEC producer.
   Barakat said that speculation that OPEC General Secretary
Subroto had arrived at a formula for resolving the differences
between the Saudis and Kuwaitis helped lift prices.
   Other analysts attributed the gains to technical factors, led
primarily by a strong rise in heating oil.
   ``Heating oil had been oversold so it had more potential to
rally,'' said Jim Steel, an analyst with Refco Inc. ``It led crude
oil and coming up to the weekend, I'm not surprised to see
short-covering.''
</TEXT>
