<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 1815EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CNW     06-02 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-CNW,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>CN&amp;W Employees Make Offer For Parent Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Employees of the Chicago &amp; North Western
announced they have submitted an offer to buy the system's parent
CNW Corp., adding a new twist to the company's fight against a
hostile takeover bid by a New York investor group.
   The Association of General Chairman, a group comprising the
leadership of the railroad's 16 unions and 6,500 members, issued a
statement saying terms of the proposal would not be revealed.
   Ed Wytkind, a spokesman for the group, said the proposal was
submitted to a committee of independent CNW board members by
Friday's 5 p.m. deadline for offers. He said the proposal calls for
employees ultimately to hold a one-third share in the recapitalized
company, with shareholders retaining the remaining two-thirds.
   ``We will not discuss the bidders or the bids received,'' CNW
spokesman James Foote said.
   Japonica Partners has offered $44 a share for outstanding CNW
stock. The New York-based investment group already owns 8.8 percent
of CNW's shares.
   CNW rose 75 cents to $46.50 a share Friday on the New York Stock
Exchange.
   Soon after Japonica launched its tender offer, CNW urged
shareholders not to sell their stock while the company searched for
other potential buyers.
   In its statement, the CNW employee group said it was undertaking
a buyout to keep CNW intact and avoid ``splintering'' of the
company's rail system, which covers 6,000 miles in nine states.
   ``We will not stand by and allow this railroad to fall victim to
the often devastating effects of leveraged buyouts,'' said Ellis
Johnson, president of the union association. ``The best way to
avoid such a fate is to take the matter into our own hands.''
   In a leveraged buyout, a company is acquired mainly with
borrowed funds that are repaid with money from the target's cash
flow or raised by the sale of its assets.
   CNW defeated Japonica's attempt to elect its own slate of
directors at the annual shareholders' meeting last month.
</TEXT>
