<FIRST>u f AM-Bonds 1stLd-Writethru   06-02 0745</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bonds, 1st Ld-Writethru,0771</SECOND>
<HEAD>Interest Rates Plunge In Bond-Buying Spree</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates thruout with late figures.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Long-term interest rates plunged to their lowest
levels in 15 months Friday as investors snapped up bonds in flurry
of anticipation that the Federal Reserve might ease credit
following a weak U.S. employment report.
   ``It was a spree, a jamboree, a jubilee,'' said Robert Brusca,
chief economist at Nikko Securities Co. International Inc.
   Trading started with a bang after the Labor Department reported
the nation's unemployment rate dipped to 5.2 percent in May from
April's 5.3 percent.
   Although lower unemployment can indicate stronger economic
growth _ which tends to boost interest rates _ the market
concentrated on factors in the report that underscored the view
that the economy is slowing. For example, the report indicated May
had the weakest month-to-month job growth since March 1986.
   The report sent bond prices sharply higher and the gains held
throughout the session.
   The Treasury's bellwether 30-year bond soared 1~ points, or
nearly $18.75 per $1,000 in face amount. Its yield, which moves in
the opposite direction, plunged from Thursday's 8.60 percent to
8.43 percent, its lowest since March 3, 1988.
   ``The report accentuated rumors all week that the Fed is going
to ease'' interest rates, said Robert Chandross, vice president and
chief economist for Lloyds Bank PLC's North America head office in
New York.
   ``The question is whether the market is expecting more than it's
going to get,'' he said.
   Indications that the economy was slowing, and thus dampening
inflation, have raised speculation the Federal Reserve might push
interest rates lower to help curb the recent rise of the dollar.
   Chandross suggested the Fed may allow the federal funds rate _
the interest on overnight loans between banks _ to trade lower. The
Fed influences the fed funds rate _ and thus other short-term
interest rates _ by adding money to the banking system or draining
it out.
   The federal funds rate traded at 9 9-16 percent late in the
session, down from 9 13-16 percent late Thursday.
   A lower federal funds rate could entice major banks to lower
their prime interest rates, a benchmark used to set interest in a
variety of consumer and corporate credit. Early Friday, Southwest
Bank of St. Louis lowered its prime rate from 11.5 percent to 11
percent, but major banks did not follow suit.
   ``If we do get some prime rate cuts by the large money center
banks, it tells the Fed that demand for money has weakened a
little, and (the Fed) will seriously consider cutting the discount
rate,'' said Jack Barbanel, senior vice president at Gruntal &amp; Co.
   While some experts speculated a widespread prime rate cut could
come as early as next week, they said they did not believe the Fed
would ease credit by cutting its discount rate, the interest it
charges on loans to banks, as quickly.
   In the secondary market for Treasury securities, prices of
short-term governments rose 23-32 point to 1[ points, intermediate
maturities jumped 1\ points to 1| points, and 20-year issues were
up a full point, according to Telerate Inc., the financial
information service.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, rose 10.93 to 1,165.03.
   In corporate trading, industrials moved higher. Moody's
Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures total return
on a portfolio of 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years
or longer, rose 2.90 to 317.63.
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds rose 13-32 point. The average yield to
maturity fell to 7.39 percent from 7.43 percent late Thursday.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills slipped to 8.62 percent as
the discount fell 23 basis points to 8.35 percent. Yields on
six-month bills fell to 8.56 percent as the discount fell 26 basis
points to 8.12 percent. Yields on one-year bills fell to 8.55
percent as the discount fell 22 basis points to 7.93 percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, which is paid at maturity.
</TEXT>
