<FIRST>u f AM-DroughtAid     06-02 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drought Aid,0672</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yeutter Authorizes Limited Haying and Grazing of Idled Acres</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN P. ROSENFELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The secretary of agriculture Friday
authorized additional limited relief for livestock producers with
parched pastures, and an Iowa cattlemen's group said that it was
pleased even if there were more strings attached than it desired.
   While the decision applies to 16 states with stunted pastures
and meager feed supplies, the U.S. Department of Agriculture said
the relief is needed most in Iowa, Kansas and Nebraska.
   The action to allow haying and grazing on lands idled under a
federal program designed to conserve highly erodable acres was
announced in Washington by Secretary Clayton Yeutter three days
after a tour of drought-stricken regions of southern Iowa.
   ``Livestock producers have exhausted stocks of hay that were
carried into winter, and they are now faced with another dry
spring. So they're out of hay and short of grass,'' Yeutter said.
   Iowa farmers with dwindling ponds, dried up wells and skimpy
pastures had urged Yeutter on Tuesday to open up land taken out of
production under the federal Conservation Reserve Program. In that
program, the government makes an annual payment to farmers who
agree to remove erodable land from production for at least 10 years.
   As of last year, 28 million acres nationwide had been placed
into the conservation reserve program and the government pays an
estimated $1.4 billion a year to participants.
   The USDA earlier had authorized livestock grazing and hay
cutting on land taken out of production under this year's commodity
programs.
   The 16 qualifying states are: California, Colorado, Florida,
Illinois, Iowa, Kansas, Minnesota, Missouri, Nebraska, New Mexico,
New York, North Dakota, Oklahoma, South Dakota, Texas and Wisconsin.
   The emergency haying and grazing rights will be granted on a
county-by-county basis.
   County offices of the Agricultural Stabilization and
Conservation Service will submit applications to their state office
for designation as a livestock emergency and recommendations will
be made to Washington.
   Richard Vohs, an aide to Gov. Terry Branstad, said it should not
take counties long to apply for the relief.
   During last year's drought, farmers and ranchers also were
allowed to harvest hay or graze livestock on Conservation Reserve
Program acres.
   Unlike the 1988 program, however, owners will not be allowed to
donate their conservation land for use by other livestock producers.
   Other USDA restrictions on use of the conservation acres are:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
    _At least 25 percent of a field be left undisturbed for wildlife
cover.
   _No haying or grazing will be allowed on fields seeded after
July 1, 1987.
   _Participants will lose 50 percent of their government
conservation reserve payments in the next contract year.
   _Only one cutting of hay will be permitted and no hay may be
harvested after July 15. Farmers must leave at least three inches
of stubble on harvested fields.
   _Grazing will only be allowed after an inspection of the field
and will not be allowed after Aug. 1.
   _Any reseeding must be paid for by the owner and the government
will not reimburse farmers for fences or watering facilities
erected on conservation acres used for livestock.
   _Vegetative cover specifications in the conservation program
contract won't be waived because of drought.
   _Compliance spot checks will be expanded for the conservation
program.
   Maynard Jayne, field manager Iowa Cattlemen's Association in
Ames, said while restrictions were more severe than his group had
recommended, ``we are quite pleased the secretary has made the
decision.''
   One sore point with the group was the decision to prohibit
donation of haying and grazing rights.
   ``Many cattlemen do not have Conservation Reserve Program''
acreage, he said, and will be denied the extra source of forage for
their livestock.
   He also said the 50 percent reduction in rental payments is
twice the level of last year, a level the Iowa cattlemen's group
had recommended be continued.
</TEXT>
