<HEAD>Completes Sale of Star-News</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Knight-Ridder Inc. has completed its sale of the
Star-News in Pasadena, Calif., and its suburban newspapers for
approximately $55 million.
   Proceeds of the sale will be used to reduce Knight-Ridder's
debt, according to a statement released Thursday by Knight-Ridder.
   The Star-News was bought by Pasadena Newspapers Inc., owned by
William Dean Singleton of Houston. Singleton also serves as vice
chairman and chief executive officer of Media News Group.
   The Star-News has daily circulation of more than 38,000, and
Sunday circulation of about 43,000. Knight-Ridder purchased the
Star-News, which employs about 200 people, in 1956.
   The suburban papers included in the deal belong to the Foothill
Intercity Newspapers group. Member newspapers include the Arcadia
Tribune, the Duartean, the Monrovia News-Post and the Temple City
Times, twice-weeklies with a combined circulation of about 24,000.
</TEXT>
