<FIRST>u f AM-OPEC 1stLd-Writethru   06-02 0631</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-OPEC, 1st Ld - Writethru,0651</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Ministers Gather for Production, Price Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 9th graf pvs, The July...to UPDATE with closing WTI price.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OPEC ministers met briefly Friday before
breaking up for private bargaining over how to set new guidelines
for pricing and producing their oil.
   Twelve ministers of the 13-nation Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries met in a 90-minute session that preceded formal
strategy sessions set to begin Monday.
   The ministers declined to give details of their talks, which
were not attended by Qatar. OPEC President Rilwanu Lukman, the
Nigerian oil minister, would only say the officials discussed ``the
whole agenda.''
   Venezuela's oil chief, Celestino Armas, said the officials would
meet again Saturday and Sunday.
   The ministers are attempting to fashion a new accord that will
guide their pricing and output policies for the last six months of
the year.
   The cartel last November reached an accord governing production
for the first half of 1989. The agreement set an OPEC output
ceiling of 18.5 million barrels a day, sharply under actual
production levels of late last year, in an attempt to support a
target price $18 a barrel.
   Prices are now more than 40 percent higher than when the
agreement was made, partly due to accidents in oil producing areas
that have caused supply disruptions.
   The average price of a basket of seven crudes monitored by OPEC
has soared from $12.34 a barrel at the end of November to nearly
$17.70 this week, although it topped $18 earlier this year.
   The July contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
U.S. crude, closed up 33 cents at $20.14 a barrel Friday on the New
York Mercantile Exchange.
   Some officials predict the ministers may decide to extend their
current accord temporarily if they cannot reach a quick consensus.
   Some OPEC ministers have presented new ideas for an accord, but
most appear unwilling to want any changes that could upset what has
been a surprisingly strong market so far this year.
   Diego Tamariz, Ecuador's oil minister, said, ``The main
objective of the meeting is to have stability.''
   Evenness in the market, he said, ``will be brought by production
levels in accordance with demand.''
   The ministers must consider whether to maintain their production
ceiling at 18.5 million barrels a day, or boost it some to 19.5
million or 20 million barrels. Some analysts say OPEC already is
producing in excess of 20 million barrels a day.
   Affecting their decision will be estimates on demand for their
oil in the second half of the year.
   The International Energy Agency, in its Monthly Oil Market
Report, predicted demand for OPEC crude would rise to 20.4 million
barrels a day in the last six months of the year.
   If the producers agree to increase their output cap, they then
have the tricky task of dividing up the extra amount.
   Several nations, including Kuwait and the United Arab Emirates,
are pressing to enlarge their quotas. Ecuador and Gabon also would
like more, officials say.
   Analysts say the Saudi Arabian delegation has suggested lifting
the overall ceiling by 1 million barrels a day and giving some of
the extra to those four nations.
   The ministers also must decide whether to maintain the $18 a
barrel target price, which has been in effect since January 1987.
   Saudi Arabian Oil Minister Hisham Nazer said on his arrival in
Vienna that he would suggest eliminating the reference price, but
has declined to elaborate on the plan. Nazer has said previously
that an option would be to eliminate the benchmark price in favor
of strict adherence to production quotas.
   OPEC members are Algeria, Ecuador, Gabon, Indonesia, Iran, Iraq,
Kuwait, Libya, Nigeria, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, the United Arab
Emirates and Venezuela.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
