<FIRST>r f BC-CDScam     06-02 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-CD Scam,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-President of Failed Bank Gets 5 Years for Selling Fake CDs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former president of the failed Golden
Pacific National Bank was sentenced to five years in prison
Thursday for defrauding bank customers of $15 million through phony
certificates of deposit.
   Kuang Hsung J. Chuang, 48, of Staten Island was convicted Jan.
18 on 22 counts of making false statements to the Federal Reserve,
misapplying bank funds and defrauding bank customers.
   According to evidence at trial, Chuang, who was also chairman of
the board, and the New York bank's former vice president and
cashier, Theresa Shieh, 37, of Queens, sold tens of millions of
dollars in bogus certificates of deposit, called ``yellow
certificates,'' between 1980 and 1985.
   Sales of the yellow certificates, so named because they were
printed on yellow paper, were kept off the bank's books and hidden
from federal regulators.
   The certificates were not federally insured and were used to
generate a multimillion dollar slush fund under Chaung and Ms.
Shieh's control, unlike genuine certificates of deposit.
   On June 21, 1985, the federal comptroller of the currency
declared Golden Pacific insolvent and placed it in receivership
under the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.
   About $15 million in yellow certificate funds were due customers
at the time. After a court battle, the FDIC has been treating the
yellow certificates as insured deposits and has been reimbursing
customers.
   U.S. District Judge Miriam Goldman Cedarbaum is scheduled to
sentence Ms. Shieh, who also was convicted, on June 12.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890602-0284 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 0154EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-SunForecast 1stLd-Writethru f0301 06-02 0569</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Sun Forecast, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0301,0584</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sun Microsystems Expects Significantly Lower Earnings</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with quotes from Sun president, analyst.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sun Microsystems Inc., completing
an expensive ``bone-by-bone transplant of the skeleton of the
company'' and plagued by supply problems, Thursday forecast
significantly lower earnings or possibly a loss in its fourth
quarter ending June 30.
   A loss would be its first since it reported red ink in its
initial quarter in 1982.
   Although Sun, a leader in workstation computers, issued its new
forecast at the close of the stock market, its share price tumbled
$1.25 to $20.75 in trading on the NASDAQ over-the-counter market.
   Revenues in the fourth quarter could fall below the $497 million
of the third quarter ended March 30, the company said. That would
put the company's fiscal 1989 revenues at about $1.8 billion, up
from $1.2 billion last year.
   ``The conversion to a new management information system in April
was not without difficulties,'' the company said. ``This slowed
production early in the quarter. In addition, the introduction in
this quarter of five major new products has made it more difficult
to forecast product mix.''
   Sun said production of the new products has been ``somewhat
impaired by an insufficient supply of certain components.''
   Scott McNealy, Sun's president, declined to specify which
components were in short supply but said, ``We expect those
component shortages to not be an issue by mid-July.''
   He also declined to say which of the company's new products were
affected most by the supply shortage or to give details of how well
the products were selling. But he said the SPARCstation1, Sun's
low-cost entry into the workstation market with a starting price of
about $9,000, was ``clearly the lead product'' among the new
entries.
   McNealy said the company could be ``faulted for not being more
precise on our forecasting,'' but he said it was difficult to
predict what customers would order and how much the change in
management information systems would affect sales.
   ``Basically, we had to do a bone-by-bone transplant of the
skeleton of the company,'' he said, referring to the replacement of
a management information computer system that had been in place
since its early days with a new system.
   Delays have also resulted from continued strong sales of Sun's
traditional products, causing unexpected production demands, the
company said.
   ``These factors have hindered Sun's ability to assess accurately
the company's incoming orders, to forecast and to schedule
production efficiently,'' the company said.
   Sun said the problems will be confined to the fourth quarter and
the company is not encouraging changes in expectations for fiscal
1990, which the company said will be ``an excellent year.''
   Kathleen Hurley, an analyst at the San Jose-base research firm
Dataquest Inc., said she was not surprised by the company's
announcement in light of the ambitious product introductions made
this year.
   ``When they announced the SPARCstation I, that's a significant
revamping,'' she said. ``That affected their net income. It takes a
lot of time and money to do that.''
   She called the cost of introducing the new products and the
multimillion-dollar change of the management information system ``a
natural migration. I don't think they messed up.''
   ``I think they'll recover by the end of the first quarter (of
fiscal 1990) or the start of the second quarter,'' she said. ``The
workstation market as a whole is doing well.''
